<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Media     03-02 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Media,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Considering Closing Territories To Journalists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSUALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government leaders concerned about Israel's
battered image abroad are arguing increasingly in favor of barring
journalists from the occupied territories after nearly three months
of violent protests there.
   Most of Israel's 24 Cabinet ministers support closing the West
Bank and Gaza Strip to journalists as long as the unrest persists,
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said after attending a Cabinet
session where the issue was raised this week.
   Closing areas to reporters ``is done in various countries around
the world where confrontations of this sort take place,'' said
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
   ``If it becomes clear that indeed it may limit the damage, I
would be willing to consider it,'' he said.
   The executive committee of Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc voted
unanimously Monday evening that journalists should be banned from
entering the territories.
   West Bank army commander Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna reissued
instructions to field commanders to close areas to reporters for
several hours if they believe it is necessary to keep or restore
calm, army officials told The Associated Press on condition of
anonymity.
   But Shamir's government partner, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres
of the centrist Labor Party, warned against further restrictions.
   ``If we were to close off the area, in my opinion, rumors of
atrocities would be spread around the world that we would not be
able to refute,'' Peres said.
   ``Israel is an open society and a free society and even if
(journalists) are not always pleasant, we have to allow them to
fulfill their jobs,'' he told reporters Tuesday.
   Other officials oppose closing the territories on the grounds
that such a move might fuel comparisons between Israel and South
Africa, an issue about which Israel has been particularily
sensitive.
   South African police, like Israeli army officers, have the
discretion to declare an area closed to media on the spot because
of unrest. Journalists then are barred from entry and must leave if
already there.
   Cable News Network's bureau chief Robert Wiener said Israeli
soldiers seized videotape last week from a crew which photographed
a Palestinian hanging dead from a pole in the village of Qabatiyeh
after his neighbors lynched him because he was suspected of
collaborating with the Israelis.
   The army was criticized afterward for failing to rescue the
Palestinian. Wiener said the soldiers detained the CNN crew for
three hours and refused to return the videotape, saying it
contained material damaging to Israel's security.
   The Israeli military command said Tuesday that ``our policy is
to keep the administered territories open to journalists. However
there are exceptions to the rule in isolated incidents where
certain troublesome areas can be closed.''
   The latest debate over media access was triggered by a CBS News
report last week that showed four Israeli soldiers beating two
captive Palestinians.
   The two were beaten for more than half an hour while a CBS
cameraman photographed it surreptitiously. After the footage was
broadcast, embassies in the United States and Europe received many
complaints and Jewish communities abroad also expressed concern,
Foreign Ministry officials said.
   The four soldiers are being investigated, the army said. The CBS
office in Tel Aviv has received anonymous threatening telephone
calls, said CBS bureau chief Terry Plantinga.
   ``One more incident like the CBS film and the territories will
be closed to journalists,'' a government official told The AP on
condition of anonymity.
   Rabin met Monday with a delegation from the Foreign Press
Association and said most Cabinet ministers supported blocking
journalists from entering the territories but he did not, according
to FPA chairman Robert Slater.
   ``The voices in favor of closing the territories have become
much louder than the others,'' Slater said. ``It appears more
likely than ever before that such a step will be taken and the FPA
is increasingly worried.''
   Two Israeli newspapers, the left-wing Al Hamishmar and the
independent Maariv, ran editorials Tuesday criticizing discussions
in government circles about closing the territories to journalists.
   ``Without media in the territories we may live in a warm
comfortable bubble next to an erupting volcano,'' Al Hamishmar
said. ``But we will be caught by surprise and off guard when the
lava overflows and threatens our very existence.''
</TEXT>
