<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MissUSA 4th-Writethru a0406 03-02 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss USA, 4th - Writethru, a0406,0817</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miss Texas, Again, Wins Miss USA Crown</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from winner,
previous Texas winners, other detail. Picks up at dash.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Courtney Gibbs became the fourth Texan in
a row to win the Miss USA crown Tuesday, besting Miss California in
the nationally televised pageant.
   ``It feels fabulous,'' Ms. Gibbs, 21, said moments after being
crowned by her predecessor and fellow Texan, Michelle Royer. ``One
of the gifts Michelle gave me was a dictionary with the word
`impossible' whited out. So of course it was possible.''
   Ms. Gibbs, of Fort Worth, won the right to compete in the Miss
Universe pageant May 23 in Taiwan. Ms. Royer, of Keller, came in
third in last year's worldwide competition, which was won by Miss
Chile.
   The blue-eyed brunette, a junior in advertising and public
relations at Texas Christian University, won over Diana Magana, 22,
of Rancho Palos Verdes, Calif., the first runner-up.
   Miss USA spokeswoman Stacy Sacco said she was stunned by the
fourth Miss Texas victory in a row. ``What are the odds?'' she said.
   Second runner-up was Miss Georgia, Donna Rampy, 24, followed by
Miss Florida, Monica Bruni Farrell, 23, and Miss Mississippi, Dana
Michele Richmond, 20.
   Soon after the beaming new Miss USA ascended her throne, the
last three title holders posed with her for photographers.
   Ms. Royer's predecessor, Christie Fichtner of Dallas, called the
last four winners ``four aces in a deck of cards.''
   The woman who started the string, Laura Martinez-Herring of El
Paso, said: ``It's always been known Texas is full of beautiful
women, and this just proves it. I just feel sorry for the next Miss
Texas.''
   Actress Tracy Scoggins and actor Alan Thicke served as co-hosts
for the program, televised by CBS. Ten semifinalists, who had been
chosen last week, were announced as the pageant opened Tuesday
night.
   The pageant capped three bizarre weeks in which two contestants
quit because of police records, animal-rights activists protested
the awarding of fur coats and the co-host, Miss Scoggins, was
attacked in a hotel elevator.
   The hosts made no mention of the various problems during the
television show.
   The late departures of two contestants, both from Minnesota,
opened a spot for Julie Nelson, 20, of Minneapolis, but the
lateness meant she arrived about a week after the other contestants.
   ``Actually, I've found this oddball situation to be quite an
advantage,'' she said before the pageant opened. ``Having so short
a time to pull myself together, getting all my clothes together,
finding a fur coat, dropping everything _ when all the other girls
had months to prepare. It shows off my abilities.''
   Miss Nelson was not among the 10 semifinalists.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Besides a mink jacket and full-length coat worth a total of
$15,000, Miss USA wins a $25,000 personal appearance contract,
$46,000 cash, a sports car, $10,000 worth of jewelry and other
prizes, including a portable home tanning center.
   About 25 animal-rights activists picketed Tuesday outside the El
Paso Convention Center to protest the awarding of the furs to the
winner.
   Members of the El Paso and Las Cruces, N.M., chapters of Sangre
de Cristo Animal Rights contend fur ranching and trapping are cruel
to the animals.
   Bob Young, director of Sangre de Cristo's Las Cruces chapter,
had asked Thicke to do as longtime host Bob Barker had done
earlier: resign in protest over the awarding of the furs.
   Thicke refused, saying the furs were taken from ranch-raised
minks that had been treated humanely. He and Young released a joint
statement Monday saying they agreed that fur-trapping is cruel but
disagreed on fur-ranching.
   In another prepageant incident, a man accused of attempted
sexual assault in the attack on Miss Scoggins last week was
released on $100 bail. Prosecutors usually ask for $15,000 bail in
third-degree felonies like attempted sexual assaults.
   A man ripped Miss Scoggins' dress and shoved her into the back
of a hotel elevator, authorities said. She fought the man off and a
man was arrested at the hotel.
   The man's bail was later raised to $100,000, which he posted.
   Another person connected with the pageant has a date with the
law. Suzanne Pitman, Miss Kentucky-USA, is awaiting trial on
drunken-driving charges.
   Two other contestants with arrest records, both from Minnesota
and both accused of shoplifting, elected to bow out.
   The original Miss Minnesota-USA, Sue Bolich, resigned after it
was disclosed she'd been accused of shoplifting $370 worth of
clothing. Her replacement, first runner-up Jolene Stavrakis, quit
after disclosing she had pleaded no contest to stealing from a
store in March 1986.
   The first Miss USA pageant was in 1952 in Long Beach, Calif.
</TEXT>
