<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DemocraticDelegates Bjt   03-02 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democratic Delegates, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Democratic ``Super Delegates'' Not Yet Backing Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three-fourths of the Democratic Party leaders
who will be national convention delegates are not yet supporting
any of the presidential candidates as the initial round of
primaries and caucuses draws to a close, an Associated Press survey
found.
   Since late last year, the candidates together have attracted
support that will add up to fewer than three dozen votes at the
convention, according to the survey, in which hundreds of the
party's ``super delegates'' were contacted.
   And despite the months of debates and the weeks of primaries and
caucuses, many of the automatic delegates, who include Democratic
National Committee members, Democratic governors and others, are
not closing in on which candidate they plan to suppport.
   ``The more I hear, the more uncommitted I become,'' said Ruth
Moss, a Democratic National Committee member from Maine.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the winner of the New
Hampshire primary, leads the pack with commitments totaling just
31.5 votes at the convention. By comparison, the runaway favorite
so far is ``uncommitted,'' a category in which delegates with
247.65 votes at the convention place themselves, the AP survey
found.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt, winner of the Iowa caucuses, is
next behind Dukakis with commitments amounting to 21 votes at the
convention, followed by Jesse Jackson with 19.55, Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore with 16.55 and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon with 15.5.
   Only Gary Hart, who has acknowledged his chances of winning the
Democratic nomination are remote at best, has not received a
commitment from any of the delegates contacted by the AP.
   When added to delegates won by the candidates in the primaries
and caucuses so far, that brings the total to 63.5 for Dukakis, 47
for Gephardt, 35.5 for Simon, 27.55 for Jackson, 16.55 for Gore and
none for Hart. A total of 258.65 are counted as uncommitted.
   The survey, conducted during the last two weeks of February,
indicates that the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary,
along with nearly weekly debates, have made little impression on
Democratic Party leaders. The survey found that just 35.25 more
convention votes have been won by the candidates since a similar AP
survey late last year.
   ``I'm still not convinced that Iowa and New Hampshire are
representative of the cross section of the United States,'' said
New Mexico party chairman Sam Pick.
   ``Call over to the grammar school and talk to any first-grader _
he knows just as much as I do,'' said J.T. Rose, a DNC member from
Arkansas. ``It's up for grabs. I'm just sitting back enjoying it.''
   That's not what the Gephardt campaign had hoped to hear after
the victory in Iowa.
   ``I think we expected a bigger bounce,'' said Jude Barry, a
Gephardt campaign aide who works on delegate selection. ``We would
like people to commit sooner, but we're encouraged by what they're
telling us.''
   Rick Hutcheson, a Gore campaign aide involved in delegate
selection, said he is not surprised to see the super delegates
holding back.
   ``These are political people; they want to wait and see what the
voters in the primaries decide and then they will exercise their
judgment,'' he said.
   However, Barry said party leaders may feel some incentive to
begin committing themselves after next week's Super Tuesday
contests, when nearly one-third of the party's delegates are at
stake.
   ``At that point I think that people start looking at the
calendar,'' Barry said. ``People who come in after New York (which
holds an April 19 primary) are really going to be seen as coming
late to the party.''
   The Democratic Party allots 362 convention votes to members of
its national committee, some of whom will cast only fractions of
votes. An additional 25 votes are given to governors of states and
territories and five to former leaders, including former President
Carter and Walter Mondale, a former vice president who was the
party's nominee in 1984.
   Delegates representing 352.75 convention votes were contacted
for the AP survey in February.
   An additional 253 delegate slots will be awarded to Democratic
members of Congress in April.
   The Republican Party makes no such provision for automatic
delegates, awarding all the seats to its national convention
through the primaries and caucuses.
   In all, 4,162 delegates are to attend the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta July 18-21, and 2,082 are needed to win the
presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
