<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Baker-Fed     03-02 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baker-Fed,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Officials Praise Fed Monetary Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is trying to soften
earlier accusations that the Federal Reserve's tight monetary
policies are nudging the country toward a recession.
   In separate forums, a trio of Reagan administration officials
said Tuesday they believe the nation's central bank is doing a good
job of supplying money to the economy.
   Just a few weeks ago, administration officials worried about the
prospect of a recession during an election year had been
complaining that the Fed wasn't pumping enough new money into the
economy.
   On Tuesday, however, Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III told
the Senate Appropriations Committee that he has ``absolutely no
disagreement'' with the Fed's monetary policy.
   Speaking at the National Press Club, Budget Director James C.
Miller III said, ``There seems to be a little bit of easing, and I
welcome that.''
   And at a meeting of the National Association of Business
Economists, Beryl Sprinkel, President Reagan's chief economic
adviser, said the administration is ``supportive of present policy
as well as the plans for the future'' the Fed revealed last week.
   The suddenly conciliatory administration tone follows a sharp
counterattack by Fed chairman Alan Greenspan, who had responded to
the administration complaints with some pointed remarks of his own.
   Greenspan said that a looser monetary policy could spark higher
inflation. He also said pressure by the administration could push
the Fed into asserting its independence by doing the opposite of
what the White House wanted.
   The administration began pulling back from its criticisms last
week. Sprinkel said he supports the Fed's policies so far in 1988,
and Reagan said at his news conference last Wednesday that he had
confidence in Greenspan, whom he appointed to the Fed job last
summer.
   The central bank can usually increase the flow of credit by
easing interest rates.
   Baker told the senators Tuesday that when it comes to finding
the balance between keeping interest rates low and avoiding
inflation, ``I think the Fed is doing that and doing a very good
job of that.''
   In other testimony, Baker played down concerns raised by
senators about the growth of the national debt.
   Projections by the Congressional Budget Office, cited at the
hearing, are that the national debt could reach $4 trillion by
1993. The debt was below $1 trillion when Reagan took office in
1981.
   ``There are some risks in the growth of debt of this magnitude,
but I think they tend to be overstated,'' Baker said. ``I think to
some extent that's a consequence of the fact that we're moving into
1988, which happens to be an election year.''
   Baker also said, however, that ``an increase in the debt is not
a development about which this administration nor the Congress can
be very happy.''
</TEXT>
