<DOCNO> AP880302-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0544EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--GirlsClubSuit     03-02 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Girls Club Suit,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girls Clubs Sues to Protect Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Girls Clubs of America leader says the
organization's identity and fund-raising are threatened by a
competing group it is suing.
   The suit filed Monday in U.S. District Court asks for an
injunction to prevent the Boys Clubs of America from changing its
name to the Boys and Girls Clubs of America.
   ``The importance of this is the perception of the public as to
who they are and who we are,'' Margaret Gates, national executive
director of the Girls Clubs, said Tuesday.
   Thomas Garth, national director-elect of the Boys Clubs, said
that organization has about 300,000 girls among it 1.3 million
members, and their parents are demanding the name change.
   The Girls Clubs says it serves about 250,000 girls and that
about 40,000 boys participate in its activities. The organization
says about 80 percent of it $2.7 million operating budget comes
from contributions and grants that benefit its many members who
come from lower-income families.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
