<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Indonesia     03-02 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indonesia,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indonesia To Choose New President, Vice President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name for Suharto and Sudharmono is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GHAFUR FADYL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An assembly began an 11-day session
Tuesday to elect a new president and vice president.
   The session opened with a 35-page report by President Suharto on
the affairs of state since he was re-elected in 1983 for a fourth
five-year term.
   The 1,000-member assembly is expected to re-elect Suharto, a
66-year-old former general and the sole candidate for president.
   The People's Consultative Assembly, dominated by the president's
governing GOLKAR Party, is a special body summoned every five years.
   The post of vice president, though largely ceremonial, has been
the subject of intense speculation in recent weeks because it is
likely to be filled by a figure considered to be Suharto's chosen
successor.
   Two people have been viewed as possible candidates for the vice
presidency: State Secretary Sudharmono, 61, GOLKAR chairman, and
Try Sutrisno, 52, newly appointed armed forces commander, who has
served four years as a Suharto aide.
   In his report to the assembly, Suharto said his administration
in the last five years has had to overcome an economic recession
and a sharp drop in oil prices, a major source of foreign exchange
in Indonesia.
   Suharto also said Indonesia's economic growth rate was estimated
to reach an average of 3.8 percent annually in the current
five-year economic plan ending March 1989. The original target was
set at 5 percent.
   In foreign affairs, the president reaffirmed Indonesia's
position that it will not normalize relations with China until
Beijing pledges it will not provide support to communist guerrillas
in the region, including Indonesia.
   Jakarta suspended relations with Beijing in 1967 after accusing
it of complicity in the abortive communist coup attempt of 1965.
   However, trade relations between the two nations have been
restored since the signing of a memorandum of understanding in July
1985.
</TEXT>
