<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF-CitrusQuarantine     03-02 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Citrus Quarantine,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas To Seek Court Order Banning Florida Citrus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas will seek a court order to stop the
shipment of Florida citrus to Texas and other citrus-producing
states, officials say.
   The move was prompted by a judge's order Tuesday that overturned
a Texas ban on the Florida fruit.
   Texas imposed the ban last month after a federal rule took
effect allowing the shipment of Florida citrus that meets certain
standards to other citrus-producing states.
   The new rule lifted a 3{-year-old federal quarantine on Florida
citrus that was prompted by discovery of the citrus canker disease
in that state.
   U.S. District Judge James Nowlin said he overturned the ban
because the federal regulation takes precedence over the state rule.
   Texas agriculture officials said the ban was needed to protect
Texas' $65 million-a-year citrus industry from canker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
