<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson-Campaign     03-02 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson-Campaign,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Says Suspected Drug Flights Should Be Shot Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Pat
Robertson said he would use the military to help stem the flow of
illegal drugs into the United States and would order airplanes
suspected of carrying drugs to be shot down.
   ``If one of those drug planes is flying without giving
identification ... coming into this country, I wouldn't hesitate to
give orders to shoot him down,'' the former television evangelist
said at a rally Tuesday.
   ``I believe we have played games long enough with drugs,''
Robertson said. ``I don't think we are being as aggressive as we
should.''
   Robertson, who has tapped a vein of anti-communist sentiment
among Cuban-Americans as he campaigns around Florida, also accused
Cuban President Fidel Castro of involvement in drug trafficking.
   Earlier, Robertson cited 21-year-old, second-hand testimony
before a Senate subcommittee as evidence that the Soviet Union has
intermediate-range missiles based in Cuba.
   He called for closing what he calls a ``Cuban loophole'' in the
U.S.-Soviet Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, which now is
awaiting ratification by the Senate.
   ``If the INF treaty is ratified without addressing this matter
then I think it will be virtually treasonous,'' Robertson said at a
news conference. ``I do not feel there is any way that they can
sweep this thing under the rug. I am not going to permit them to do
it.''
   Several U.S. officials said Tuesday the Cuban military has some
surface-to-surface missiles in its inventory, but none has a
nuclear warhead and none could reach the United States even if it
did.
   Robertson quoted 1967 testimony by Paul Bethel, a State
Department official from Miami, who said Cuban refugees had told
him of seeing missiles, and one of the refugees, identified only as
Mr. Apud, who swore Cuban soldiers let him know about missiles
aimed at Washington before he left in 1966.
   Neither man testified he had personally seen the missiles, the
transcript indicates.
   The testimony was given to the Judiciary subcommittee to
investigate the administration of the Internal Security Act and
other internal security laws. Robertson read portions of it to
supporters Tuesday at a breakfast in Fort Lauderdale and during a
rally the night before in Miami.
   ``I've been accused of bringing funny facts,'' Robertson told
the Fort Lauderdale gathering. ``Ladies and gentlemen, the clear
eyewitness, sworn testimony of witnesses before a Senate Judiciary
committee is not funny facts. ... This is documented evidence.''
   Robertson's assertion that there are missiles based in Cuba has
been denied by the White House, congressional defense experts and
Castro, who told NBC on Monday that Robertson should ``go and see a
doctor, really, or a psychiatrist, because this is pure madness.''
   Several defense and administration officials were asked Tuesday
about Robertson's claim. The officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity because they did not want to become involved in the
presidential race, said Cuba has about five dozen Frog-4 and Frog-7
battlefield missiles, dating from the 1960s.
   The Frog-7, when originally introduced by the Soviets, could
carry either a conventional or nuclear warhead, ``but we're
confident no nuclear warheads ever went to Cuba for that missile
and it doesn't have any range anyway,'' said one source who
requested anonymity.
   According to the reference book ``Jane's Weapon Systems,'' the
Frog-7 has a range of only about 43 miles _ or half the distance
between Cuba and Florida. Moreover, the rocket has no guidance
system to direct it to a specific target.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said last month that Cuba
has been under extensive surveillance since the 1962 missile crisis
and there is ``no evidence'' any other nuclear weaponry had ever
been deployed there by the Soviet Union.
   In the subcommittee transcript, Apud said he was told by Cuban
soldiers he had known for many years that the missiles were
nicknamed ``Washington Left,'' ``Washington Right,'' and
``Washington Central.''
</TEXT>
