<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DamagedLand     03-02 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Damaged Land,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Says Bureau Of Land Management Lax In Protecting Streamsides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional study is painting a dismal
environmental picture of vital streamside areas on federal property
across the West.
   Tens of thousands of miles of these riparian areas have been
degraded by poor livestock grazing practices on land leased to
ranchers by the Bureau of Land Management, according to the General
Accounting Office, the investigative wing of Congress.
   James Duffus, a GAO official, says the damaged land would start
repairing itself if the bureau either would ban cattle from
degraded streamsides or limit the amount of grazing there.
   But that solution is being made difficult because bureau leaders
appear to be siding with opposition from many ranchers who pay
below-market rates to graze cattle on the taxpayers' land, he told
a House hearing Tuesday.
   Streamside areas are important in the arid West because they
help raise water tables, collect sediment, increase the
availability of forage, dissipate the energy of flood waters and
serve as fish and wildlife habitats, said Duffus, the GAO's
associate director for resources, community and economic
development.
   ``It has taken decades of abuse to produce the level of riparian
area degradation that currently exists,'' he told the Interior
national parks and public lands subcommittee. ``Most riparian areas
managed by the bureau are in degraded condition largely as a result
of poorly managed livestock grazing.''
   Duffus said that while the bureau does not know the extent of
the damage, ``tens of thousands of stream miles on federal
rangelands remain in degraded condition.''
   Duffus said two bureau assessments found that 80 percent of the
12,000 miles of streamside areas in Idaho need better management
and that 90 percent of 5,000 miles in Colorado were rated in poor
or fair condition.
   Not only has the bureau reduced its ranks of wildlife and
fisheries biologists since 1981, many remaining personnel
responsible for riparian areas don't believe the bureau is serious
about improving the condition of the streamside areas, according to
Duffus.
   ``These staff widely believe that if their proposed actions for
restoring riparian areas are opposed by the permitted ranchers,
their managers will not support them,'' he said.
   ``Many bureau staff ... recounted specific instances where their
riparian management efforts were specifically undercut by bureau
headquarters or local management direction after permitted ranches
raised objections,'' Duffus said.
   Subcommittee Chairman Bruce Vento, D-Minn., distributed copies
of a 1986 bureau headquarters memo telling field personnel that
streamside area management ``requires the full support and
cooperation of the permittee or lessee.''
   Pointing to the memo, Vento asked whether ranchers using bureau
land for cattle grazing are experts in environmental restoration.
   ``I wouldn't look to them for any expertise,'' Duffus replied.
   Tim Locke, a bureau spokesman, gave no immediate response when
asked by The Associated Press to comment on Duffus' report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0237EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DigitalRecorders Bjt   03-02 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digital Recorders, Bjt,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Recording Industry Vows New Attack on DAT Recorders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The music industry promises to find a new way
to thwart home taping with digital recorders now that its proposed
electronic anti-taping device has been declared ineffective by the
National Bureau of Standards.
   The bureau's report, released Tuesday, dealt a blow to the
recording industry's campaign to prevent digital audio tape, or
DAT, recorders from reaching the domestic market.
   The recorders, now manufactured by Japan and other foreign
makers, can copy compact disc recordings with virtually no loss in
sound quality. The U.S. recording industry fears that the machines
will lead to mass copying that would devastate the compact disc and
record markets, and so far has managed to keep the devices off the
U.S. market.
   But Rep. Robert W. Kastenmeier, D-Wis., chairman of a House
Judiciary subcommittee that handles copyright issues, said the
results of the bureau's study _ which he requested last year _
shows that Congress should stop trying to prevent U.S. sales of DAT
recorders.
   Kastenmeier said the report appears to doom an industry-backed
bill that would require equipping DAT recorders with scanning
devices intended to prevent copying of specially coded recordings.
   The bill, sponsored by Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., also would
prohibit the manufacture or sale of any device designed to bypass
the scanner.
   The bureau, an agency of the Commerce Department, said that the
scanning device was unreliable and easily bypassed, and that it
damaged the sound quality of recordings.
   ``Because the report was conclusive about the ineffectiveness of
blocking devices, it is even more desirable that the DAT
controversy be resolved by the industries involved, rather than by
congressional imposition of a solution,'' Kastenmeier said.
   Kastenmeier said in an interview that as a result of the bureau
of standards report, ``I think it highly unlikely that the Waxman
bill will succeed.''
   U.S. manufacturers voluntarily blocked introduction of DAT units
on the domestic market until Congress resolved the home taping
issue, but the self-imposed ban has recently shown signs of
crumbling under pressure from foreign manufacturers and demand from
U.S. recording enthusiasts.
   Kastenmeier said an alternative to a congressional solution
might be payment of recording artists out of proceeds from sales of
DAT units, or from an endowment fund created by the recording
industry.
   Jason Berman, president of the Recording Industry Association of
America, said the industry accepts the study results but intends to
find a new technological solution to home taping, which he said
costs the recording companies $1.5 billion in lost sales annually.
   ``Working together with the hardware manufacturers, we are
certain to find an acceptable technological solution,'' Berman said.
   Meanwhile, recording industry officials promised to sue any
manufacturer that tries to sell the machines in the United States
before the copying issue is resolved, either legislatively or
through industry negotiations.
   But Gary Shapiro of the Home Recording Rights Coalition said
``there is no reason at this point why manufacturers should not be
selling'' digital recorders in the United States.
   The coalition has been fighting anti-taping efforts as an
infringement on the rights of consumers to make home recordings of
records, tapes and compact discs for their private use.
   The scanning device was designed to detect ``notches,'' or tiny
bands of frequencies removed from the audio signal of protected
recordings, and interrupt taping of copies with intervals of
silence.
   The bureau said its series of laboratory tests showed that
notched material was recorded anyway in about half of the sound
tracks studied.
   Advocates of the anti-taping device claimed that the notches did
not affect sound quality. But the bureau said its study showed that
``the system's encoder alters the original electrical signal,''
resulting in ``a discernible difference'' between notched and
unnotched recordings.
   Also, the bureau said, ``the copy prevention system can be
bypassed easily.'' It said its engineers designed and built several
electronic circuits to circumvent the system in five different ways.
   ``The circuits are simple and easy to construct'' and cost about
$100, the bureau said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
