<DOCNO> AP880302-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Stock Bjt   03-02 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Stock, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Stock Profits Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III's investment
manager turned a $40,000 profit for him under an arrangement that
may have involved financial favors or gifts to the attorney
general, says a senator.
   The investment manager, W. Franklyn Chinn, ``wasn't investing
Mr. Meese's money, so much as he was assigning profits and losses
to the accounts of Mr. Meese and his other clients at his own
discretion,'' Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said Tuesday.
   Chinn, now under indictment in the Wedtech scandal, turned a
profit of nearly $40,000 for Meese on a $50,000 investment in just
23 one-day trades of brand-new stock issues over an 18-month span.
Meese established a limited blind partnership with Chinn's company
and the attorney general says that under the arrangement he knew
nothing about Chinn's stock trading activity.
   The Democratic majority staff of the Senate subcommittee on
oversight of government management found that stock purchases by
Chinn which later appeared in Meese's account were initially made
without identifying the customer in whose name the stock would
eventually be recorded. The purchases were assigned by Chinn to the
accounts he managed, after the profit or loss was known.
   The report said that in one instance, Chinn bought and sold
5,000 shares of a new stock issue in Oliver Stores Inc. worth
$30,000 on Feb. 11, 1986. It wasn't until the next day, however,
that Chinn instructed Imperial Trust Co. that 2,000 of the shares
were to be recorded for Meese's account. The transaction gave Meese
a profit of more than $1,700.
   In seven of the 23 stock trades, Chinn spent substantially more
money on behalf of his corporation's limited blind partnership with
Meese than Meese had invested in the account, the subcommittee
staff found. The sums ranged from $5,000 to $140,000.
   Chinn exceeded the account balances for his other customers as
well, said the subcommittee staff. He avoided the appearance that
he had exceeded the account balance by directing that his stock
purchases be recorded as if they had been made in smaller lots, any
one of which would not exceed the account balance.
   ``Because he did not allocate winners and losers to his clients'
accounts until after the fact, he was effectively able to assign
greater benefits to some _ including apparently Mr. Meese on
numerous occasions,'' Levin said in a statement. ``This procedure
again raises questions about possible financial favors or gifts.''
   Levin asked the Office of Government Ethics in a letter for a
formal finding on whether Meese complied with federal regulations
governing gifts and loans to public officials.
   Levin also sent a copy of the letter to the Securities and
Exchange Commission to investigate possible violations of
regulations prohibiting brokers from exceeding account balances and
regulations governing the conduct by investment advisers.
   Meese ``had no knowledge of Chinn's stock trading activity and I
don't think Meese should be held responsible,'' said one of the
attorney general's lawyers, Nathan Lewin.
   ``This blind partnership was set up to be sure that he had no
knowledge of how things were being done.''
   Lewin dismissed suggestions that Meese should have reported the
amount over the account balances as gifts, saying ``there were a
number of losing transactions as well as profitable transactions.''
   Meese made a profit on 18 of the trades and lost money on five.
   According to the majority subcommittee staff, on Sept. 4, 1986,
Chinn had $730,000 in five of his customers' accounts at Imperial
Trust Co., but on that day bought $6.6 million in Sears, Roebuck
stock for them, which subsequently was reflected as 34 separate
transactions and sales.
   Chinn, a former director of scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp., was
introduced to the attorney general in 1985 by longtime Meese friend
E. Robert Wallach. Chinn and Wallach are now under indictment for
racketeering, fraud and conspiracy in an alleged scheme to extract
payments from the Bronx, N.Y., defense contractor in order to
influence Meese and other federal officials. Wallach and Chinn have
pleaded innocent.
   Meese has been under criminal investigation by independent
counsel James McKay since last May 11 for his involvement with
Wedtech. Meese acknowledges interceding on behalf of the company
when he was White House counselor to ensure that the firm got a
fair hearing from the Army in its effort to win a $32 million
no-bid engine-building contract. The company eventually got the
work.
   Sources familiar with McKay's probe say one aspect of the
investigation has been an examination of Chinn's stock trading to
determine whether Chinn may have given Meese preferential treatment
over other customers.
   Meese may be found to have benefited from a ``very subtle
bribe'' if preferential treatment were found and were determined to
be a reward for official action, one knowledgeable law enforcement
source said in December.
   One of Chinn's lawyers, Penny Cooper, said the questions
addressed by Levin's subcommittee are ``exactly the same material
the independent counsel went over for months and they found no
wrongdoing. There was no wrongdoing.'' She said that Chinn ``did no
better for Meese than any other client.''
   The subcommittee staff didn't reach any conclusions on whether
Meese received preferential treatment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
