<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0243EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TempletonPrize     03-02 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Templeton Prize,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prestigious Religion Prize Awarded To Moselm For First Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 11 a.m. EST. Time set by source</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inamullah Khan of Pakistan today won the 1988
Templeton Prize for promoting interreligious cooperation. He is the
first Moslem to win the $390,000 international award.
   It is biggest prize given in the world, about $40,000 more than
the Nobel prizes in science and literature.
   Announcement of this year's winner was to be made at a news
conference at Manhattan's Church Center of the United Nations.
   Khan, 73, a founder and secretary-general of the World Moslem
Congress, was cited for his ``tireless work as a coordinator for
peace between Moslems, Christians and Jews.''
   Khan, of Karachi, also is chairman of the executive committee of
the interreligious World Conference on Religion and Peace,
presiding at meetings around the world.
   He has been keenly supportive of United Nations concerns,
including disarmament, human rights, education and welfare, and
twice has chaired meetings of the World Federation of United
Nations Associations in Geneva, Switzerland.
   The annual prize, established in 1972 by American financeer John
Templeton, is given to recognize those ``who through original and
pioneering ways advanced the knowledge and love of God.''
   The 1988 prize is to presented May 10 by England's Princess
Alexandra at London's Guild Hall.
   Of the previous 15 winners, 13 have been Christians, one Hindu
and one Buddhist.
   The first winner was Mother Teresa of Calcutta, India, founder
of the Roman Catholic Missionaries of Charity, while last year's
winner was physicist Stanley L. Jaki, a Roman Catholic, of Seton
Hall University in South Orange, N.J.
   Other winners have included:
   Southern Baptist evangelist Billy Graham, Russian Orthodox
expatriate Alexander Solzhenitsyn, Belgium's Cardinal Joseph
Suenens, U.S. Presbyterian educator James I. McCord and France's
Brother Roger, founder of the Taize ecumenical community.
   An international, interreligious panel of judges picks the
winners.
   Khan, born in Burma and a graduate in arts and law from Rangoon
University, was a high school principal in Rangoon and editor of
Burma's Moslem Daily until 1942 when Burma was occupied by Japan.
   He then settled in India, where he headed the All-India Burmese
Evacuees Association and the Islamic Brotherhood Society. On
establishment of Pakistan in 1948, he became a citizen, settling in
Karachi.
   There, he founded the World Moslem Congress, its offices
initially in his home, but which now has an imposing new
headquarters there.
   As secretary-general, he has traveled throughout the Moslem
world, including both sides of the protracted Iran-Iraq war, and
has stood with banned Christian leaders in South Africa.
   The Rev. Wilbert Forker, vice president of the Templeton
Foundation, said Khan has given ``much energy and imagination to
building bridges between the Moslem world and neighbors from other
religions and cultures.''
   He ``has lived in a generation when religion has often come in
for attack from secular sources'' and has challenged ``atheistic
teachings and practices'' and pressed religion to correct its
failings, Forker said.
   ``He is clearly a man sustained by his faith in God and in human
values and by his sense of solidarity with his community and with
humanity,'' Forker said. ``Religion for him is not simply a private
matter but an essential motivation for society.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BeltMisuse Bjt   03-02 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Belt Misuse, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Improper Use of Seat Belts Dangerous but Common</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many motorists who wear seat belts are still
exposing themselves to serious injury by wearing them improperly,
according to a federal study that says women, children and
motorists over 50 are most likely to put themselves at risk.
   The National Transportation Safety Board raised questions
Tuesday about the way some belt users wear the safety devices after
examining 167 accidents in which at least one occupant was belted.
   Twenty-one percent of the motorists wearing belts had too much
slack in the shoulder harnesses, and 7 percent of the occupants,
often children, wore belts that were improperly routed behind the
back or under an arm.
   Thirty-one states have laws requiring use of safety belts. But
NTSB Chairman Jim Burnett said, ``We have a lot of misuse and that
problem has to be tackled.''
   Overall, the safety board said, lap-shoulder belts provide
excellent protection with 80 percent of the belted occupants
suffering minor or no injuries. But the study suggested the results
could have been even better were it not for improper wearing of
belts.
   The NTSB study was not a random sample and, therefore, does not
necessarily translate into similar percentages for all motorists,
said Lynne Smith, who was involved in writing of the report. But,
she added, the data are consistent with previous findings of
widespread misuse.
   For example, the report cited an earlier insurance industry
study of Maryland motorists indicating that belts are worn too
loosely about one-fourth of the time.
   Examples of misuse with tragic consequences included a head-on
collision and an accident in which a car struck a tree, according
to the safety board.
   In the head-on crash, a passenger who had loosened her shoulder
belt significantly died of massive injuries, while the driver who
had worn his belt snugly ``walked away from the crash with moderate
injuries,'' said Suzanne Stack, an NTSB staff researcher.
   In the other crash, the driver, who had worn his belt properly,
escaped with minor injuries when his car struck a tree, but the
passenger, whose shoulder belt was routed under her arm, was killed
from extensive injuries.
   The board also cited examples of people suffering extensive
injuries _ fatal ones in a case involving a 7-year-old boy _ when
belts were used while seats were in the reclining position. In some
cases the combination of the belt and the reclining seat may create
new dangers, the report suggested.
   The four-member safety board urged the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration to require that safety belts meet standards
for the maximum amount of slack allowed or require that the belt
systems be equipped with a ``pre-tension'' device that
automatically pulls a belt tight a split second before a crash.
   The safety board questioned the widespread use among U.S.
carmakers of a belt design that allows a person to pull the belt
out to its full length without it automatically retracting. Most
foreign manufacturers use another design which automatically keeps
the belt snug against the occupant, but which has been criticized
as being less comfortable and, therefore, less likely to be used.
   The safety board said there is evidence indicating drivers aged
50 years or older and female occupants are the most likely to
misuse belts, especially wearing them too loosely. Ms. Smith said
that, generally, slack equal to no more than the width of a fist
should be allowed in the shoulder belt.
   A particularly high misuse of belts was found among children.
One-third had part of the belts behind the back or under an arm.
   ``Such misuse ... seriously degrades the protective capabilities
of the lap-shoulder belt, reducing it to a lap-only belt with
inferior crash protection,'' the safety board said.
   A number of auto safety pamphlets, including two distributed by
the NHTSA and one by the American Automobile Association, have
advised parents to place the shoulder belt behind a child if the
harness crosses the neck or face.
   ``The safety board does not agree,'' the NTSB report said.
``There is little evidence that small children or short adults are
likely to be harmed by the shoulder portion of a belt.''
   The board called for the highway safety agency to revise its
brochures.
   NHTSA, which issues auto safety regulations, was reviewing the
NTSB report, said spokeswoman Betsy Tyson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     03-02 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ABC Gets Olympics Rating Boost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States might not have fared that well
in the Winter Olympics, but ABC was a big winner.
   The high-rated two weeks of prime-time Olympics, pre-empting
ABC's entire schedule, have given the network a February sweeps win
that breaks NBC's 11-sweeps streak. ABC is now second on the season.
   The Olympics averaged a prime-time rating of 19.3 and a 30
share, up 5 percent over the 1984 Winter Olympics, according to the
A.C. Nielsen Co. ABC estimates that more than 150 million viewers
saw some of this year's Games.
   Saturday night's figure-skating finale was last week's No. 1
show, earning a rating of 26.4 and a 43 share, and included the
highest-rated half hour of Saturday viewing since ``Roots'' in 1977.
   Olympics coverage on Monday, Tuesday and Thursday also made it
into the top 10. Wednesday's was 12th, Sunday's 17th, and Friday's
30th. ABC had no other prime-time programming.
   The Olympics also apparently helped ABC continue its three-week
win streak over CBS in news. For the week that ended Feb. 26, ABC's
``World News Tonight'' had an average rating of 11.7 and a 21
share. ``CBS Evening News'' had an 11.2 and 20 and ``NBC Nightly
News'' had 9.9 and 18.
   The rating is the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million
households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in
use.
   ABC won the week that ended Feb. 28 with an average rating of
20.5. NBC was second with 15.6 and CBS third with 13.5. It was the
highest weekly rating for any network since October 1986, and ABC's
highest since October 1985.
   February is one of four months a year when local ratings are
measured for use in negotiating advertising rates. With only days
left uncounted in the February sweeps, ABC led NBC by about 1.5
rating points. CBS is third.
   NBC has an average 16.3 after 23 weeks of the television season.
ABC is second with 14.1, and CBS third with 13.6.
   The top 10 prime-time shows last week were: Saturday Olympics,
ABC; ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC; Tuesday Olympics, ABC; ``A Different
World,'' NBC; Monday Olympics, ABC; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS;
``Cheers,'' NBC; Thursday Olympics, ABC; ``Murder, She Wrote,''
CBS; and ``Matlock,'' NBC.
   The four-part miniseries ``Noble House'' ended disappointingly
for NBC. The final installment Wednesday night took a slight
upturn, but was only 20th.
   The first part of CBS' two-part ``Bluegrass'' did better, coming
in 15th with a 17.6 rating and 27 share.
   The annual rerun of the classic movie ``The Wizard of Oz'' on
CBS last Wednesday had its lowest rating yet, but still placed 25th
with a 15.3 and 22.
   The lowest-rated shows of the week _ the rankings were
abbreviated due to the Olympics taking up ABC's schedule, were:
``Wiseguy,'' ``Cagney & Lacey,'' ``Sonny Spoon,'' ``Charlie
Brown,'' ``Our House,'' ``Garfield,'' ``Equalizer,'' ``High
Mountain Rangers'' and ``West 57th,'' which was against the
Olympics Saturday night and got a dismal 5.5 rating and 9 share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
