<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Grammys     03-02 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grammys,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>30th Annual Grammy Awards Feature Michael Jackson Performance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   And the winner is ...
   Michael Jackson? U2? Prince? Whitney Houston?
   The answer could be any and all of the above tonight at the 30th
Annual Grammy Awards, which return to New York City after a
seven-year absence and promise a number of special performances and
possible surprises.
   Jackson, who has four nominations, will perform his most recent
hit, ``Man in the Mirror,'' with an all-star backing cast including
Andrae Crouch, The Winans and Siedah Garrett. It is the superstar's
first televised live appearance in five years.
   The Grammys will be broadcast on CBS-TV from Radio City Music
Hall beginning at 8 p.m. EST.
   Not performing but likely to spend plenty of time on stage are
the Irish rockers U2, who garnered four major nominations and go
head-to-head with Jackson for album of the year.
   U2, whose album ``The Joshua Tree'' vaulted them to prominence
last year, also is up for record of the year, song of the year and
best rock vocal performance by a group or duo.
   Jackson has additional nominations for best male pop vocal
performance, best male rhythm and blues vocal performance and
producer of the year with Quincy Jones.
   Prince (``Sign O' the Times'') and Houston (``Whitney'') are
also up for album of the year, along with Dolly Parton, Linda
Ronstadt and Emmylou Harris for their ``Trio'' album.
   Prince also has been nominated for best rhythm and blues vocal
performance by a group or duo with Sheena Easton for ``U Got the
Look,'' which also garnered him a nomination for best rhythm and
blues song _ a songwriter's award.
   Houston, who will perform the nominated ``I Wanna Dance With
Somebody,'' is a potential winner in the categories best female pop
vocal performance and best female rhythm and blues vocal
performance.
   But there are lesser-known nominees with good chances at
capturing one of the tiny phonograph trophys handed out by the
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences.
   New York's own Suzanne Vega, a cult favorite who broke into the
top 10 with her song ``Luka,'' is up for record of the year, song
of the year and best female pop vocal performance. Los Angeles'
favorite sons, Los Lobos, are nominated both for their inspired
remake of Ritchie Valens' ``La Bamba'' and their brilliant second
album, ``By the Light of the Moon.''
   Los Lobos will perform their version of ``La Bamba,'' a Mexican
folk tune adapted by the late Valens, at the awards show and Vega
is slated to do ``Luka.'' The only other nominee scheduled to
perform is best new artist hopeful Terence Trent D'Arby.
   D'Arby's competition includes Breakfast Club, Cutting Crew,
Swing Out Sister and Jody Watley.
</TEXT>
