<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Canada-Autos 360   03-02 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Autos, 360</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Critics Charge US-Canada Pact Leaves Auto Problems Unsolved</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A treaty to eliminate most tariff barriers
between the United States and Canada leaves disputes in the auto
industry unresolved, witnesses at a House hearing said.
   Lee Kadrich, director of governmental affairs and international
trade with the Automotive Parts and Accessories Association, said
Tuesday the treaty was ``a lopsided agreement that sanctions
long-standing Canadian protectionism.''
   He told the trade subcommittee of the House Ways and Means
Committee that the treaty would put U.S. parts makers at the mercy
of foreign competitors.
   Automotive products, which account for about one-third of the
trade between the United States and Canada, have been governed for
more than 20 years by the Auto Pact, which gives duty-free
treatment to some parts and vehicles moving between the two
countries.
   Critics of the free-trade agreement, however, charge that
Canadian efforts to attract manufacturing have given their makers
an unfair advantage under the Auto Pact, and the agreement leaves
that advantage in place.
   ``Our current bilateral auto trade is skewed, to Canada's
benefit, by a number of trade-distorting practices,'' resulting in
part from Canada's domestic-content requirements and duty rebates
on some auto parts, said Rep. Sander Levin, a Southfield, Mich.,
Democrat.
   Steve Beckman, international economist for the United Auto
Workers union, said that the treaty, by retaining Canadian
production incentives for Honda, Toyota and Hyundai, provides ``a
subsidy of Canadian production, much of which will be sold in the
U.S.''
   An exception to that overall assessment was given by Thomas
Hanna of the Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association, which
represents auto manufacturers.
   Hanna said the treaty would create the world's largest
free-trade zone and ``takes on and resolves most of the trouble
spots which were developing in the bilateral auto trade.''
   He said concerns that the treaty would provide expanded entry
for Japanese and Korean manufacturers were unfounded because the
North American auto industry already has excess manufacturing
capacity.
   ``It makes no sense for the Canadian government to lure more
foreign auto investment, especially when much of the production
would be headed for the U.S. market,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0253EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hussein-Helicopter     03-02 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hussein-Helicopter,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter Crash Probe Ends Without Probable Cause Determined</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board says
it was unable to determine what caused the crash in 1986 of a
helicopter scheduled to carry the entourage of Jordan's King
Hussein in which four people died.
   Investigators concluded that poor flying conditions, including
fog that caused limited visibility, were factors in the June 6,
1986, crash in Sutton, Mass. But the official probable cause was
listed as ``undetermined.''
   Dennis Jones, the lead investigator, said Tuesday the massive
disintegration of the helicopter hindered the inquiry. ``We're only
as good as the evidence,'' he said.
   ``There's no evidence to point to anything that we can
concretely say'' triggered the crash, NTSB spokesman Michael Benson
said.
   Investigators originally concentrated on a mysterious piece of
wire that raised questions of sabotage, but that turned out to be
part of an electrical testing instrument.
   The investigation later focused on what looked like a frayed
cable that controlled the tail rotor, which provides stability to
the craft. But the final report, issued Monday, said ``no
pre-impact part failure (or) malfunction was found.''
   Four employees of Sikorsky Aircraft were killed when the
seven-seat, Sikorsky-built S-76B helicopter went down on a trip
from Hanscom Field in Bedford, Mass., back to Sikorsky headquarters
in Stratford, Conn.
   The helicopter was one of four Sikorsky had provided to Hussein
during his New England visit, but the king, his family and aides
drove from Massachusetts to the Westover School in Middlebury,
Conn., for the graduation of his daughter, Princess Zeim, because
of the bad weather. Her twin sister, Princess Aisha, graduated from
the Dana Hall School in Wellesley, Mass., later that weekend.
   Sikorsky spokesman Marty Moore said the company supports the
board's findings.
   Benson said the crash illustrates the need for smaller aircraft
to carry ``black boxes,'' devices that would tape the crew's
conversations and possibly provide clues.
   The safety board has been pushing the Federal Aviation
Administration to require cockpit voice recorders in smaller craft,
including helicopters that seat at least six passengers. The FAA is
considering the proposed rules change.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0311EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Superconductivity     03-02 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Superconductivity,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Confirm Superconductivity Temperature Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists in two laboratories say they have
confirmed a report from researchers that a new kind of
superconducting material loses all resistance to electricity at a
record high temperature.
   Researchers at the University of Arkansas say the material
showed zero resistance at about minus 269 degrees Fahrenheit, more
than 20 degrees above previous widely accepted reports for stable
superconducting compounds.
   Paul Chu of the University of Houston said he had confirmed the
Arkansas results, finding zero resistance at minus 272 degrees. He
said his sample also expelled an applied magnetic field, a hallmark
of superconductivity called the Meissner effect.
   The results also have been confirmed by researchers at
International Business Machines Corp., said IBM spokesman Jerry
Present. He said he could not release details.
   Superconductivity is the ability to carry current without
resistance. Scientists are trying to make materials that become
superconducting at as high a temperature as possible, to make them
practical for uses in high-speed computers, bullet trains and other
applications.
   Higher temperatures than the Arkansas mark have been reported in
the press. But some have not been confirmed in other laboratories,
and others refer to the temperature at which a sample shows initial
signs of isolated pockets of superconductivity, rather than
superconducting pathways along its entire length.
   The new compound showed initial signs of superconductivity at
minus 238 degrees, said University of Arkansas researcher Allen
Hermann, who did the research with Zhenghi Sheng.
   That is slightly higher than the mark of about minus 243 degrees
recently reported for superconductors that include the element
bismuth rather than a so-called ``rare earth.''
   The Arkansas compound uses the element thallium rather than
bismuth or rare earth. Other ingredients are calcium, barium,
copper and oxygen.
   The results were announced to the press and at a scientific
meeting last month, but were not widely reported. They have been
accepted for publication in the British journal Nature, Hermann
said in a telephone interview.
   Chu said lessons from the thallium and bismuth compounds will
help in developing materials with still higher temperatures. He
also noted that the thallium compound showed zero resistance above
100 degrees on the Kelvin scale, giving a psychological boost for
hopes of higher temperatures.
   The 100-degree Kelvin mark corresponds to about minus 280
degrees Fahrenheit.
   Thallium is ``not quite practical'' for applications outside the
laboratory because it is toxic and in limited supply, he said.
   Hermann said he thinks thallium and bismuth eventually will be
abandoned in favor of new materials with higher temperatures and
better characteristics for applications.
   Brian Schwartz, physics professor at Brooklyn College, said the
Arkansas work is encouraging because it shows that substituting
elements in superconducting materials may lead to higher
temperatures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
