<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Singers     03-02 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Singers,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Singers Protest Israel's Handling of Arab Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30 of Israel's leading
entertainers staged a sing-in to protest the government's handling
of 12 weeks of Arab riots in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``Shalom, shalom, we are making peace. There will be peace. We
are together beyond fear,'' they sang, swaying together on a stage
in front of Tel Aviv's City Hall.
   About 3,000 Israelis sang along in Hebrew to the tune of ``We
are the World.''
   The protesters also heard newly released peace songs and carried
placards that said ``We won't be a nation of bullies'' and ``Enough
of occupation.''
   The demonstration was held in Kings of Israel Plaza, site of a
protest by more than 100,000 Israelis in 1982 that helped lead to
Israel's pullout from Lebanon.
   Tuesday's protest was sponsored by Red Line, peace activists who
are staging a four-day march from Rosh Haniqra on the Lebanon
border to Jerusalem, where about 1,500 marchers are expected today.
   Three months of Arab rioting against the 20-year Israeli
occupation of their homelands has produced a crop of new protest
songs, the first since the end of Israel's three-year occupation of
Lebanon in 1985.
   Among the stars was Rita Fayrouz, the Iranian-born singer who
recently released ``A Song For Children.'' The lyrics say, ``he was
born of mother war, but deep in his heart, he just wanted to be a
poet.''
   A number of participants expressed disappointment at the
relatively small turnout. But Rami Kleinstein, a rock musician and
Ms. Fayrouz's husband, predicted ``change is going to happen.''
   One of the most critical songs was by Si Hyman, 26, who wrote
``Shooting and Crying'' to protest an incident last month in which
Israeli soldiers buried alive four Arabs in Kfar Salem. The victims
were rescued by relatives.
   Ms. Hyman sang:
   ``Shooting and crying, burning and laughing
   ``When did we learn to bury alive?
   ``Shooting and crying, burning and laughing
   ``When did we forget that we also had children killed?''
   In an interview after the performance, she said she was shocked
that ``this was done by the Jewish people who lived through the
Holocaust. I said to myself we've got to stop it.''
</TEXT>
