<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NATO-Congress     03-02 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO-Congress,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historian Says Allies Need To Increase Share Of Defense Burden</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and Western Europe were rebuilt with
America's help after World War II and should now repay the United
States by picking up a larger share of NATO and Japanese defense
costs, according to a well-known historian.
   The comments Tuesday by Yale historian Paul Kennedy echoed other
calls by legislators and former government officials as President
Reagan flew to Europe for a two-day meeting of the 16-nation North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Kennedy, author of ``The Rise and Fall of Great Nations,'' told
the Senate Budget Committee that calls for increased ``burden
sharing'' are part of the effort to find a way out of ever-growing
defense expenditures.
   Some American allies ``are now richer per capita than the USA,''
Kennedy said, adding that Japan and Western Europe ``ought to bear
a larger share of the defense burden.''
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., chairman of the panel, agreed,
saying: ``It seems to me we are draining our power trying to do too
much. Our adversaries are happy to see us try. Our allies haven't
done as much as they can to help.''
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci also agreed at least in part
with Kennedy. At a House Budget Committee hearing earlier Tuesday,
he said, ``I quite agree with the thesis that our allies need to do
more.'' But he added that ``I don't think it is very useful to
simply berate the Europeans on this.''
   Carlucci told the House panel that he doesn't think NATO will
increase spending in response to complaints by Congress.
   Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., chairman of the committee, complained
about what he called ``unequal sharing'' by NATO countries. ``Our
allies in NATO are not doing, in my estimation, enough for their
own defense,'' he said.
   The United States is spending about 6 percent of its gross
national product on defense while no other countries in NATO are
above 3 percent, Gray said.
   Rep. Richard Durbin, R-Ill., said the average Japanese citizen
spends about $100 a year in taxes for defense, while the average
American spends $1,200.
   ``We need to make every effort to get our allies to do more,''
Carlucci agreed, but he added that they do more than is ``generally
recognized.'' He cited a statistic that NATO would supply 90
percent of the ground troops that would be used to halt a Soviet
non-nuclear attack.
   Carlucci said America's defense budget is 5.7 percent of the
nation's GNP, not 6 percent and he added that U.S. defense budgets
generally have stayed even or declined in recent years.
   NATO has long set a target for each member to increase spending
by 3 percent a year after inflation, and most nations don't meet
that target, Carlucci said. The United States hasn't met the 3
percent target for at least four years, he added.
   Carlucci and Adm. William Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, said NATO needs to improve its conventional
defenses in the wake of the treaty banning medium-range atomic
missiles from Europe.
   Crowe detailed NATO's shortcomings in non-nuclear weapons, but
added, ``surely the prospect of having to fight 16 nations at once
remains a sobering one for the Kremlin.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Congress     03-02 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Congress,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Off To Sluggish Start Despite Promises, Hopes</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Congress convened last July for
the first time in 15 years, it vowed to build democracy from the
ruins of authoritarian rule. Seven months later, critics say it has
been slow to address fundamental issues.
   The new constitution, drafted under President Corazon Aquino,
reestablished the bicameral, U.S.-style Congress. Former President
Ferdinand Marcos abolished Congress in 1972 and replaced it with a
single-chamber, rubber-stamp assembly.
   Members of the Senate and House of Representatives were elected
in May 1987, and Congress convened last July 27. Since then, more
than 6,000 bills have been submitted in the 23-member Senate and
the 202-member House.
   As of the end of February, only 13 had been enacted into law.
   ``The bills are not an indication of quality at all,'' said Rep.
Bonifacio Gillego. He said most were for local projects such as
roads, schools and hospitals.
   Meanwhile, legislation on major national issues, such as land
reform, has been bogged down by special interests and
organizational problems in the two chambers.
   Commentators and congressional sources disagree on why Congress
has not been more productive.
   Some complain that traditional politicians spend too much time
on ``peripheral'' topics or delivering lengthy speeches while
ignoring complex issues.
   ``It's part of the turmoil of transition, part of growing up,''
said opposition leader Wilson Gamboa, who was defeated for the
Senate last May. ``Vital issues of legislation that should have
far-reaching effects on the condition of the people have not been
addressed.''
   Some congressmen defend the slow pace, saying it is better to
take time with complicated issues than rush legislation which
members may later regret.
   ``We cannot afford to hurry that much and regret it later,''
said Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile. ``We're not just talking about our few
interests but a complex situation.''
   Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate Defense Committee,
also defended the slow pace.
   ``Is that what they want, faster laws but probably imperfect
laws?'' Maceda said in an interview. ``We're slower, but probably
all sides are heard.''
   Last month, eight Senators formed a ``conscience bloc'' and
publicly criticized Senate President Jovito Salonga for delays in
bringing legislation to the floor.
   One of the eight, Sen. Alberto Romulo, said economic and social
issues ``have not been given the importance they deserve.'' He
added, ``Our performance will be assessed by how much we have done
to improve the quality of life of our people.''
   Salonga promised to speed up Senate proceedings and reduce the
time allotted for speeches.
   Some congressmen also complain that the two chambers lack
sufficient staff and resources to provide members with detailed
information and advice on legislation.
   Many commentators view the current debate on land reform as a
test case of Congress' ability to legislate controversial issues
with far-reaching impact on national life.
   Last July, Mrs. Aquino decreed a nationwide land redistribution
program but left virtually all the difficult decisions, such as
compensation and retention limits, to Congress.
   She gave the lawmakers 90 days to approve the legislation, and
House Speaker Ramon Mitra boasted his chamber would meet the
deadline within 30 days. But neither the House nor the Senate has
approved a land reform bill, in part because of opposition by
landlord members.
   ``There has been considerable delay, almost intentional on the
part of the landlords to avoid the passage of an agrarian reform
bill,'' said Gillego, chairman of the House's Land Reform Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
