<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugTesting     03-02 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Testing,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says Drug Rulings Should Be Appealed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department should appeal a pair of
conflicting rulings on random drug testing for civilian government
employees in order to resolve the issue, says a judge responsible
for one of the decisions.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas F. Hogan on Tuesday ordered the Army
to stop random checks of 9,400 of its civilian employees for drug
use because the tests are an unreasonable search prohibited by the
Constitution.
   ``It is with some regret that the court removes what might be a
powerful weapon from the nation's arsenal in the campaign against
illegal drug use, but the values represented by the Constitution
and Fourth Amendment are transcendent,'' Hogan ruled.
   Hogan said random checks could not be justified by safety
concerns because the urine test used by the Army did not indicate
whether an employee was using drugs on the job.
   The ruling was made on three challenges brought by public
employees unions to the Army's 1986 order directing random drug
tests of civilians in sensitive jobs. The cases involved unions
representing civilians at Ft. Stewart, Ga., the Sharp Army Depot in
Lathrop, Calif. and guards at Aberdeen Proving Ground, Md.
   Noting that another federal judge in Washington last year upheld
random drug testing of nearly 30,000 Transportation Department
employees, Hogan invited the Justice Department to appeal his
decision.
   He also suggested that the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here
consolidate the two cases for a single review of ``a question of
exceptional importance.''
   Based on Hogan's invitation, ``we are reviewing the opinion and
are considering an appeal,'' said Amy Brown, a Justice Department
spokeswoman.
   On Monday, the Supreme Court agreed to review a ruling by a
federal appeals court in New Orleans, which had upheld drug testing
of U.S. Customs Service employees who seek promotions.
   A federal appeals court in San Francisco last month ruled
unconstitutional the mandatory drug testing of railway workers
involved in accidents.
</TEXT>
