<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Kennedy-Hunger     03-02 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy-Hunger,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Offering Plan To Increase Food Stamp Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy says increases in the
government's food stamp program are needed to make up for Reagan
administration cuts that have helped create hunger in America
through the 1980s.
   ``The cold statistics only begin to measure the toll in terms of
the human lives damaged, disabled and destroyed by our shameful
abdication of responsibility in recent years,'' the Massachusetts
Democrat told a group of nutrition activists Tuesday.
   ``We have financed the greatest arms buildup in human history,
but once again we are losing the war on hunger,'' he said.
   Kennedy, chairman of the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee, planned to introduce legislation today with Sen. Patrick
J. Leahy, D-Vt., and Rep. Leon E. Panetta, D-Calif., that would
help ``right those wrongs.''
   ``I do not intend to accept proposals that seek to balance the
federal budget on the backs of poor children,'' he said. ``Survival
of the fittest may be the law of the jungle, but it is not the law
of America, and it is time for America to help.''
   Kennedy said his anti-hunger legislation would raise food stamp
benefits ``so that no Americans are forced to go hungry for the
last part of every month.''
   It also would ease food stamp eligibility requirements and
provide more public information about the program.
   Kennedy said hunger in America was largely eradicated by the
late 1970s, but ``misguided'' budget cuts under President Reagan
have ``rubbed salt in the wounds'' created by the recession of the
early 1980s, triggering the re-emergence of hunger.
   Earlier, Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn told the Food Research
and Action Center's annual conference that the nation needs a
``compassionate urban agenda.''
   Flynn, chairman of the U.S. Conference of Mayors' task force on
hunger and homelessness, said both problems are growing, especially
among families with children.
   ``The sad truth is that hunger is now more prevalent in our
nation than at any time since the Great Depression,'' he said.
</TEXT>
