<1ST_LINE>r w PM-USPostmarks     03-02 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Postmarks,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain's `Jesus' Postmark Unlikely To Show Up Here</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Jesus Postmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stamp cancellation such as the British one
proclaiming that ``Jesus Is Alive'' could not be issued in the
United States, a Postal Service official says.
   The Postal Service's 74 division managers can approve special
cancellations for events of general public interest, said Dick
Rustin, manager of the Stamp Information Branch.
   The special cancellations may not deal with things only of local
interest or for political, religious, fraternal, trade or
commercial purposes, he said Tuesday.
   The British Post Office on Tuesday began postmarking nearly all
letters mailed in that country with the words ``Jesus Is Alive!''
as part of a private arrangement financed by an evangelist.
   Jewish leaders criticized the Christian cancellation as
potentially offensive.
   The special postmark, which also contains a small cross, will
last six weeks and was paid for by Paul Slennet, who sells
religious literature at two bookstores in Southend-on-Sea, east of
London. He said God told him to buy the postmark.
   The state-owned Post Office said Slennet paid the equivalent of
$88,500 for the privilege of having every letter mailed through 68
of Britain's 69 sorting offices with the Jesus message.
   Rustin said groups seeking the special cancellations have to pay
$900 for the engraving of the cancellation plus about $100 for each
canceling die to be used. For a large post office many dies can be
required, Rustin said.
</TEXT>
