<HEAD>Boston Globe, Black Star Photographers Winners Of Photo Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Greene of The Boston Globe and Anthony
Suau of Black Star were chosen the top newspaper and magazine
photographers of the year in the 45th annual Pictures of the Year
competition at the University of Missouri.
   The top photo essayist award went to Herman Leroy Emmet, a New
York City free-lancer who won for a seven-year documentary focusing
on migrant workers.
   Bill Kuykendall, director of the Pictures of the Year
competition, said Tuesday that a record 1,995 photographers entered
more than 37,000 photographs in what he called ``the world's
largest and most significant photojournalism competition.''
   The contest is cosponsored by the National Press Photographers
Association and the University of Missouri School of Journalism.
Eight experts in photography worked for two weeks narrowing the
field of more than 37,000 entries in 38 categories.
   The winners by categories:
   Newspaper Photographer of the Year: Bill Greene, The Boston
Globe, first; John Tlumacki, The Boston Globe, second; and Melissa
Farlow, The Pittsburgh Press, third.
