<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     03-02 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Set 1988 Volume Record; Dollar Down Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange surged closer to pre-crash
levels today, setting a new 1988 record for volume, while the
dollar fell slightly.
   ``Foreign buying and a bullish economy in the United States have
convinced domestic investors to join in,'' said a market analyst
who requested anonymity, adding that the strength of the market has
been surprising.
   ``Latecomers have been trying to catch the bus. I would be
concerned if turnover like today's continued, though, because it
could show that the market is overheating,'' he said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at
25,682.82 points, up 246.92 points, or 0.97 percent from Tuesday's
close. Volume in the first section was 1.7 billion shares, a record
high for this year.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 128.47 yen,
down 0.16 yen from Tuesday's close of 128.63 yen. The dollar opened
today at 128.43 yen.
   A currency dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo, who also
spoke on condition of anonymity, said the dollar was trading in a
narrow range in the absence of major market-moving news.
   Trading on the first section of the exchange totaled 900 million
shares at the end of the morning session, before closing the day
100 million shares higher than the previous 1988 record, set
Tuesday.
   Prior to the October crash, the Nikkei index stood at 25,746.56.
   ``Institutional investors are responding positively to the
favorable outlook for the economic performance of Japanese firms in
this fiscal year,'' said Hiromi Yoneyama, a dealer with Wako
Securities.
   Yoneyama said corporate earnings of major firms were expected to
show better-than-expected results in fiscal 1987, which ends March
31.
</TEXT>
