<2ND_LINE>PM-Wyoming Caucuses,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One for Dole, One Uncommitted _ Wyoming GOP Starts Picking
Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole picked up a delegate and
another was slated uncommitted as Wyoming's GOP presidential
delegation selection process got under way.
   Republicans in two counties met Tuesday to select two of the
state's 18 delegates to the Republican National Convention.
   Most of the rest of the GOP delegates and 13 of the state's 18
Democratic delegates will be selected Saturday, three days before
Super Tuesday.
   Despite the emphasis on campaigning in the South, Wyoming was
getting some attention from the candidates.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee and Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis both planned stops in the state before Saturday's county
conventions. Gary Hart, who is from neighboring Colorado, has
visited.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt bought radio ads in Wyoming, the first
time a candidate has advertised his candidacy over the airwaves.
   None of the Republican candidates were expected in the state,
where Vice President Bush and Sen. Bob Dole were considered the
frontrunners.
   Natrona and Platte counties were the first to allocate
presidential delegates Tuesday, with eight other counties ready to
select their GOP delegates on Saturday.
   The Natrona County delegate, Judy Catchpole, said she was
committed to Dole; the Platte County pick, Natty Dodge, was
uncommitted.
   Weston County Republicans planned to choose their delegate
Friday and Niobrara County party members were to do the same on
March 12.
   The final six presidential delegates will be selected at the
state Republican convention on May 7 in Cheyenne. All 23 Democratic
presidential delegates will be selected Saturday at county
conventions throughout the state.
   Gore already received the support of former Gov. Ed Herschler
and another of the state's five ``super delegates,'' who can remain
uncommitted going into the Democratic National Convention in July.
</TEXT>
