<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Carter-Democrats 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carter-Democrats, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0489, 480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former President Carter Says Democratic Nominee Before Convention
Unlikely</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: To restore first reference to Sen. Sam Nunn, SUB 5th graf,
bgng ``Carter made ...''; to delete Nunn's first name, SUB 8th
graf, bgng ``He said ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PLAINS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter said there's an
even chance that none of the Democratic presidential candidates
will have a lock on the party's nomination before the national
convention in July.
   Carter, who has not endorsed any of the candidates, received a
visit Tuesday from one of the hopefuls, Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri, who characterized the meeting as a non-political call on
``an old friend.''
   ``My hope is that out of the primary and caucus season will come
a clear winner,'' Carter said just one week before 20 states, most
of them south of the Mason-Dixon line, hold primaries and caucuses
with 1,307 delegates at stake.
   ``I'm not sure that's a likelihood now,'' he said.
   Carter made it clear he is not one of those waiting for some
other candidate to enter the race _ a Mario Cuomo, Bill Bradley or
even Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn.
   ``I would not personally favor turning to someone outside the
active candidate group for the nomination,'' said the former
president.
   Carter explained his decision not to endorse any of the party's
contenders, saying ``it is better for us not to take a preferential
position among the Democratic candidates.''
   He said the only Democrat he might have thrown his support
behind was Nunn, who decided against entering the race.
   Carter talked about the Democratic race and Super Tuesday after
meeting at his rambling brick home with Gephardt, one of six
Democratic aspirants for the presidency.
   Gephardt denied he had any political motive for his trip to this
tiny Georgia town Carter put on the map.
   ``I didn't come here to try to be helped on Super Tuesday,''
said Gephardt, who stopped in Georgia on a trip from Williamsburg,
Va., to Columbia, S.C.
   ``I came here today not to enhance my prospects, but to greet an
old friend,'' he said.
   Gephardt, Carter and his wife, Rosalynn, stood on the front walk
of the former president's home at 1 Woodland Road. His hair much
whiter than when he left the White House in January 1981, Carter
wore an open-necked checked shirt, a tweed jacket and khaki pants.
   Asked if he missed all the attention of a political campaign,
Carter laughed and said he and his wife had just returned from
skiing in Colorado.
   But he was also willing to answer questions as long as reporters
had any to ask.
   Carter was careful to say something nice about all the
Democratic candidates, and suggested that any one of them could do
well in the South.
   ``I'm sure Sen. (Albert) Gore (of Tennessee) will have an
advantage among some voters because he's a Southerner,'' said
Carter. The former president's daughter, Amy, has endorsed Jesse
Jackson.
   ``Amy doesn't ask me for counsel,'' he said, when asked if she
had discussed her position with him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
