<1ST_LINE>u p PM-VermontPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0502 03-02 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vermont Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Win in Vermont; Jackson Hails Strong Second-Place
Showing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: To delete ``with'' SUBS 2nd graf, bgng ``Our message ...'';
to correct spelling of ``pronounced'' SUBS 4th graf, bgng ``Still,
the ...''; to correct spelling of ``candidates'' SUBS penultimate
graf, bgng ``But the ... .''</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush and Democrat
Michael Dukakis, on New England home ground, triumphed in Vermont's
``beauty contest'' primary, but Jesse Jackson and Bob Dole had
reason to celebrate as well as the presidential pack headed into
the final days of the Super Tuesday campaign.
   ``Our message continues to win,'' Jackson exulted after
finishing a strong second in Vermont, which has only a tiny black
population. Jackson garnered 26 percent to Dukakis' 57 percent.
   Dole, outspent and out-organized, nonetheless made an impressive
showing, gaining 39 percent to Bush's 49 percent in what his
campaign called the vice president's ``back yard.'' Bush has a
summer home in Maine.
   Still, the vice president pronounced himself pleased.
   ``This win gives us three out of three in New England, and I'm
hopeful we can be as successful this Saturday in South Carolina and
on Super Tuesday,'' said Bush, who was campaigning in Florida.
   No delegates were at stake in the Tuesday primary. Delegate
selection begins at local caucuses next month and representatives
of the Dole campaign said they would work now on organizing for the
caucuses.
   Dukakis, fresh from a weekend win in Maine's Democratic caucus,
was buoyant about his victory.
   ``It's terrific, we're rolling 'em up,'' said the Massachusetts
governor, who was campaigning in Baltimore. With a strong
organization and the endorsement of Gov. Madeleine Kunin, Dukakis
had been expected to do well here.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, who has been Dukakis' chief opponent in
some recent contests, trailed with 8 percent. Gephardt backers said
his poor showing was caused by a lack of spendng in the state by
his national campaign.
   ``Dukakis and Jackson both made a decision to compete,'' said
Lt. Gov. Howard Dean, Gephardt's state chairman. ``You can't
overcome national organizations with just a Vermont organization.''
   Some political observers had predicted a tight race between
Jackson and Gephardt for second place, but Jackson stole the show.
He ran a strong second in the state's largest city of Burlington
and actually beat Dukakis in 27 communities and tied him in two.
   ``We have found the common chord that is linking the American
people,'' said Jackson from his mother's home in Greenville, S.C.
   ``It's putting to rest once and for all that he is candidate for
black people,'' said Burlington Mayor Bernard Sanders, a Jackson
backer. ``We are the whitest state in America. I think it's an
extraordinary showing.''
   In unofficial results, with 100 percent of the state's 262
precincts reporting, Dukakis had 28,244 votes or 57 percent;
Jackson 13,030 votes or 26 percent; Gephardt 3,968 votes or 8
percent; Simon 2,596 votes or 5 percent and Hart 2,052 votes or 4
percent.
   Bush received 23,550 or 49 percent; Dole got 18,636 or 39
percent; former television evangelist Pat Robertson 2,447 votes or
5 percent; Rep. Jack Kemp 1,866 votes or 4 percent. Dropouts Pete
du Pont and Alexander Haig received 794 votes, or 2 percent and 327
votes or 1 percent respectively.
   The Robertson and Kemp campaigns put up little effort in the
state, although Robertson plans to compete in the caucuses.
   ``I really didn't contest it,'' said Robertson, in Orlando, Fla.
``We had virtually no organization in Vermont.''
   In years past, Vermont's primary won national media attention
because of its timing. Candidates could use a victory in the state
to build momentum following a victories in New Hampshire or Iowa.
Or, they could try to repair an image wounded by a loss in either
of those two states.
   But the timing element worked against the state this year.
Because no delegates were being allocated, the candidates
practically ignored the state to concentrate on the mega-delegate
race in the South.
   The primary was part of the state's annual ritual, Town Meeting
Day, when Vermont's voters decided town budgets, road repairs and a
host of other local issues. Turnout was lower than expected, with
just under 100,000 venturing to the polls.
</TEXT>
