<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SuperTuesdayPoll     03-02 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Super Tuesday Poll,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Leads Dole Among Republicans; Dukakis, Jackson Top Dems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush had a nearly 3-to-1 lead over
rival Bob Dole among Republicans likely to vote in Super Tuesday's
16 primaries, while Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson were battling
for the lead in the Democratic contests, according to poll results
published today.
   The vice president held a strong lead in virtually all the 16
states holding primaries next Tuesday, according to the Washington
Post-ABC News poll. He had the support of nearly 60 percent of the
946 likely Republican voters surveyed, while the Kansas senator had
just over 20 percent.
   Former television evangelist Pat Robertson trailed with slightly
more than 10 percent and Rep. Jack Kemp of New York had 5 percent.
   In a survey of 1,121 likely Democratic voters in the 16 primary
states, Jackson had an edge in Mississippi, Georgia, Alabama and
North Carolina and was roughly tied with Dukakis in Arkansas,
Florida, Texas and Virginia.
   Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor, held a strong lead in his
home state, Rhode Island and Maryland. Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore
Jr. led in Tennessee and Kentucky, and Missouri Rep. Richard
Gephardt was ahead in his home state.
   Louisiana voters appeared to be split among Jackson, Dukakis and
Gore, and Oklahoma was a three-way contest among Dukakis, Gore and
Gephardt.
   When the survey was conducted Feb. 17-28, Dole was running even
with Bush only in Missouri and Maryland. In the next-closest states
of Arkansas and Rhode Island, he was a little more than 10
percentage points behind Bush.
   The newspaper said the poll results had ``varying margins of
error,'' but did not provide them.
</TEXT>
