<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Vezzetti     03-02 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Vezzetti,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flamboyant Mayor of Hoboken, N.J., Dies Of Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOBOKEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Thomas Vezzetti, the badly dressed
bootlegger's son who took to the streets with a bullhorn to win
elections and fight the gentrification of this Hudson River city,
died early today. He was 59.
   Vezzetti died of a heart attack at St. Mary Hospital shortly
after midnight, police said.
   Vezzetti, a lifelong bachelor, was said to have been angry
Tuesday night by the outcome of a special election in the 5th Ward.
A councilman who frequently criticized Vezzetti's policies won a
special election over a candidate supported by the mayor.
   Officials said that at about 11 p.m. Tuesday neighbors heard
Vezzetti fall in his apartment and they called for an ambulance.
   City Business Administrator Edwin Chius said City Council would
meet later today to choose a successor to head this city of 42,000.
   Before Vezzetti's election to public office, he had developed a
reputation as an eccentric, sometimes wearing mismatched shoes,
orange pants and a Hawaiian shirt. His face was often unshaven and
he sometimes carried his belongings in two paper bags.
   He also was a political gadfly, showing up at school board and
city council meetings, complaining about the waste of taxpayers'
money.
   He took a bullhorn in 1982 and walked up and down Washington
Street, the city's main artery, to announce he was challenging the
city council president in the next election.
   He won, and then used the tactic against Mayor Steve Cappiello
in 1985, hitting on the theme of stopping yuppies from sweeping the
working and middle class out of the city across the Hudson from
Manhattan.
   ``If you want to stay in Hoboken, vote for me,'' he often said.
   He forced Cappiello into a runoff, and the mayor questioned
Vezzetti's mental competence and wardrobe.
   ``Clothes do not make the man,'' Vezzetti said at a campaign
debate.
   And he beat the three-term mayor in a major upset. Supporters
literally carried him to City Hall.
   His longtime motto was ``It's not that I'm so good. It's just
that they're so bad.''
   Thomas Jefferson Vezzetti and his twin sister, Louise, were born
in 1928.
   He once described his father as a ``bootlegger'' who owned five
saloons. The mayor's mother was an heiress to a peanuts and dried
fruits fortune.
   ``That's where I get my campaign money from,'' Vezzetti once
told New Jersey Monthly.
   ``He was one of a kind,'' said Police Chief George Crimmins.
``It'll be a long time before he can be replaced.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
