<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoBlind     03-02 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No Blind,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Condo Rejects Would-Be Neighbor Because He Is Blind</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEERFIELD BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A condominium association rejected
an attempt by a blind man to move in because of his disability, the
man says.
   ``I was offended, insulted and hurt,'' Larry Tomacek, 35, said
from his parents' home in nearby Delray Beach. ``I'm still trying
to understand this. I'm a responsible adult and generally a good
neighbor.
   ``If I was some scum off the street, I'd understand,'' said
Tomacek, adding that he is mobile.
   But the Kenwick ``B'' Condominium Association of Century Village
sent a letter to apartment owner Donald Finck saying members voted
unanimously to reject Tomacek ``because the applicant ...
unfortunately is blind.''
   ``His presence here would pose some very serious problems to all
the owners here,'' the letter said.
   Tomacek, who supports himself on Social Security and disability
benefits, suffers from retinitis pigmentosa, a degenerative disease
that destroys the retina of the eye cell by cell.
   ``I was very distressed,'' Finck said. ``You can't do that. It's
discrimination. (Tomacek) is entitled to live wherever he wants.''
   Jim Green, legal director for the American Civil Liberties Union
in Florida, and Harry McGee, regional manager for the State
Division of the Blind Services, agreed that the association's
letter indeed was discriminatory.
   Florida law prohibits discrimination in housing on the basis of
physical impairment, Green said.
   Should charges be filed, a conviction on the second-degree
misdemeanor carries a maximum 60-day jail sentence and $500 fine.
   Condo association president David Cohen declined to comment on
the matter.
   Tomacek said he no longer wanted to rent the apartment.
   ``With neighbors like that, who would need enemies?'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
