<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Bangladesh     03-02 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bangladesh,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Gets Under Way In Bangladesh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bands of teen-agers taunted police and
erected barricades in the capital's streets today as a 36-hour
nationwide general strike protesting parliamentary elections got
under way.
   Police and paramilitary troops patrolled the city's streets,
which were nearly empty of traffic, and guarded main intersections.
   Shops and businesses were shuttered and most bus, train and
ferry service was canceled. Government offices were closed because
authorities had declared today and Thursday, the day of the
elections, holidays.
   Major opposition parties called the strike in an attempt to
disrupt the balloting, which they are boycotting and claim will be
rife with fraud. Voters are to choose Bangladesh's fourth
Parliament in 17 years of independence.
   President Hussain Muhammad Ershad announced the elections in
December when he dissolved Parliament in an effort to end an
opposition campaign seeking his ouster that began Nov. 10.
   Ershad, a 58-year-old former army general, seized power in this
nation of 105 million people in a 1982 bloodless coup. He was
elected president in 1986 in balloting the opposition said was
rigged.
   Dhaka was generally calm this morning, but small groups of
youths briefly stoned police in some parts of the city during the
afternoon.
   Four people were reported admitted to Dhaka Medical College
Hospital suffering minor injuries from homemade bombs.
   Youths stopped a municipal garbage truck, smashed it with sticks
and clubs and set it ablaze. Downtown, protesters threw up
barricades of broken bricks, which riot police later removed.
   On a street across from police headquarters, a police van was
briefly stoned, but there was no confrontation between attackers
and police.
   Near the city's main bus station, a band of about 70 youths
marched through the streets chanting ``strike, strike.''
   Police in riot helmets watched from trucks. The government also
called in 9,000 soldiers to guard against election-day violence.
   The mainstream opposition of 21 parties is boycotting the
balloting, but between eight and 102 political parties are vying
for Parliament's 300 seats.
   The two main opposition leaders, Sheik Hasina of the Awami
League and Khaleda Zia, warned that Thursday's vote would trigger
more bloodshed.
   Pre-election violence has claimed at least eight lives,
including that of a candidate who was gunned down by suspected
anti-government protesters.
   During Feb. 10 local elections, more than 100 people were
killed, by government count. The unofficial estimate is as high as
500.
   Since the campaign seeking Ershad's ouster began, at least 25
people have been killed in police clashes with mobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
