<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0536EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-US-Vietnam     03-02 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Vietnam,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Said To Urge Larger American Involvement In Southeast Asia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has begun urging the United States to
play a larger role in Southeast Asia and to work for a settlement
of the conflict in Cambodia, four U.S. scholars said after
returning from two weeks in Vietnam.
   Three said the push indicated that Vietnam was changing and
wanted to improve relations with the United States.
   The fourth said Vietnam was just putting into practice the old
Chinese proverb: ``Using barbarians to control barbarians.''
   The four China specialists spoke at a briefing Tuesday sponsored
by the Henry Luce Foundation, which supported their trip from Dec.
29 to Jan. 11.
   In all, seven American ``China hands'' took part in the trip,
which included stays in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City, once known as
Saigon, and talks with high-ranking Vietnamese officials.
   Helen Chauncey, a professor of history at Georgetown University,
said America's preoccupation with its loss of the Vietnam War and
with the POW-MIA issue was hampering its ability to respond to a
changing Vietnam.
   ``We have to stop letting the past determine our actions in the
region,'' agreed Brantly Womack, a professor of political science
at Northern Illinois University.
   Jonathan Pollack, of the Rand Corporation, was not as optimistic
about the changes in Vietnam or about the prospects for peace in
Indochina.
   Pollack contended that the fighting in Cambodia was still a
``sideshow'' in a larger struggle between the Soviet Union and its
ally Vietnam against China. It will remain the scene of violence
until the larger powers can sort out their problems, he said.
   Frederic Wakeman Jr., a history professor at the University of
California, Berkeley, said he was impressed by changing Vietnamese
society, citing Beatles songs played on a flight from Hanoi and the
raffish tilt of berets on the heads of Communist Party officials.
   ``We were astonished again and again by the candor of the
Vietnamese,'' Wakeman said. ``Intellectuals, officials, party
members were all very open.''
   As a China scholar, Wakeman said, he was particularly interested
in the entrepreneurial spirit of the ethnic Chinese in Ho Chi Minh
City.
   ``We had the sense in Saigon of a commercial economy waiting to
break loose,'' he said.
   Chauncey and Womack said a combination of circumstances has
given America a chance for a new beginning in Vietnam.
   For the first time, Womack said, Vietnamese officials, including
Foreign Minister and Vice Premier Nguyen Co Thach, are talking with
eagerness about leaving Cambodia.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, kicked out the
Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge and installed a puppet government in
Phnom Penh.
   About 140,000 Vietnamese troops remain in Cambodia fighting a
resistance coalition headed by Prince Norodom Sihanouk that is
backed by China, the United States and the free-market countries of
Southeast Asia.
   But last year, Sihanouk split with the coalition and began
direct negotiations with Hun Sen, prime minister of the
Vietnamese-backed government.
   Chauncey said the negotiations, supported by Vietnam, were a
sign that Vietnam wants to end the conflict.
   ``Vietnamese officials told me they want the United States to
play an active role in negotiations to bring peace to Cambodia,''
she said.
   Vietnam also is trying to boost its economy, in which the
average annual income is about $125. As such, it has recognized the
need for foreign exchange and investment from the West.
   Wakeman said he believed Vietnam wants an increased U.S.
presence to counterbalance Chinese interests in Southeast Asia.
   ``In part, it's a very old diplomatic tactic of using the
barbarians to control the barbarians,'' he said.
   Chauncey said the United States must reassert itself in
Southeast Asia.
   ``If it doesn't, we will be left behind in what will be a
realignment of political and economic forces,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
