<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersTalks     03-02 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Talks,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV, Movie Writers Vote Whether To Authorize Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Coast members of the Writers Guild of
America almost certainly voted to authorize a strike against movie
and television producers, a former guild president said.
   The vote was taken Tuesday night in Hollywood by secret ballot,
and results were not expected to be announced until Thursday. The
9,000-member union also includes 2,500 East Coast members who were
scheduled to vote this afternoon.
   The guild's contract expired at 12:01 a.m. Tuesday.
   Union negotiators said a replacement contract offered by the
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers was calculated
to force a strike. The negotiators unanimously urged members to
reject the offer and vote instead for a strike authorization, said
Cheryl Rhoden, a guild spokeswoman.
   She said 2,400 ballots were cast Tuesday night.
   The former guild president, Mel Shavelson, said that judging
from the sentiments he heard expressed during the balloting, ``I
don't think there was any doubt as to what the vote was.''
   While a strike could begin as early as Thursday, Shavelson said
it was unlikely a walkout would be called immediately.
   A strike could have an immediate impact on talk shows and soap
operas, which use scripts daily and without much lead time.
Prime-time programs and feature films would be affected only by a
longer strike.
   Negotiators for the two sides met for just two hours before
quitting Tuesday afternoon.
   The brief meeting followed a 21-hour session that lasted until
7:15 a.m. Tuesday and made progress on ``25 to 30 lesser issues,''
said Herb Steinberg, spokesman for the producers.
   Steinberg and Ms. Rhoden said three major stumbling blocks
remained. The writers are seeking more ``creative rights'' to
control what happens to their scripts and higher payments when
programs are distributed in foreign markets. The producers want to
give writers reduced payments for domestic syndication of one-hour
television programs, a shrinking market.
   The entertainment writers last went on strike three years ago.
The walkout lasted two weeks before writers voted to accept a
package offering them essentially the same terms as one they had
earlier rejected.
   The median annual income for guild writers is $40,000, but about
half of the members are unemployed at any given time, the union
says.
</TEXT>
