<DOCNO> AP880302-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0540EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Norway-WarGames     03-02 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Norway-War Games,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>War Games Dovetail With NATO Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-NATO Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five thousand troops from half the NATO
countries were airlifted to the mountains and valleys of northern
Norway in a show of unity as leaders of the alliance gathered in
Brussels at a major strategy conference.
   U.S. transport planes on Tuesday ferried in the combat units for
the maneuvers, code-named ``Arrowhead Express,'' which climaxes in
two weeks in a battle on snow-covered terrain against an ``enemy''
of 9,500 Norwegian forces.
   The exercise mobilized the Allied Command Europe Mobile Force, a
brigade designed to rush to areas of potential conflict with the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   The maneuvers were clearly intended to serve political more than
military aims, and to demonstrate the cohesion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   ``Our operational role is in peacetime, to show as many flags
with as much visibility as possible in a threatened area to deter
an aggressor,'' said British Maj. Don McLaren.
   ``If we reach the combat stage, we've failed,'' he said in a
telephone interview Tuesday from command headquarters in Bardufoss,
1,000 miles north of Oslo.
   Although not officially tied to the summit, the exercise
dovetails with President Reagan's recent efforts to reassure U.S.
allies of the American commitment to defend Europe at the same time
that it negotiates arms reductions with the Soviet Union.
   The war games also coincide with mounting Norwegian concern that
NATO's flank in the north Atlantic will become more active
following the U.S.-Soviet agreement to dismantle intermediate-range
nuclear weapons.
   ``The INF agreement has made the Norwegian and the Barents Seas
more important,'' Kaare Willoch, chairman of the Norwegian
parliament's foreign affairs committee, said Tuesday.
   The Soviet Union has built the world's greatest concentration of
firepower on the Kola Peninsula adjacent to Norway's northern
border.
   Willoch, a former conservative prime minister, said in an
interview that the Soviet buildup in the north had been going on
for decades and had shown no signs of slackening since the
disarmament accord was signed in December.
   ``The buildup proceeds. It necessitates NATO countermeasures,''
while negotiations continue on further arms reduction accords, he
said.
   The Soviet Northern Fleet, armed with submarine-launched,
long-range nuclear weapons, must pass Norway to reach the Atlantic
fire zone, the closest point of deployment to the United States for
Soviet missiles.
   Norway's northwestern coast, kept ice-free all year by the
warmth of the Gulf Stream, also becomes more attractive to the
Soviets as naval warfare grows in importance in Soviet military
strategy, Norwegian analysts say.
   One war scenario foresees the Soviets slicing off Norway's
remote and nearly unpopulated northern province, challenging NATO's
willingness to respond. That is precisely the kind of action the
Allied Command Europe Mobile Force was formed in 1960 to deter,
McLaren said.
   Arrowhead Express, commanded by Norwegian Vice Admiral Torolf
Rein, involves forces from eight of NATO's 16 countries: the United
States, Canada, West Germany, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Britain and Norway.
   The U.S. role in Arrowhead Express is limited to air support,
since its units are not trained for arctic warfare. Much of the
maneuvering will be done on skis or snowmobiles, McLaren said.
   The force holds maneuvers twice a year, once in Norway or
Denmark and once along an isolated region of NATO's southern flank
in Turkey, Greece or Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0075 </DOCNO>
