<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Journalists     03-02 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Journalists,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Polish Journalists Sentenced To Prison For Spying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court sentenced two Polish
journalists to prison after convicting them of selling information
to Western intelligence agencies, a government spokesman said.
   Mariusz Dastych, 46, and Tadeusz Podwysocki, 56, both formerly
worked for the official government daily newspaper Rzeczpospolita
and were arrested last April on spying charges. Both reported on
Poland's economy.
   A Warsaw military court on Monday sentenced Dastych to eight
years in prison after finding him guilty of selling information
since 1973 to the CIA on Poland's ``socio-political situation,''
government spokesman Jerzy Urban said. The court also fined Dastych
$790 and ordered the confiscation of all his property, said Urban,
speaking at his weekly news conference Tuesday.
   Podwysocki received a 1{-year prison sentence because the court
accepted his defense that he was ``unaware that information he had
communicated was used for intelligence purposes,'' Urban said.
   Podwysocki, one of Poland's best-known economic reporters, also
was barred from working as a journalist for two years, fined $530
and ordered to pay back all the Western currency he had received
for the information. Urban did not specify how much the journalists
received for selling the information.
   Urban said Dastych and Podwysocki had cooperated with
``representatives of another Western intelligence service,'' which
he would not name.
   He refused to confirm or deny reports that the second country
involved was Japan. According to Western press reports, they were
accused of passing trade secrets to Japan.
</TEXT>
