<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-02 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storms Thunder Across Southern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms rumbled across the southern Plains,
unleashing tornadoes, hail as big as baseballs and heavy rain.
   In Texas, two tornadoes touched down near Wichita Falls Tuesday,
along with hail up to 1} inches in diameter, but no injuries or
damage were reported. Baseball-size hail fell at Lake Kickapoo, and
winds gusted to 62 mph at Lake Kemp. More than 3{ inches of rain
fell in six hours in Wichita Falls.
   Hail as big as golf balls fell in southern and eastern Oklahoma.
   A tornado touched down briefly near Orosia, Calif., southeast of
Fresno, but no injuries or damage were reported.
   In Southern California, rain showers were scattered late Tuesday
from the valleys to the coast. Up to 4 inches of snow and winds up
to 35 mph were expected across the area through Thursday morning.
   In Denver, rain changed to snow late Tuesday as a cold front
swept across the central Rockies and central Plains. Snow
advisories were posted for Colorado's Front Range and Wyoming's
southern mountains. One to 4 inches of snow was expected in Denver,
with up to 8 inches possible in the foothills of the Colorado
Rockies. In southeast Wyoming, up to 3 inches of snow could fall by
this afternoon, with up to 6 inches possible in the mountains.
   Snow showers also fell across sections of Michigan, but much of
it was light and there was little accumulation. Freezing rain
caused slippery roads in parts of Lower Michigan.
   Today's forecast called for numerous showers and thunderstorms
across much of Texas, eastern Oklahoma, and the lower and middle
Mississippi Valley, with possibly severe thunderstorms in central
and eastern Texas, extreme southeast Oklahoma, southwest Arkansas
and western Louisiana; rain from Missouri across the Ohio Valley
and in western Pennsylvania; rain or snow showers in Michigan and
northern Illinois; rain changing to snow in northeast Kansas; snow
showers from eastern Colorado across Wyoming to western South
Dakota; showers and a few thunderstorms, with snow in higher
elevations, in western Colorao, Utah and northern Arizona and rain
on the Northwest coast.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s and 70s from
the south Atlantic Coast states to the Gulf Coast, Tennessee and
lower Mississippi valleys and Texas, with a few 80s in southern
Texas; the 60s along the Mexican border of New Mexico and Arizona
and in much of California; the 20s or 30s in northern New England
and parts of New York state and from Michigan to the upper
Mississippi Valley and the High Plains; and in the 40s and 50s
elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees below zero at Massena, N.Y., to 69 degrees at Brownsville,
Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 42 fair; Boston 19 windy; Buffalo 23 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 38 fair; Cincinnati 36 partly cloudy; Cleveland 39
cloudy; Detroit 31 partly cloudy; Miami 59 fair; New York 24 fair;
Philadelphia 27 fair; Pittsburgh 30 fair; Portland, Maine 11 fair;
Washington 31 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 23 snow; Chicago 43 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 64 cloudy; Denver 30 snow; Des Moines 31 fair;
Indianapolis 42 cloudy; Kansas City 49 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul
26 cloudy; Nashville 37 cloudy; New Orleans 55 foggy; St. Louis 45
showers.
   _West: Albuquerque 39 partly cloudy; Anchorage 30 partly cloudy;
Las Vegas 54 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 51 showers; Phoenix 62
partly cloudy; Salt Lake City 40 cloudy; San Diego 53 showers; San
Francisco 49 fair; Seattle 47 drizzle.
   _Canada: Montreal 3 fair; Toronto 23 snow.
