<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mixed against major foreign
currencies in Europe early today. Gold bullion rose.
   Traders in Italy and West Germany said there was very little
activity in exchange markets, continuing a trend of the past few
days.
   The dollar fluctuated within a narrow range during the first
hours of trading and was expected to hold steady throughout the
European session in the absence of any market-related news.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.6875 West German marks, up from 1.6855
   _1.3945 Swiss francs, up from 1.3915
   _5.7135 French francs, up from 5.7065
   _1.8940 Dutch guilders, unchanged
   _1,244.00 Italian lire, down from 1,244.35
   _1.2565 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2570
   The British pound edged down to $1.7743 from $1.7775.
   The dollar eased in Tokyo, closing at 128.47 Japanese yen, down
from Tuesday's close of 128.63 yen. In later London trading today,
the dollar was little changed, at 128.50 yen.
   London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price of
$431.55 a troy ounce, up from $428.70 late Tuesday.
   In Zurich, gold traded at a bid of $431.50, up from $429.50.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $433.96, up
from $433.80.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid of $6.25 a troy ounce,
down from $6.29.
