<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AirplaneDrugs     03-02 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airplane Drugs,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arrested Aboard Plane On Drug Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jetliner returned to Kennedy Airport after a
passenger was found in a lavatory with crack and equipment to burn
it for ``freebasing,'' authorities said.
   The man and a companion who was standing outside were arrested
Tuesday by federal agents who happened to be aboard, said Robert
Stutman, head of the Drug Enforcement Administration's New York
office.
   A flight attendant who smelled ether discovered the man in the
lavatory, along with about a quarter-ounce of crack, a torch, ether
and butane, Stutman said. The man outside also had crack in his
possession, he said.
   ``This could have produced a real tragedy,'' Stutman said.
``Ether is an extremely volatile, explosive substance when it is
near flames.''
   Richard Moskowitz and Jeff Tofler were arrested on charges that
included possession of cocaine and interference with a flight,
Stutman said. They were turned over to the FBI upon landing, he
said.
   About 98 passengers were aboard Eastern Airlines Flight 977,
which left Kennedy at 1:35 p.m. and was scheduled to arrive in
Miami at 4:24 p.m., said Karen Ceremsak, an airline spokeswoman.
   When the pilot learned about the alleged drug activity, he
notified a DEA agent and a U.S. Customs agent who were on board to
attend a trial in Miami, Stutman said.
   The ages and hometowns of the suspects were not immediately
known.
   A powdered form of cocaine, not crack, a potent derivative, is
usually used in freebasing, a process in which the powder is mixed
with ether and then heated so the fumes can be inhaled, Stutman
said.
   He said there was no damage to the aircraft.
</TEXT>
