<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0639EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     03-02 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldier Kills Seven Sleeping Comrades Before Being Shot Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sri Lankan soldier opened fire with
a semi-automatic rifle and killed seven sleeping comrades before he
was shot to death by his commander, military officials said today.
   Nine other soldiers were wounded in the Tuesday night attack at
an army camp next to a steel mill 10 miles southeast of Colombo,
they said.
   The attacker was a member of the People's Liberation Front, an
ultra-nationalist Sinhalese group that has raided several military
camps to steal weapons, the officials said.
   The officials, who by regulation cannot be identified, said the
attack was designed to kill as many soldiers as possible and to
steal weapons. They said all the victims were Sinhalese, the
majority ethnic group that controls the government and military in
Sri Lanka.
   The officials were unable to explain why the assailant risked
making so much noise by gunning down fellow soldiers if the purpose
of the attack was to collect weapons and escape.
   A vehicle had arrived at the scene to enable the attacker to
make his getaway, they said, but the escape was foiled when the
commanding officer heard the shooting, rushed to the scene and
killed the soldier.
   The driver escaped in the vehicle, the officials said.
   Neither the soldier nor his commander was identified, but the
officials said they both served in a signal corps unit.
   According to the officials, similar attacks have occurred in the
past but this was the largest number of soldiers ever killed by a
fellow soldier.
   The government has blamed the People's Liberation Front for the
assassinations of at least 150 government officials and supporters
since July 29, when Sri Lanka signed a peace accord designed to end
a 4-year-old separatist war by Tamil guerrillas.
   The front says the accord makes too many concessions to the
minority Tamils and has vowed to kill anyone who supports the pact.
   Military officials said last winter that front had about 4,000
supporters in the 45,000-man army.
   India mediated the peace accord last summer and it now has
45,000 peackeeping troops in the island.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus and comprise 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people, want a separate homeland, claiming they
are discriminated against by the majority Sinhalese Buddhists.
</TEXT>
