<DOCNO> AP880302-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0709EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Vietnam-MIAs 1stLd-Writethru a0525 03-02 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-MIAs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0525,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hanoi Returns Remains Vietnam Says It Believes Are Of MIAs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with return of remains, details. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam today repatriated what it
believes are the remains of 17 American servicemen listed as
missing in action from the Vietnam war, a U.S. military official
said.
   The Vietnamese also turned over written reports on three other
missing Americans, said Lt. Col. Paul Mather, head of the U.S.
military team that flew to Hanoi to receive the remains.
   The remains were flown to the Army's Central Identification
Laboratory in Honolulu for analysis after a brief turnover ceremony
at Hanoi's Noi Bai Airport.
   The repatriation was the fourth largest since the war ended in
April 1975 with a communist victory over the U.S.-backed South
Vietnam government. The largest was in August 1985, involving 26
sets of remains.
   Earlier reports that 20 remains were to be returned today
resulted from a misunderstanding in communications from Hanoi, said
Mather, the head of the Bangkok office of the U.S. Joint Casualty
Resolution Center.
   The center, based in Hawaii, is entrusted with resolving the
fates of nearly 1,800 Americans listed as missing in action, or MIA.
   Mather said some of the 17 remains and three cases on which
written reports were received were on a list of 70 high priority
cases that U.S. presidential envoy and retired Gen. John W. Vessey
Jr. gave the Vietnamese during his mission to Hanoi last August.
   The United States says that in these so-called ``discrepancy
cases,'' there is strong evidence the Vietnamese know what happened
to the missing men, including photographs of them taken after their
capture.
   Mather said each set of remains was accompanied by a written
report containing such information as the area where the remains
were found, and what people there said about them. He said the
Vietnamese also turned over identification cards and ``dog tags'' _
military identification tags which servicemen wear around their
necks.
   Mather said the remains were placed in metal transfer cases and
loaded onto a C-141 transport plane for the flight to Honolulu. A
U.S. honor guard saluted as each case, draped with a folded U.S.
flag, was loaded during the half-hour ceremony, he said.
   A high proportion of remains returned by Vietnam after a
preliminary analysis are later confirmed by the U.S. Army
laboratory as those of MIAs.
   Mather also announced that the Vietnamese have set March 12 as
the starting date for the next round of ``technical talks'' on MIAs.
   During these talks, which Hanoi has agreed to hold six times
annually, experts on both sides discuss ways of retrieving remains,
locating warplane crash sites and related issues.
   Today's turnover was the third since Hanoi agreed during
Vessey's visit to break a long deadlock and resume efforts to
account for the missing men.
   The United States pledged then to look into Vietnam's own
humanitarian concerns, and an official U.S. medical team flew into
Hanoi today to continue that mission, said the spokesman of the
U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, Ross Petzing.
   It was the fourth visit by a U.S. medical team. The teams have
been studying the plight of disabled war veterans and other
humanitarian cases and made recommendations on how private U.S.
charitable organizations can aid rehabilitation programs.
   Petzing said the team included Dr. Bruce Van Dam, an orthopedic
surgeon at the Walter Reed Army Medical Center in Washington, D.C.;
Frederick Downs, the director of the Prosthetics and Sensory Aids
Service of the Veterans Administration; and Laurence Kerr, the
State Department's desk officer for Vietnam.
   The Vietnamese have said they prefer direct U.S. government aid,
but Washington has refused because of its embargo on aid to protest
Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
