<HEAD>Police Probe Cross Burning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were searching for suspects in the
cross burning near the home of a black couple in a racially
integrated neighborhood.
   ``It was done so quietly that we did not hear a thing,'' Mary
Lomax, 72, said Tuesday. ``Nothing like this has ever happened here
in our lifetime.''
   She said her 19-year-old granddaughter, who lives across the
street, spotted the cross burning Monday night in a lot next to the
home Mrs. Lomax shares with her husband. The cross stood 4{ feet by
6 feet.
   Police said Tuesday they had no witnesses.
   ``It is an out-of-the way neighborhood and it suggests something
local,'' said Sgt. Angus Park. ``We know of no incident that could
have triggered the cross burning.''
   Cross burning is a felony punishable by three years in jail and
a $5,000 fine. According to the Office of Human Rights, the last
cross burning in Howard County occurred in October 1984. Four
juveniles were arrested.
</TEXT>
