<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0757EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Delta-Liability     03-02 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta-Liability,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Attorney Charges Pilot Drug Abuse In Delta Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of the Delta airliner that
crashed at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport in 1985, killing
137 people, had a pattern of ``use and abuse'' of three
tranquilizers, a government lawyer said.
   Attorney Roy Krieger suggested during his opening statement at a
trial to determine liability for the crash that Delta Capt. Edward
M. Connors might have habitually piloted jetliners under the
influence of drugs.
   Krieger told U.S. District Judge David O. Belew Jr., who is
presiding over the non-jury trial, that prescription records will
show Connors took the tranquilizers Dalmane in 1978, Valium in 1982
and 1984 and Stelazine from 1982 to 1985.
   The records will show ``a clear pattern of use and abuse of
these tranquilizers'' over the eight years before the Aug. 2, 1985,
crash, Krieger said.
   ``The conclusion is inescapable,'' Krieger said. ``He must have
been taking them on the days he was flying'' because the
prescription quantities were too large to have been taken only when
he was off duty.
   ``Why should the day of the crash be any different than all the
other days in the previous years that he was taking
tranquilizers,'' Krieger said.
   Delta lawyer John Martin said during a break in the trial that
there is no evidence that Connors was using Stelazine at the time
of the crash. He said too little tissue was recovered from the
crash to run tests for drugs other than alcohol. Those tests were
negative.
   ``The medical experts will show (Stelazine) is a prescription
tranquilizer that would not affect a person's ability to fly
anyway,'' Martin said. ``There are pilots who fly taking
Stelazine.''
   During his opening statement, Martin said negligence on the part
of Federal Aviation Administration and National Weather Service
employees caused Delta Flight 191 to crash.
   ``The crew of 191 found themselves in the wrong place at the
wrong time'' because none of the government employees did their
jobs,'' he said.
   Martin claimed FAA controllers and the weather service failed to
warn the flight crew of the severity of weather at the airport.
   A report by the National Transportation Safety Board concluded
that the crash was caused, in part, by the pilot's decision to fly
the L-1011 widebody jet into a wind shear, a violent downdraft.
   The trial will determine whether the government must pay part of
$91.2 million in claims that Delta's insurers have paid so far in
the crash.
   In December, Belew ruled that about 90 lawsuits filed by
individuals against Delta should be parceled out from federal court
in Fort Worth to other federal courts. About half of those suits
have been settled.
</TEXT>
