<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Besser     03-02 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Besser,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Stooges' `Joe' Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Besser, a rotund member of The Three
Stooges for two years, was found dead of an undetermined illness at
his home, his publicist said. He was 80.
   ``He had been ill for some time and wouldn't even see a
doctor,'' said publicist Jeff Lenburg. Besser's body was found
Tuesday by a relative, Lenburg said.
   ``I go back 50 years with Joe Besser when I played vaudeville
with him,'' said comedian Milton Berle. ``He was one of a kind. He
was very innovative, very creative. He was a darling of a man, very
congenial.''
   Besser joined Moe Howard and Larry Fine from 1956 to 1958 and
was one of several actors to replace Shemp Howard as the third
stooge.
   The Three Stooges specialized in head-knocking, eye-gouging
slapstick, pratfalls and endless buffoonery. The trio made more
than 190 short films and about 50 feature-length films until the
'60s, Lenburg said.
   Besser embraced his role, bouncing off his fellow stooges in a
schtick that distinguised his character.
   No matter how light the slap, Besser's invariable response was a
whining, ``Not so h-a-a-a-a-a-r-d.'' The stooges' preposterousness
elicited from Besser an exasperated, ``Ooooh, you crazy.''
   The original Three Stooges, created in the vaudeville days of
the 1920s, were Morris ``Moe'' Horowitz, who changed his last name
to Howard; his brother Samuel ``Shemp'' Horowitz and Larry
Fineberg, who used the stage name Fine.
   By the early 1930s, Shemp had left in a pay dispute and was
replaced by his brother, Jerome Howard, known as Curly. Curly left
the team in 1946 after suffering a stroke, and brother Shemp came
back to replace him. After Shemp's death in 1955, he was replaced
by Besser, who in turn was replaced in 1959 by Joe De Rita, who
played ``Curly Joe,'' when the trio began making feature films.
   Curly Howard died in 1952. Moe Howard and Fine died in 1975. De
Rita, the last surviving stooge, is 79 and retired, Lenburg said.
   The character of Joe became Besser's trademark and he added to
it in television's ``The Abbott and Costello Show,'' where he
played the mean, whining brat ``Stinky'' who liked to slap Lou
around.
   He appeared on ``The Abbott and Costello Show'' in the 1950s and
'60s, along with regular appearances on ``The Ken Murray Show'' and
``The Joey Bishop Show.''
   Besser made 250 television appearances during his 67-year
career, joking with such comics as Berle and Jerry Lewis. He also
appeared in more than 40 films.
   Before becoming a Stooge, Besser worked as a comedian on
Broadway, on radio and in motion pictures.
   In the 1940s, his portrayal of an exasperated, whining child
earned him a spot in Olsen and Johnson's long-running Broadway
show, ``Sons o' Fun,'' a sequel to their ``Hellzapoppin.''
   Besser called his association with the Stooges ``the happiest
years of my life in show business.'' He was on hand in 1983 when
The Three Stooges were awarded a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame.
   Besser is survived by his wife of 56 years, Ernie. Funeral
arrangements were pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0091 </DOCNO>
