<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pinochet-Bombs     03-02 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pinochet-Bombs,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet: Bombs at Airport Part Of Assassination Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet said a chain
of bombs found at the end of an airport runway were planted by
leftist extremists who planned to assassinate him by destroying his
plane.
   Authorities disclosed late Monday that they had discovered six
homemade bombs loaded with plastic explosives and shrapnel at the
city airport of La Serena on the Pacific coast 300 miles north of
Santiago.
   Attached to each bomb were about 300 sticks of dynamite,
according to a communique issued by the Civil Aviation office.
   The bombs were buried at the western end of the runway and
connected to a 2,000-foot-long detonating cable that ran to a
ravine beside the airport.
   The explosives were discovered on Saturday, the communique said.
   Pinochet was to fly to La Serena on Jan. 29 to appear at an
agricultural fair, but canceled the visit at the last minute.
   On Tuesday, during a tour of southern Chile, he told reporters
there was evidence the bombs were planted in anticipation of his
visit.
   ``They knew I was going to the north and prepared the explosive
material that was found,'' he said during a stop in the town of
Maullin, 700 miles south of the capital. His remarks were carried
by Santiago radio stations.
   He said it was only by chance that he did not travel to La
Serena. ``There were a series of problems that obliged me to stay
in Santiago,'' he said.
   In September 1986, Pinochet survived an ambush of his motorcade
by a commando of the pro-communist Manuel Rodriguez Front, the
country's main lefitst guerrilla organization. Five of his
bodyguards were kiilled in the attack with machine-gun and rocket
fire.
   Pinochet, commander of the army, seized power in a 1973 coup
that toppled the elected government of Marxist President Salvador
Allende.
</TEXT>
