<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby M,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Accepts Baby M Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Beth Whitehead-Gould and her former husband
will reportedly receive up to $40,000 in a settlement with the
agency that brokered her contract to act as a surrogate mother in
the Baby M case.
   The agreement, signed in Manhattan by U.S. District Judge Pierre
N. Leval, dismisses the case without costs or attorneys' fees, but
does not reveal terms of the settlement.
   However, it was reported early last month that the Infertility
Center of New York and its founder, Noel Keane, agreed to pay the
couple $30,000 to $40,000.
   Keane, reached Tuesday at his law office in Dearborn, Mich.,
said only that ``attorneys' fees would have been much more'' than
his payment to the couple.
   The lawyer for Mrs. Whitehead-Gould, Joel D. Siegal of Newark,
N.J., did not return a telephone call Tuesday.
   Mrs. Whitehead-Gould and Richard Whitehead, her husband at the
time the contract was signed, had charged in a lawsuit that the
Infertility Center and Keane committed fraud in the Baby M contract.
   The suit questioned whether Mrs. Whitehead-Gould was properly
counseled before becoming a surrogate mother.
   After being accepted by the center, Mrs. Whitehead-Gould signed
a contract with a Tenafly, N.J., couple, William and Elizabeth
Stern.
   Under the arrangement, Mrs. Whitehead-Gould was to accept
$10,000 to become pregnant through artificial insemination with
Stern's sperm, and then relinquish the baby to the couple.
   However, after the baby was delivered, Mrs. Whitehead-Gould
launched a long, but ultimately unsuccessful, campaign to keep the
baby girl, now nearly 2 years old and living with the Sterns.
</TEXT>
