<DOCNO> AP880302-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0843EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Anti-Semitism     03-02 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Anti-Semitism,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Acknowledges Anti-Semitic Excesses Of 1968</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today acknowledged
``manifestations of anti-Semitism'' in a 1968 purge of
intellectuals and liberals that forced thousands of Jews out of the
Communist party, government and academia.
   An article in the Communist party daily Trybuna Ludu said
innocent people were harmed merely for advocating reform, but it
added that ``the predominant majority of party and state activists
had no part in anti-Semitism.''
   Addressing the 20th anniversary of the March 1968 event, the
1{-page article said some conservative, nationalist party factions
``took advantage of the Jewish ancestry'' of some of their
political rivals.
   ``Injustice was done to many people of Jewish descent as they
were removed from political and professional positions,
irrespective of their views and conduct,'' the paper said.
   But, it added, all the people in the conservative faction in the
intra-party struggle were not anti-Semitic, and some actively
disassociated themselves from anti-Semitism.
   About 9,000 Jews lost positions in the party, government,
academia and other official institutions in the purge. An estimated
12,000 to 20,000 Jews emigrated, the majority of the Jewish
population that remained after the Nazi Holocaust.
   The first word that the party was going to issue a revised
history of the 1968 ``anti-Zionist'' purges came at the end of
January in a speech by a Polish historian in Jerusalem.
   Two weeks ago, the party weekly Polityka printed a chronology of
the events with a critical introduction. But the Trybuna Ludu
article, which was reported by the state-run news agency PAP and
television, has the authority of an official party statement.
   Speaking more generally about the persecution of liberals at the
time, the party paper said, ``Identification of the pro-reformatory
movement with revisionist and anti-socialist movements was a
mistake on the part of the leadership.''
   It said the party leadership failed to make contact with the
leading intellectuals who made ``rational proposals of
democratization and who sought a dialogue with the authorities''
while recognizing the authority of the party.
   Discrimination against Jews, in the guise ``anti-Zionism,''
began after Israel's victory in the June 1967 Middle East war. But
it accelerated sharply in 1968.
   Before World War II, Poland was home to more than 3.5 million
Jews _ more than half the world's Jewry. There are now believed to
be between 7,000 and 15,000 Jews, with not a rabbi among them.
   ``All the obscenities of the March (1968) propaganda campaign
have been repeated, all of them,'' said Adam Michnik, a prominent
opposition activist and historian who was a student leader in 1968
and a chief target of anti-Semitic attacks.
   ``What has been done is nothing but cosmetics,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   A leading party theoretician and journalist, Ludwik Krasucki,
said on Polish television Tuesday that the party's attempts to
reconsider the history of the period were vital.
   He expressed hope that with a thorough re-examination of the
period, in all its aspects, ``this chapter, which nevertheless
can't be forgotten, shall once and for all be closed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0847EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Delvalle 1stLd-Writethru a0451 03-02 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delvalle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Delvalle Defies Noriega, Sheds Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 5, In time, to show comparison with Aquino</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a week ago, Eric Arturo Delvalle was
reviled in much of the hemisphere as a figurehead president of
Panama, a tool of the country's military establishment, a man who
gave Panama's political system a constitutional facade.
   But, in a single stroke, Delvalle has carried out a remarkable
political rehabilitation. He has been transformed from Delvalle the
Meek to Delvalle the Martyr.
   Much of the Reagan administration's strategy toward Panama over
the past few days has been built around Delvalle and his claim to
be Panama's constitutional president.
   He is an integral part of the administration's ``chipmunk
strategy'' toward Panama _ keep gnawing away at Panama's economy,
at military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega's claim to legitimacy
and his reputation and base of support at home and abroad.
   In time, the administration hopes, Noriega will wake up, find
his hold on power has evaporated and depart his homeland quietly.
The administration wanted a democratic symbol around whom
Panamanians could rally, and found one in Delvalle, the man who
defied Noriega, the armed forces chieftain, political heavyweight
and, according to a federal indictment, cocaine smuggler. For now,
at least, Delvalle has the earmarks of a Panamanian version of
Corazon Aquino, a democratic symbol around whom opposition to
Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos coalesced.
   Delvalle's image as a powerless front man dates back to when he
took office in the fall of 1985. Noriega was unhappy with the
president at the time, Nicolas Ardito Barletta, because of an
independent streak, and he forced Barletta from office.
   Delvalle was sworn in as president under the most unpromising of
circumstances. In effect, he had to behave according to Noriega's
wishes or he would end up like Barletta. He carried that burden for
two years.
   The image he projects nowadays is quite different. A certain
mystique has developed around Delvalle since he tried to fire
Noriega and wound up out of office himself. Rather than flee the
country after his dismissal, he has gone into hiding, issuing
proclamations to his countrymen, making videotaped messages and
frustrating efforts by Noriega's forces to locate him.
   One of his chief allies these days is Gabriel Lewis, a former
ambassador to Washington who is now a captain of the anti-Noriega
campaign in exile.
   To hear Lewis tell it, Delvalle had wanted to break with Noriega
for five months but was reluctant to do so because of ``confusing''
signals from Washington.
   Lewis said Tuesday that Noriega has been suspicious of
Delvalle's intentions for some time and kept telling the president,
``Don't act against me because the gringos are behind me.''
   This was based on what Noriega felt were reassuring visits by
emissaries from Washington, including Assistant Defense Secretary
Richard Armitage.
   One turning point occurred in early January, Lewis said, when a
gathering of Panamanian opposition leaders met in Miami and
Delvalle sent an envoy.
   ``The emissary told us that if we gave him (Delvalle) assurances
that we would support him, he was ready to act and dismiss
Noriega,'' Lewis said.
   ``We sent him back a message,'' Lewis said. ``We have heard that
many times. We want deeds and not words. If you fire Noriega and
his cronies, we will give you support.''
   Contacts with Lewis and other Noriega opponents continued, with
some messages being passed by Delvalle's dentist in Florida.
Another turning point took place in early February when two Florida
grand juries charged that Noriega was a key figure in an
international drug smuggling ring.
   With an end to the ambiguity in Washington's position, the
opposition front suggested that Delvalle come here to announce his
break with Noriega before the Organization of American States.
Delvalle agreed and arrangements were made.
   But then Delvalle had second thoughts, reasoning that firing
Noriega at OAS headquarters in Washington might be seen ``as acting
on instructions from the United States,'' Lewis said. But was
Delvalle getting cold feet?
   At Lewis' instigation, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., called
Delvalle to give him encouragement. On Feb. 17, Delvalle was in
Miami and invited Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams to
visit him.
   If Delvalle was ousted for trying to fire Noriega, Abrams
assured him, the United States would support him as Panama's
constitutional president, Lewis said. Eight days later, in an
important moment in Panama's tumultuous history, Delvalle fired
Noriega only to be dismissed himself hours later by Noriega's
allies in the National Assembly.
   Lewis said the turn of events was foreseen in an 18-point
anti-Noriega conspiracy crafted by the opposition coalition.
   He said the program is up to point six. Twelve to go.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
