<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Gromyko     03-02 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Gromyko,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministry Disputes Gromyko's Memoirs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry said today that many aspects
of Soviet President Andrei Gromyko's memoirs dealing with
Chinese-Soviet relations are false.
   ``Many of the recollections and descriptions in Gromyko's
memoirs relating to the history and present state of Chinese-Soviet
relations do not square with the facts,'' ministry spokeswoman Li
Jinghua told a weekly news briefing.
   She refused to elaborate on what elements in the memoirs China
disputed.
   The New York Times, quoting an advance copy of Gromyko's
two-volume book ``Memoir,'' said Gromyko claimed Chinese leader Mao
Tse-tung proposed in 1958 that the Soviet Union help lure U.S.
troops into China and attack them there with nuclear weapons.
   Gromyko wrote that Mao was expecting a U.S. attack on mainland
China because of Washington's support for the Nationalist Chinese
government on Taiwan and tensions over the tiny islands of Quemoy
and Matsu in the Taiwan Strait.
   Gromyko said in ``Memoir'' that he rejected the plan, proposed
while he was on a secret August 1958 visit to China, according to
the Times.
   Ms. Li confirmed that Gromyko, then Soviet foreign minister,
visited China in 1958. She refused to comment on the purpose of the
trip or the content of his talks with Mao.
   At the time, the Soviet Union had close ties with the younger
communist state and provided it with economic and military aid. The
two countries split bitterly a few years later over ideological and
strategic differences.
   ``Memoir'' is due to be distributed soon to Soviet bookstores.
It covers nearly 50 years of Soviet diplomacy, including relations
with nine U.S. presidents from Franklin D. Roosevelt to Ronald
Reagan, the Times said.
</TEXT>
