<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CarKids     03-02 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Car Kids,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Pleads Guilty to Reduced Charges In Deaths Of Two Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old woman could be sentenced to
up to four years in jail and fined $10,000 in the deaths of her two
children last summer in a locked, sun-baked car.
   Lisa Shields, of White Township, pleaded guilty Tuesday to
reduced charges in the deaths of Kristle, 3, and Calvin Shields, 1.
   Washington County Judge John Bell accepted pleas to two counts
of endangering the welfare of children, and Indiana County District
Attorney William Martin agreed to drop two counts of involuntary
manslaughter. No sentencing date was set.
   Mrs. Shields' 24-year-old husband, John Shields, goes on trial
March 14 on charges of involuntary manslaughter and endangering the
welfare of children.
   Mrs. Shields stopped her trial, which began Monday, and pleaded
guilty after her husband testified that he had agreed to care for
the children and had locked them in the car while his wife slept.
   Shields said he hid the car in which the children were sleeping
in a sunny area at the rear of a farmhouse after a friend told him
a warrant had been issued for his arrest because the car had no
license plates and was not registered.
   He said he closed the car windows ``because it was supposed to
rain'' and locked the doors because ``I didn't want anyone taking
my kids.''
   Shields said he left the children in the car because the house
was unheated and had broken windows.
   Earlier Tuesday, Dr. William Kenney, a Penn State University
assistant professor of physiology, said the temperature in the car
probably reached 150 degrees, which the children could have
withstood for 17 minutes.
   Both parents have been in jail since their arrests shortly after
the children's deaths in August.
</TEXT>
