<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorthSubpoenaed     03-02 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Subpoenaed,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accused Drug Trafficker's Lawyer Says Oliver North Will Plead
Fifth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer seeking Lt. Col. Oliver North's
testimony in a drug trial says the ex-National Security Council
aide will refuse to answer questions by invoking his constitutional
right against self-incrimination.
   Ronald C. Dresnick, who obtained subpoenas last week against
North and two other figures in the Iran-Contra affair, said Tuesday
he had not decided whether to pursue his bid to compel North to
appear March 15 in U.S. District Court in Detroit.
   However, the attorney said he believed North could provide
information to support his claim that his client, Frank Ivan Turek
Correa, of Colombia, was a victim of entrapment or other government
misconduct.
   Dresnick said he wanted to question North about Michael Palmer,
a former airline pilot whom Dresnick claimed was being protected
from prosecution.
   Palmer accompanied Correa and other defendants on an airplane
that allegedly carried drugs from South America to Michigan, the
attorney said. But Dresnick said he believed Palmer was allowed to
go free because the government wanted to conceal his alternate role
in shipping food and clothing to the Contra rebels trying to topple
the government of Nicaragua.
   Dresnick, in court papers seeking to subpoena North, said the
DC-6 airplane allegedly used to ship the drugs to Michigan was once
owned by Vortex Air International. Palmer is a former executive
with both Vortex and Southern Air Transport, which Dresnick called
a CIA-backed operation.
   ``I believe the government knows about Palmer and ... must be
aware that Palmer was involved in drug smuggling,'' Dresnick said.
   Palmer also has been subpoenaed to testify in Detroit, but his
whereabouts are unknown, Dresnick said. The attorney said he was
forced to subpoena North because of the government's refusal to
produce Palmer.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Donaldson acknowledged Tuesday
that Palmer was not included in a Sept. 24, 1987, indictment naming
Correa and seven other defendants. He said the government had no
interest in North's testimony and declined further comment.
   Dresnick said Barry Simon, a Washington attorney representing
North, told him by telephone Monday that his client ``indicated he
will take the Fifth Amendment.''
   ``If that's all that's going to happen, it's a little pointless
to drag him out (to Detroit) to say that,'' Dresnick said.
   Simon, contacted Monday night, had declined to say whether North
would appear in Detroit and would not answer any other questions.
</TEXT>
