<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chad-Libya     03-02 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chad-Libya,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Chadian Claim Of Imminent Libyan Offensive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,000 Libyan soldiers have
entered northwestern Sudan to launch an offensive against Chad, the
government radio of Chad said.
   N'djamena radio said the troops joined thousands of other
soldiers already stationed in Sudan's Darfour province ``with the
complicity of the Khartoum authorities.'' The report Tuesday night
was monitored in Abidjan.
   The column included regular soldiers from the Libyan army as
well as mercenaries, the radio said. It added that Libyan leader
Col. Moammar Gadhafi was planning an attack.
   Chad and Libya have been observing a cease-fire in their war
over the disputed Anzou strip, a mineral-rich area that lies
between the two countries. The cease-fire was arranged by the
Organization of African States last September.
   Chad frequently has accused Libya of using Sudan to launch
attacks against it.
   ``As for Khartoum and its government, Chad reiterates its appeal
for a sense of responsibility to avoid turning the Sudanese
territory into a powder keg and an aggression base against a
neighboring and brotherly country. Otherwise, Chad will assume its
responsibility,'' the radio said.
   A special Organization of African Unity committee is to meet in
Dakar, Senegal, on April 10 to negotiate a settlement in the
Chad-Libya conflict.
</TEXT>
