<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     03-02 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Relative Says Marcos' Cancer Ruled Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deposed President Ferdinand Marcos
said his doctors once suspected he had cancer but surgery proved
the diagnosis wrong, an uncle of President Corazon Aquino reported
today.
   Rep. Francisco Sumulong said through a spokesman that Marcos
told him of the preliminary diagnosis when the two men met in
Hawaii in early February. He said Marcos had thyroid surgery in
October, after which doctors ruled out cancer.
   On Tuesday, the Peoples Journal Tonight quoted Sumulong as
saying that Marcos was in declining health and may be suffering
from cancer. A Marcos spokesman in Honolulu denied the report in
the Manila newspaper.
   Sumulong and Mrs. Aquino's cousin, Rep. Egmidio Tanjuatco, met
separately with Marcos earlier this year in Hawaii, where the
former president has lived since he was ousted in a
military-civilian revolt in February 1986.
   Marcos spokesman Leonie Tan confirmed the meetings but denied
that the former president had used his health to strike any deals
with the Aquino government for his return.
   ``He's in excellent health,'' Tan said. ``He has regular medical
check-ups and definitely does not have cancer.''
   Mrs. Aquino said in Manila on Tuesday that before Marcos would
be allowed to return he must return billions of dollars he
allegedly took from the country he ruled for 20 years.
   Marcos repeatedly has denied stealing money from the
Philippines, and Tan said he had not offered to pay any money back.
   ``No deal has been struck, indeed, not a single item on the
agenda has been decided,'' Tan said.
   It is not known when negotiations for Marcos return will start,
``but the desire from both sides is that talks begin immediately,''
Tan said.
   Marcos lives with his wife, Imelda, in a mansion in the Makiki
Heights section of Honolulu. Both have frequently expressed their
desire to return to the Philippines, but cannot because Mrs. Aquino
revoked their passports shortly after assuming the presidency.
</TEXT>
