<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WorkingYouths     03-02 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Working Youths,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>True Light Church Members Fined for Violating Child Labor Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge rebuked Shiloh True Light
Church of Christ for exploiting children and cited church members
for contempt of court for violating federal child labor laws.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Potter also ordered two companies
owned and operated by church members to pay $203,272 to cover a
federal investigation and litigation expenses and to pay employees
back wages and interest.
   The actions Tuesday further set back the church's campaign to
stop what it calls government interference with its religious
beliefs.
   Potter ruled that church members and the two companies _ McGee
Brothers Co. Inc. of Union County and Wendell's Woodwork Inc. of
Mint Hill _ violated his October 1987 order to obey federal child
labor laws.
   True Light families educate their children at home. The church
also sponsors a job-training program that gives youths the
opportunity to earn money while learning such trades as
bricklaying, woodworking and sewing.
   Church members acknowledged during the trial they used their
children, some as young as 9, at construction sites and in
workshops where they carried bricks, laid foundations and more
recently, operated forklifts and power saws. They said they had
been doing that for at least 100 years.
   In October, Potter ordered children to stop working for the
companies. When the owners of the companies continued the program
for the church, the Labor Department asked they be found in
contempt.
   In separate judgments, Potter ordered both companies again to
obey the laws and warned that McGee Brothers would be fined $10,000
and Wendell's Woodwork $5,000 for each day the companies remain in
contempt of his order.
   In addition, Potter said Wendell's two owners _ Wendell Long and
Herbert Long _ would be fined $500 each per day that they remained
in contempt of his order. The five brothers who own McGee Brothers
face fines of $1,000 per day each if they remain in contempt.
   Potter also ordered McGee Brothers to pay $133,890 in back wages
and interest to employees who had not been paid minimum wages and
for overtime work.
   Calls to both companies' offices and the offices of their
attorneys for comment were not returned.
   ``We feel like our freedom of religion and freedom of worship
has been violated,'' said Rommie Purser, the church's minister.
``We just plan to go on to the Supreme Court and see if we aren't
being denied freedom of worship.''
   In a January trial, the Labor Department charged the owners of
the two companies _ all of whom are members of the church _ with
violating the federal statute against child labor.
   The judge wrote in his 58-page opinion that the children
employed ``are children doing adult's work, and regardless of the
label defendants have attached to them, i.e. `trainees in Shiloh
Vocational Training Program,' they are manifestly being exploited
by defendants in this case, whether or not they proclaim their
purpose to be in furtherance of their religious beliefs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Kidnap 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0521,0830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scandinavians Discuss Their Captivity, Leave Lebanon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs to UPDATE with freed UN workers departing
Cyprus for Zurich; picks up 9th graf pvs: `Stening said...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Scandinavian U.N. relief workers
freed from 25 days in captivity said today that their Moslem
abductors moved them often, did not reveal their identities and
treated them well.
   Swede Jan Stening, 44, and Norwegian William Jorgensen, 58, who
were freed by their abductors Tuesday night, made the comments at a
packed news conference at a hotel in Christian east Beirut.
   ``We were very well treated during the whole period of
captivity,'' said Stening. Jorgensen said Stening was speaking for
``both of us.''
   Stening said neither of them had any idea about the identity of
their captors, their motives or their demands.
   ``All our guards were masked,'' Stening said. ``We changed
locations seven or eight times. We never knew where we were held at
any time.''
   ``We were held together ... Both of us were blindfolded at the
beginning for an hour or so but then the blindfolds were removed
and we were allowed to talk freely to each other,'' Stening said.
``We were moved from one location to another at night and in the
trunks of the cars,'' Stening added.
   He said their captors ``interrogated us in a polite manner,
asking such questions as the names of countries we worked at and
the kind of jobs we had.''
   After the news conference, the former hostages left Lebanon in a
U.N. helicopter from Christian east Beirut for Larnaca, Cyprus.
They then departed Larnaca for Zurich, Switzerland, aboard a
regular Swissair flight for their journey home.
   Stening said four gunmen kidnapped them near south Lebanon's
provincial capital of Sidon as they were driving in a U.N. car from
their base in the southern port of Tyre to Beirut on Feb. 5.
   Asked whether either one could tell if the kidnappers were
Palestinians or Lebanese, judging by their accent, Stening said in
English: ``No. We haven't the slightest idea. I don't know Arabic.''
   The two worked for the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, which cares
for 280,000 Palestinian refugees in Lebanon.
   Jorgensen said ``yes'' when asked whether he would be willing to
return to work for the agency in Sidon after their ordeal.
   John Fennessey of Ireland,the agency's acting director, told
reporters at the news conference that the two former captives
``wish to join their families as soon as possible and we're going
to fulfill that'' request.
   The first word about the release came in a handwritten Arabic
statement delivered to a Western news agency in Beirut late Tuesday.
   It was accompanied by a picture showing the two men. It said
after they were ``proved innocent, they were released.''
   The statement did not say what they had been accused of, but in
earlier statements the group claimed the men were involved with the
intelligence service of an unidentified foreign power. U.N.
officials blamed the abductions on Palestinians acting individually
for personal, not political, motives.
   The kidnappers of U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, who
was abducted in south Lebanon Feb. 17, said in a statement released
Tuesday they would put him on trial. They accused Higgins of
working for the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency.
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth, which claimed
Higgins' abduction, said Israel's crackdown on anti-occupation
Palestinian riots in the West Bank and Gaza Strip and the Middle
East trip of U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz ``make us
more determined to try this criminal, Higgins.''
   Both the United Nations and the United States have denied that
Higgins, who served with the U.N. peacekeeping force in south
Lebanon, was a CIA spy.
   Reporters in Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut, said the two
Scandinavians were turned over by their abductors at 8 p.m. Tuesday
to Palestine Liberation Organization representative Salah Salah.
   They were then driven to Beirut by the militia of leftist Sunni
Moslem leader Mustafa Saad, who controlled the city since the 1975
outbreak of the Lebanese civil war.
   Higgins, 43, was abducted near south Lebanon's ancient port of
Tyre. He heads a 76-man U.N. observer group that monitors truce
violations on the Lebanon-Israel border under a 1949 armistice
agreement.
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth is believed to be
made up of pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems. It previously claimed
responsibility for kidnapping 12 Lebanese Jews in west Beirut and
said it killed eight of them.
   In all, 23 foreigners are missing after being kidnapped in
Lebanon since March 1985. They are nine Americans, four Frenchmen,
three Britons, two West Germans, an Italian, an Irishman, an Indian
and two unidentified men.
   Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
