<HEAD>Newspaper Poll Shows Robertson Strength Among SC Southern Baptist
Ministers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper poll of Baptist ministers in South
Carolina shows former television evangelist Pat Robertson with a
plurality of support in the influential group, despite its
theological differences with the Republican presidential candidate.
   Robertson has said he has to win South Carolina's Republican
primary Saturday, three days before the Super Tuesday primaries in
other mostly Southern states. About 700,000 of South Carolina's 3
million people are Southern Baptists, with about 2,000 ministers.
   A poll conducted last weekend by The Atlanta Journal and The
Atlanta Constitution showed Robertson with the support of 31
percent of the ministers who plan to vote Saturday.
   Vice President George Bush was second at 24 percent, followed by
17 percent for Kansas Sen. Bob Dole and 10 percent for New York
Rep. Jack Kemp.
   Although Robertson is a former Southern Baptist minister _ he
stepped down as he began his presidential campaign _ he comes from
a charismatic branch of the denomination, believing, among other
things, in faith-healing and speaking in tongues. Most of the
fundamentalist members of the denomination reject such teachings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Days Before Primary, SC Counties Struggle to Man Precincts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Republican party officials say the
large turnout expected for Saturday's presidential primary is
stretching their manpower to the limits.
   The party still is looking for volunteers to help man the polls
and will probably have to combine some precincts, officials said.
   ``Any time you try to man 1,800 precincts with volunteers, it's
a lot of work,'' said state Republican Party Executive Director
Tony Denny. ``Some counties have got it licked and are in good
shape, others are struggling and trying to find volunteers during
the last minute.
   ``But I think we'll get the precincts open.''
   The largest primary race the GOP has held in the state came in
the 1980 presidential campaign, which drew about 145,000 voters,
Denny said.
   He is anticipating a turnout of about 175,000 Saturday. Denny
said regular June primary elections never have drawn more than
approximately 60,000 voters statewide.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Texas Teachers Group Drops Simon, Endorses Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texas State Teachers Association has
dropped its endorsement of Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, dealing
another blow to a presidential campaign that a Simon official said
has been misconstrued as dead in the South.
   The TSTA, Tuesday switched to Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
as its candidate in next Tuesday's Texas Democratic presidential
primary. TSTA, with 95,000 members is the state's largest teacher
organization.
   ``While Sen. Simon's strong national record on education
prompted our endorsement, his decision not to campaign in Texas
forced us to reassess our position,'' TSTA President Charles Beard
said at a news conference.
   Simon announced last week he does not have sufficient money to
mount full campaigns in the Super Tuesday states, including Texas.
But Bob Krueger, Simon's Texas chairman, said Tuesday that Simon is
running in Texas and expects to earn some delegates.
   Simon will campaign in Texas on Monday and Tuesday, according to
Krueger.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robertson To Hit Spending Ceiling In South Carolina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson apparently will be the only
one of the four Republican presidential candidates to hit the legal
spending limit for Saturday's South Carolina primary, campaign
officials say.
   About 25 percent of the money Robertson is spending in South
Carolina will go into television advertising, which includes a 30
minute television ad expected to air Thursday or Friday night in
Greenville, Charleston and Columbia markets, said Kerry Moody,
Robertson's national deputy press secretary.
   The bulk of the money has gone into field organization efforts,
including distribution of 200,000 tapes titled ``Pat Robertson:
What I Will Do as President.''
   In New Hampshire, Robertson sent more than 200,000 tapes, and in
last week's South Dakota race, he sent 206,585 tapes.
   Robertson also spent the legal limits in Iowa and New Hampshire.
The limit set by the Federal Election Commission for South Carolina
is $916,099.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Files To Get on Hoosier Primary Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson has qualified to be on the
ballot for Indiana's May 3 Democratic presidential primary.
   Jackson supporters Tuesday submitted the required ballot
petitions to the secretary of state's office. At least 500
signatures from each of the state's 10 congressional districts are
required to qualify for the statewide ballot.
   Jackson became the fifth Democrat to earn a spot on the ballot.
Also competing for the 79 delegate votes available through the
primary are Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, Sen. Albert Gore of
Tennessee, Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts and Sen. Paul
Simon of Illinois.
   Jackson finished third in the 1984 primary behind then Colorado
Sen. Gary Hart and former Vice President Walter Mondale.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas and Rep. Jack Kemp of
New York have filed for the Republican primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Roemer To Announce His Choice For President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov.-elect Buddy Roemer, who is expected
to endorse Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., says he will soon
announce his choice for the Democratic presidential nomination.
   ``I'd tell you now if the media wasn't here,'' Roemer joked when
asked Tuesday about his choice by a class of high school students
in Baton Rouge. ``I'll make an announcement in a joint news
conference later this week.''
   ``He'll make the announcement Thursday morning, I believe at 9
a.m.,'' an aide told reporters.
   Gore also plans a 9 a.m. news conference Thursday ``to announce
a major statewide endorsement,'' according to his campaign
officials.
   Other presidential candidates are planning swings through
Louisiana prior to the March 8 Super Tuesday presidential primaries
and caucuses in 20 states and American Samoa.
</TEXT>
