<HEAD>Precede TAMPA, Fla.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Vows He Won't `Sit Out There Unprotected' As Dole
Attacks
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with Bush comment today; pick up 3rd graf pvs
bgng ``But when...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, buoyed by
polls showing him with a comfortable lead in the South, said today
no candidate can win the nomination without winning on Super
Tuesday.
   ``You cannot design a strategy to be president of the United
States without doing well in the Super Tuesday states,'' Bush said
at a breakfast with supporters here at the start of a campaign day
that will take him to Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana and South
Carolina.
   Bush said Tuesday he wants to keep ``a rather high plane'' in
the closing days of the Super Tuesday campaign.
   But when asked about a television advertisement in which Dole
attacks him on the Iran-Contra affair, Bush told reporters: ``We'll
see whether it helps him, but I think I have every right to set the
record straight. You ought not to be surprised if you see some
comparative ads.
   ``You know, we're not going to sit out there unprotected,'' he
added.
   After a swing through South Florida on Tuesday, Bush planned to
breakfast today with senior citizens in Pinellas County, then head
on to Mississippi and Louisiana campaign events.
   Bush said that he is confident but not cocky about the campaign
for the March 8 Super Tuesday of 20 primaries and caucuses, most in
the South. A Washington Post-ABC poll released today gave him a 3-1
lead over Dole.
   ``Two weeks ago yesterday, the polls (in New Hampshire, where he
won the primary) showed me on the canvas; and the voters said
different. I'm not going to get overconfident (because polls show
him leading in the South),'' said Bush.
   The vice president campaigned Tuesday with former Sen. Barry
Goldwater, the 1964 Republican presidential nominee from Arizona,
and Florida Gov. Bob Martinez.
   In recent days, Dole has made a point of saying he is the only
candidate ``tough enough'' to deal with the problems a president
faces.
   Bush replied with an appearance that played up his combat
record. When he arrived at the Tampa airport, a Grumman Avenger
plane, the same model he flew during World War II, had been brought
from a nearby air museum. He climbed into the cockpit.
   Later, Bush drove a paving machine at the construction site of a
North Miami Beach development.
   Bush's mother, who lives in Palm Beach, briefly joined him. Also
campaigning with Bush in Tampa was his son Jeb, who is Florida's
Secretary of Commerce.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1001EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0467,0775</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pledges to Seek Rapid Conclusion Peace Talks, Snags Remain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with talks beginning, mediator's
comments. Picks up 11th graf pvs, `Otherwise, he ...; One word cq
for Najib.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mediator through nearly six years of peace
talks on Afghanistan opened a crucial and perhaps final round today
and said he was sure it would lead to the withdrawal of Soviet
troops.
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez said ``difficult'' problems
remained but that he believed both sides were determined to
overcome them and reach a settlement as soon as possible.
   Cordovez said the negotiations would last as long as was
necessary to forge that settlement.
   ``Perhaps it will be signed earlier than you think,'' he added.
   ``I have the impression that the Afghan people are tired of this
conflict, that they will want peace,'' Cordovez said. He did not
specify what problems remained, citing a need of confidentiality
that allowed the parties to be ``flexible''
   Cordovez spoke to reporters shortly before beginning his shuttle
between the Pakistani and Afghan delegations, seated in separate
rooms in the Geneva office of the United Nations.
   The indirect format was adopted because Pakistan, representing
the anti-Marxist Afghan guerrillas, does not recognize the
Soviet-backed Afghan government of President Najib.
   Cordovez said he had been in contact with representatives of
several countries, including the United States, the Soviet Union,
the European Community and Australia, to discuss humanitarian aid
to Afghanistan after a settlement.
   ``I have the feeling that there will be a broad international
effort,'' he said.
   Pakistan has insisted that pullout of the 115,000 Soviet troops
from Afghanistan be accompanied by formation of a broad-based
transitional government to replace the Afghan regime.
   The Soviets intervened in 1979 to back the Kabul government
against Moslem insurgents.
   Pakistan's chief negotiator, Minister of State Zain Noorani,
said Pakistan came to Geneva with a ``constructive attitude to
finalize the text of the peace package.''
   The head of the Afghan delegation, Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil,
did not renew charges that Pakistan's demand for an interim
government threatens to thwart a settlement.
   Both held separate news conferences on Tuesday.
   Wakil said he approached the talks with a ``sense of full
optimism.''
   Asked whether Pakistan would sign the peace package with the
Najib government, Noorani said that would be decided after
consultations in Islamabad on Sunday with ``national leaders,''
including opposition leaders.
   The Geneva talks will recess to allow Noorani to take part in
those talks.
   Noorani said Pakistan would continue to press for an interim
government acceptable to all Afghans to be created in conjunction
with a Soviet withdrawal.
   Otherwise, he said, there is a threat of new bloodshed
preventing the return to Afghanistan of more than 3 million refuges
from Pakistan and another 2 million from Iran.
   ``We also seek cooperation of the Soviet Union,'' said Noorani.
``We feel that after 8{ years of occupation, the Soviets owe it to
the people of Afghanistan to give them a durable peace.''
   Wakil said Afghanistan has no preconditions for the makeup of
the future government.
   But seven Pakistan-based resistance movements that claim to
speak for the about 200,000 Moslem guerrillas have ruled out any
power-sharing with Najib. Last week, they presented their own plan
for an ``Islamic government.''
   Kabul immediately rejected the plan, which Noorani described as
a ``positive proposal.''
   The talks have moved rapidly since Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's Feb. 8 announcement that Moscow would bring its troops
home within 10 months starting May 15, provided a Geneva settlement
is signed by March 15.
   Noorani said the March 15 date ``is not all that important'' and
that he is sure Soviet withdrawal plans would not be upset if the
signing came later.
   He said the timetable for the pullout is now within ``negotiable
range,'' but he indicated there are still considerable differences.
   Pakistan wants at least half the Soviet troops to leave during
the first three months of a pullout, Noorani said. Gorbachev has
been vague on the subject, which is directly related to the
question of a cutoff in Western aid to the guerrillas.
   The United States is reported to have given the guerrillas $700
million last year.
   Wakil said agreements already drawn up provide for the cutoff to
coincide with the start of the Soviet pullout.
   The Afghan monarchy was overthrown in 1978 and a communist
government was installed. The Soviets intervened at the request of
the embattled new Marxist government.
</TEXT>
