<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BurningScalp     03-02 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burning Scalp,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Water Stoppage Causes Man to Burn Scalp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTNOR, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A water stoppage that took place about 30
minutes earlier than announced left a man with a burned scalp.
   At 7:30 a.m. Monday, Keith Dennis, of Ventnor, applied a caustic
hair relaxer to his scalp. Fifteen minutes later, he ducked his
head under the shower, only to discover there was no water.
   Dennis knew a new water main was being connected as part of a
road reconstruction, but residents had been notified that water
would be turned off about 8:15 a.m.
   Faced with a scalp that was beginning to burn, Dennis and his
wife, Melissa, first tried to bail some water out of the bottom of
the bathtub. Then they tried melting ice cubes on his head.
   ``It started burning more and more,'' Dennis said.
   Dennis considered rinsing his hair with any liquid in the
refrigerator, but was worried about chemical reactions, he said.
   He shouted for workers on the street to turn his water back on,
but said they laughed.
   The couple then called a poison hot line, asking for an
ambulance to bring water.
   But the message got garbled by the time it got to emergency
officials: ``The dispatcher said this guy had shampoo in his hair,
and could we send a bucket of water over,'' is how fire Capt. Bert
Sabo recalls it.
   An ambulance was deemed unnecessary. The Dennises wound up
driving to a hospital, where Dennis was treated for first-degree
burns.
</TEXT>
