<DOCNO> AP880302-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1029EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TurtleExcluders     03-02 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turtle Excluders,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shrimpers Say They Will Disobey Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUSTIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman says shrimpers will defy a
federal regulation requiring the use of devices designed to save
endangered sea turtles, despite a federal judge's decision to
enforce the regulation.
   To further complicate matters, Louisiana Wildlife and Fisheries
agents are prohibited by state law from enforcing the federal
regulation requiring use of turtle excluder devices, which
shrimpers claim could ruin their business.
   Federal enforcement of the regulations began Tuesday after U.S.
District Judge Patrick Carr threw out a suit by shrimpers that
claimed that the devices cut down on their shrimp catches and
aren't effective.
   But Louisiana's Department of Wildlife and Fisheries is bound by
a state law forbidding enforcement of the federal law, said Phil
Bowman, assistant chief of the seafood division.
   ``We'll have to consult with legal counsel before we know what
to do,'' he said.
   Tee John Mialjevich, spokesman for Concerned Shrimpers of
Louisiana, vowed defiance despite Carr's ruling.
   ``I don't care if he upheld it. It's a bad law, and the
shrimpers ain't going to live by it,'' he said.
   The law also went into effect Tuesday in Texas, Mississippi and
Alabama waters, and has been in effect in Florida since Jan. 1.
Louisiana waters won't open to shrimping for two months, but big
boats work year-round in federal waters beyond the three-mile limit.
   Coast Guard patrols caught six shrimp boats working without the
devices since the law went into effect in Florida, Suzanne Montero
of the National Marine Fisheries Service said by telephone from St.
Petersburg, Fla.
   There were no reports of violations Tuesday, she said.
   The maximum civil penalty is $10,000, but first-time offenders
will probably be fined $5,000 to $7,500, she said.
   Under the law, most shrimpers will be required to use the
cage-like devices to save turtles protected under the Endangered
Species Act. The devices, which fit in shrimp nets, have slats to
force a trapped turtle out of a flap, but critics say they don't
always work that way.
   Critics said sometimes shrimp escape and debris gets caught in
the frame and ruins the net.
   Mialjevich said Florida shrimpers experienced catch reductions
of 35 percent to 50 percent.
   ``I'm telling you myself _ personally _ I'm not going to pull a
TED (turtle exclusion device), because I can't make a living. I'll
lose everything I've accumulated in 45 years. ... I can't take a 1
percent shrimp loss. How am I going to take a 35 percent loss?''
said Mialjevich.
   Carr had said in advance that his ruling would not determine the
effectiveness of the devices, but would address only whether the
government had followed proper procedures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
