<DOCNO> AP880302-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1034EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Scandal     03-02 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Scandal,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Social Democrat Chief Resigns In Kickback Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of the Social Democrats, one of five
parties in the government coalition, resigned after accusations
that he was involved in a kickback scandal.
   Franco Nicolazzi, 63, submitted his resignation as party
secretary on Monday to preserve party unity, he said. He denied
wrongdoing, saying ``these hands are clean.''
   The scandal involved millions of dollars allegedly paid to
prominent politicans by companies in exchange for prison
construction contracts. Nicolazzi is under investigation but hasn't
been charged.
   Nicolazzi was public works minister in several governments from
1980 through June. During his tenure, he helped pass a decree
authorizing $629 million for new prison construction.
   Pressure to resign built last week when Gabriele Di Palma, a
close associate of Nicolazzi and former head of the ministry's
public construction department, was detained by Swiss authorities
while allegedly trying to sneak into Switzerland.
   Nicolazzi was secretary of the Social Democrats since October
1985.
   The party received 3.4 percent of the vote in elections to the
Chamber of Deputies last June. Only the Liberals, with 2.1 percent,
had fewer votes among the five coalition parties. The others are
the dominant Christian Democrats, the Socialists and the
Republicans.
   Pier Luigi Romita, a senior Social Democrat deputy, is
considered the favorite to become the new leader of the party.
</TEXT>
