<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Britain-Fire,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out On Roof Of London Stock Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out today on the roof of the 26-floor
London Stock Exchange, but officials said it was quickly brought
under control and no one was injured.
   Police closed nearby streets and scores of spectators gathered
as smoke billowed from the skyscraper in London's financial
district.
   Press Association, the British domestic news agency, said a few
people were evacuated from upper floors, but work continued
elsewhere in the building.
   The fire broke out in a cooling tower and appeared to have been
started by a workman's blowtorch igniting trash in the area, the
news agency said.
   The Stock Exchange said none of its financial services were
affected.
   Since the switch to computers on Oct. 27, 1986, most trading on
the London Stock Exchange has been done by telephone rather than on
the floor of the exchange.
</TEXT>
