<2ND_LINE>PM-Swaggart, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Official: State Council Held Tight On 3-Month Suspension</HEAD>
<NOTE>EdS: Leads with 10 grafs to update with comment from national
church spokeswoman; picks up graf 7, `The Louisiana...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assemblies of God leaders in Louisiana have
rejected a request by national church officials to toughen their
recommended sanctions against evangelist Jimmy Swaggart, a church
official says.
   Juleen Turnage, spokeswoman at church headquarters in
Springfield, Mo., said today that national church officers have not
been informed of any decision by the Louisiana district.
   The Louisiana official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said Tuesday the 19-member state presbytery decided at a nine-hour
meeting Monday in Alexandria to resubmit its original
recommeendation that Swaggart be barred from preaching for three
months as part of a two-year program of rehabilitation.
   The official said it would now be up to national Assemblies of
God officials to decide whether to accept the state panel's
recommendation.
   The Assemblies' General Presbytery has a regular session
scheduled March 29, but an emergency session could be convened
sooner.
   Mrs. Turnage said at least three of the officers must attend any
meeting of the Executive Presbytery. She said it would be at least
Thursday before three of the officials will be back in Springfield.
   Mrs. Turnage said she talked by telephone Tuesday night with the
Rev. G. Raymond Carlson, the general superintendent of the church,
who said he believes it would be unprecedented for a state
presbytery to reject the national church's recommendations.
   Asked about reports last week from from friends of Swaggart that
he might leave the church if he feels the punishment is too harsh,
Mrs. Turnage said national officers have heard nothing directly
from Swaggart.
   ``We're not dealing with a radical or a rebel here. If he does
leave the church, it will be because his ministry can't survive
without him. It will be a pragmatic decision,'' she said.
   ``I think he is very committed to the church,'' Mrs. Turnage
said.
   The Louisiana Presbytery's original sanction was a two-year
rehabilitation program that also included counseling for Swaggart,
who heads a ministry that reportedly takes in $150 million a year.
   Swaggart stepped down from the pulpit Feb. 21, telling the
congregation at his Baton Rouge worship center in a tearful
confession that he had sinned against his wife and God. Swaggart
reportedly paid a prostitute to pose nude for him and then tried to
make a deal with a minister who confronted him about it.
   The national presbytery reportedly recommended barring Swaggart
from the pulpit and television for a year, with an additional year
of regulation of his ministry afterward.
   A Louisiana Assemblies of God official contacted Tuesday night
by The Associated Press confirmed that the state panel stood by its
previous punishment for the evangelist. The decision originally was
reported by KATC-TV of Layfayette.
   When asked if Louisiana officials had sent back their original
censure to the church's national leaders, the source said, ``It
would be correct to say that.''
   Cecil Janway, the Assemblies of God district superintendent for
Louisiana, had said any actions made Monday by the state board
would not be made public.
   There was no indication whether Swaggart attended that meeting.
The Rev. Jim Rentz, who is substituting for Swaggart at his Family
Worship Center, did attend.
   Forrest Hall, secretary-treasurer of the Louisiana district
council, acknowledged Monday that national Assemblies of God
representatives also were at the meeting.
</TEXT>
