<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Boeing-Exits     03-02 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boeing-Exits,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Will Require 10 Seats in New 747s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration will
require The Boeing Co. to install 10 exit doors in its new 747
passenger jetliners, rather than the eight the company prefers, the
agency's chief said today.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor told a House subcommittee that
for safety reasons, he had decided to issue a final rule that would
require the additional doors and expected it to be ready by late
summer.
   A Boeing official, however, told the lawmakers that having eight
doors would be safe.
   ``Prudence,'' McArtor said when asked during a break in the
hearing about why he had made his decision. ``Just a concern of
safety.''
   Boeing plans to soon begin building a new line of the wide-body
747s, whose first generation went into service in 1970. The
aircraft, which can carry more than 500 passengers, are the most
frequently used jetliners for international travel and are also
commonly used for coast-to-coast flights within the United States.
   There are currently eight-exit versions of the 747s used by
foreign airlines, but they carry only 440 passengers.
   McArtor told the House Public Works investigations subcommittee
that the new rule would require a maximum of 60 feet between exit
doors for aircraft flown by U.S. airlines. This would, in effect,
require 10 doors in the 747s.
   In testimony prepared for delivery to the subcommittee, Boeing
Vice President Orvil M. Roetman contested McArtor's decision.
   ``Data, tests, in-service experience and analysis all show that
the 747 distances between exit doors, with either eight or 10 doors
on the main deck, are more than adequate for providing safe
evacuation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
