<HEAD>Restaurant Owner Accused Of Diverting Surplus Government Food</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Siinto is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman was accused of diverting more
than $8,000 in surplus government food intended for school lunch
programs to his catering business and restaurants.
   Siinto Wessman, 70, was cited Tuesday in a criminal complaint in
state district court with two counts of fraud.
   From 1981 through June 1986, Wessman's catering firm, the Neal
Bort Co., had contracts with the Mountain Iron-Buhl, Biwabik and
Gilbert school districts to provide hot lunches under the federal
Child Nutrition Program.
   The contracts allowed the catering firm to obtain surplus
government commodites, including cheese, hamburger and butter, for
use in the school programs.
   The criminal complaint alleges Wessman diverted the food to two
restaurants, which have since closed, and to his catering business.
   ``The charges are absolutely false,'' Wessman said Tuesday. ``I
don't know anything about it.''
   The charges each carry penalties of up to 10 years in prison and
a $20,000 fine.
