<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Shultz-Mideast 3rdLd-Writethru a0559 03-02 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Mideast, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0559,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Sends Shultz Back to Middle East</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Reagan announcement; picks up 7th graf
pvs, ``The spokesman</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, stepping up American
peace efforts in the Middle East, today directed Secretary of State
George P. Shultz to return to the region for further talks with
Arab and Israeli leaders.
   Reagan acted after receiving a report from Shultz on his four
days of diplomatic shuttling in the area and a critical session
Tuesday in London with King Hussein of Jordan.
   ``All countries in the region believe it is useful for the
United States to remain engaged in this process,'' Reagan said.
``We will spare no effort in our search for a comprehensive
settlement.''
   Shultz will leave from Brussels after the windup of a NATO
summit meeting Thursday. He is expected to make stops in Israel,
Jordan and Egypt before returning to Washington next weekend.
   Marlin Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, told reporters
earlier today, ``The President has said on a number of occasions
the United States wants a more visible role in the Middle East in
terms of trying to be helpful, that we were willing and eager to
participate in any way that could move the peace process forward.''
   The U.S. spokesman said Shultz was doing ``yeoman's work'' in
trying to promote negotiations.
   A U.S. official, who demanded anonymity, said Hussein had not
``thrown cold water'' on the U.S. initiative but also had not
endorsed it.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir had a similar reaction.
   ``If I had to describe the situation, I would say that nobody
has signed up to our proposals, but everybody wants us to keep
working,'' Shultz said Tuesday in Tel Aviv.
   Yossi Ben-Aharon, director-general of Shamir's office, said both
Jordan and Israel had asked Shultz to continue his mediation
effort, however.
   Shultz saw Reagan briefly Tuesday night on the president's
arrival from Washingtoon, but `they really didn't get a chance'' to
talk about the Middle East, Fitzwater said.
   ``We will see where it goes from here,'' the U.S. spokesman
said. ``There is no decision at this point.''
   Hussein is demanding an active Soviet role in peace talks and
participation by the Palestine Liberation Organization as he sole
representative of the 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs who live under
Israeli control in the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Shamir, menawhile, refuses to deal with the PLO, which is
considered to be a terrorist group both by Israel and the United
States, and wants also to block participation by the Soviets, who
have backed Arab positions in the past and do not have diplomatic
relations with Israel.
   Shultz has made a point of emphasizing a need for U.S.
communications with the Palestinians, despite a ban on PLO
contacts. ``There's not a substitute for directly sitting down with
people,'' he said Tuesday. ``And that's in a sense what we've been
calling for all along.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
