<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BidRigging     03-02 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bid Rigging,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dredging Company Will Plead Guilty to Rigging Bids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest dredging company will
plead guilty to a charge of rigging bids on Army Corps of
Engineers' dredging projects in the Gulf of Mexico in 1983-84, a
company officer confirmed today.
   Great Lakes dredging company of Oak Brook, Ill., will pay $4.26
million in fines as part of a plea bargain covering bid-rigging
charges filed Tuesday against the company in federal courts in New
Orleans, Philadelphia, San Francisco and Cleveland, said U.S.
Attorney John Volz.
   As part of the agreement, a subsidiary of Great Lakes, North
American Trailing Co., also will plead guilty in New Orleans to
1986 charges of bid-rigging and submitting false statements to the
government, Volz said.
   North American's charges relate to bids submitted on dredging
projects let for bid by the corps from 1982-84.
   ITEL Corp. acquired Great Lakes in 1985, and with it the legal
problems.
   Gary Hill, vice president for finances, said today that the plea
bargain is the final step in clearing up the problems.
   ``The company has been on a `good behavior' program, so to
speak, for over a year. That includes a lot of internal safeguards
to make sure that never happens again,'' Hill said from his
Illinois office. ``We set them up to establish ourselves once again
as a responsible contractor.''
   No company officials were named in the charges Tuesday, but at
least three have entered guilty pleas in the case over the last 18
months.
</TEXT>
