<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IRA-Parade     03-02 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IRA-Parade,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jailed IRA Member Selected Honorary Grand Marshal of St. Patrick's
Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish Republican Army member convicted of
killing a British Army officer has been selected honorary grand
marshal of Philadelphia's St. Patrick's Day Parade.
   After initially rejecting Joseph Patrick Thomas Doherty last
week, the board of the St. Patrick's Day Observance Association
reconsidered this week after some members ``vociferously voiced
their feelings,'' City Councilman and board member Francis W.
Rafferty said Tuesday.
   Thomas J. Gibson, this year's grand marshal and a charter member
of the St. Patrick's Day Association, and other board members had
questioned whether any honorary grand marshal should be selected
this year for the March 13 parade.
   ``I think it takes away from what the parade was organized
for,'' said Gibson, a Southwest Philadelphia tavern owner. ``It's a
religious parade, a Catholic religious parade ... and there's
nothing in there (the association constitution) that says we should
go in for these kinds of politics.''
   Doherty, 33, has been held in New York City's Metropolitan
Correctional Center since 1983 on charges he illegally entered the
country using a false passport after he escaped from a Belfast
prison.
   Requests by the British government to have Doherty extradited
have been rejected. He faces a life sentence in Northern Ireland.
   The U.S. attorney general began reviewing the case last year,
according to Doherty's attorney, Stephen Somerstein.
   Doherty has been named honorary grand marshal in St. Patrick's
Day parades in Hartford, Conn., and Bergen County, N.J., in past
years, said Somerstein. Irish Solidarity Day in New York was
dedicated to him last year, he said.
   Doherty's mother, Maureen, is expected to attend the parade,
according to Vincent Scully, Doherty's champion in the Irish
community and the state vice president of the Ancient Order of
Hibernians. Parade participants will be asked to wear yellow arm
bands to show their solidarity with Doherty, Scully said.
   ``We consider him a hostage,'' said Scully. ``I don't know him
and he doesn't know me, but I can't tolerate another Irishman
treated like dirt.''
</TEXT>
