<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GoetzInheritance     03-02 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Goetz Inheritance,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goetz To Inherit $140,550 From Father's Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City subway gunman Bernhard Goetz
Jr. will inherit $140,550 from his father's estate, but the sum
will hardly cover legal bills stemming from his 1984 shooting of
four teen-agers, a lawyer said.
   Besides four years worth of unpaid legal fees for the shooting
in a subway train, Goetz is being sued for $63 million by three of
the four black teen-agers he shot.
   The inheritance ``won't go very far in defending him on
anything,'' said Joseph Kelner, who has defended Goetz free of
charge in the civil cases.
   Kelner also said Tuesday that he planned to drop Goetz as a
client, saying Goetz has been ``uncooperative.''
   Goetz last October was sentenced to six months in jail and five
years probation for carrying an unlicensed gun, which he used to
shoot the young men. A jury acquitted him of more serious charges,
including attempted murder.
   He is free on $5,000 bond pending appeal.
   Goetz, his brother and two sisters are to share the $562,200.92
remaining in the estate of their father, Bernhard Willard Goetz Sr.
of Orlando, Orange County Probate Court records show.
   Goetz Sr., 78, died Sept. 4, 1984, the day Goetz paid $400 for
two 9mm pistols at Ken's Firearms Inc., giving his father's address
as his. Goetz's father had moved to Orlando in 1963 from Rhinebeck,
N.Y., where the family owned a dairy, a bookbinding company and
several real estate parcels.
   A lawyer for one of the shooting victims, James Ramseur,
welcomed news of Goetz's inheritance.
   ``I'm surprised,'' said Ron Kliegerman. ``His attorneys have
been telling us all along that he doesn't have a dime. Now we know
there's something there.''
   Ramseur's suit seeks $8.5 million, paraplegic Darrell Cabey is
suing Goetz for $50 million and Troy Canty has brought two suits
for $2.5 million _ one for negligent injury, the other for
intentional injury.
   ``The amount of time that will be involved in this case and
damages involved obviously will far exceed $150,000,'' Kliegerman
said.
</TEXT>
