<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Sopkin     03-02 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Sopkin,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Atlanta Symphony Director Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conductor Henry Sopkin, who started with
100 high school musicians and gradually created the Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra, has died. He was 84.
   Sopkin, who lived in Palo Alto for three years, died of heart
failure Tuesday after entering Stanford University Medical Center
last week.
   Before his retirement in 1966, he was musical director of the
symphony for two decades, overseeing more than 1,000 performances
and artists including Jascha Heifetz and Benny Goodman.
   A native of the New York City borough of Brooklyn, he studied
violin as a youth and entered the American Conservatory of Music in
Chicago, where he grew up, earning bachelor's and master's degrees
in music. In the 1920s and '30s, he taught at the conservatory, at
high schools and at Woodrow Wilson College before he was hired in
1944 to direct the Atlanta Youth Symphony Orchestra.
   With a budget of $5,000, he developed the youth symphony into an
adult professional organization with a $300,000 budget 21 years
later.
   After he retired, Sopkin was an instructor with the California
Institute for the Arts in the Los Angeles area, where he lived for
19 years before moving to Palo Alto.
   Sylvia, his wife of nearly 60 years, died in 1986. Survivors
include two sons, a brother, two sisters and a grandson.
</TEXT>
