<2ND_LINE>PM-Philly Ash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0635,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ship Still Anchored; Legal Questions Unresolved</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 8th graf, `The Coast...' with 3 grafs to update with
inspection results.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ship carrying incinerator ash from
Philadelphia won't be allowed to return to tie up here until there
is an agreement about cleaning up 2,000 to 4,000 tons of ash
reportedly left in Haiti, a lawyer says.
   Bruce Phillips, attorney for Joseph Paolino & Sons Inc., which
has a contract with the city to dispose of the ash, said the Khian
Sea would be allowed to dock at Paolino's pier only after there is
an agreement on cleaning up the ash in Gonaives, Haiti.
   ``We want an enforceable covenant that the material will be
removed from Haiti or disposed of in an environmentally sound
manner,'' Phillips said.
   Robert Cordes, president of the ship's operator, Amalgamated
Shipping Co. of Freeport, Bahamas, declined to comment when reached
at his office by The Philadelphia Inquirer.
   Phillips said Paolino will not be paid unless it can show the
ash has been disposed of legally.
   The ship had been turned away from six countries while wandering
the Caribbean and the Atlantic seeking a dumping spot. It anchored
at the mouth of Delaware Bay, north of Lewes, Del., on Tuesday.
   In addition to the question about the ash in Haiti, the ship's
80-mile voyage up the Delaware River to Philadelphia was delayed by
inspections and a pier fire.
   The Coast Guard refused to allow the ship to proceed until it
passed an inpsection by the American Bureau of Shipping.
   The Coast Guard said this morning that the ship passed an
inspection conducted Tuesday, and that the captain of the port has
determined the ship is ``safe to transit U.S. waters,'' the coast
guard said.
   No time was set for the Khian Sea to travel upriver. Its radar
system still didn't work and the coast guard said the ship is
restricted to daytime traveling.
   The environmental group Greenpeace has labeled the Khian Sea's
cargo toxic. State tests conducted when the ash was loaded found no
dangerous levels of toxins, and recent federal tests from the same
incinerator came to the same conclusions.
   The Fire Department, meanwhile, is investigating a rubbish fire
at the Paolini pier this morning. The fire damaged a transfer
station, a company official said.
   Coast Guard spokesman Scott Miller said the city will appoint an
independent engineering firm to determine the safety of the pier
and whether the Khian Sea will be able to dock there.
   Paolino is expected to send the residue to an Ohio landfill,
where the bulk of the city's ash has been dumped for the past two
years, said Phillips.
</TEXT>
