<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MentalHealth     03-02 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mental Health,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rosalynn Carter Urges New Mental Health Spending as House
Considers Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former first lady Rosalynn Carter said
Wednesday that mental illness was America's No. 1 health problem as
a House panel opened hearings on a plan to increase spending on
care and services for mentally ill senior citizens.
   The ``Elderly Mental Health Initiative'' advanced by Rep. Edward
Roybal, D-Calif., would increase outlays for community-based
services for the elderly and their families, on research into
prevention, treatment and services, and on training for health care
professionals.
   It also would lift the lifetime limit on inpatient psychiatric
care paid by Medicare and expand Medicare to cover more outpatient
and community-based mental health services. And it would require
Medicaid to cover community-based services as well.
   In addition, the Roybal bill would create a consumer bill of
rights and set up a national mental health education program.
   ``Now is the time for federal action,'' Roybal said in opening a
hearing on the subject. ``For far too long, mental health care has
been a neglected priority.''
   The Roybal bill would authorize $161 million in new spending in
its first year, most of it to expand mental health grants to
states. The money does not include added expenditures under the
Medicare and Medicaid programs, for which Roybal did not provide an
estimate.
   According to a report compiled by Roybal's House Select
Committee on Aging, between 15 percent and 25 percent of Americans
over 65, about 7 million people, have significant mental health
problems. Very few receive appropriate care, the report said.
   Mrs. Carter and Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste told Roybal's
committee the federal government needs to pay more attention to
mental health needs and spend more on them.
   She called mental health ``America's No. 1 health problem.'' She
recommended substantially higher spending channeled through states,
improvements in Medicare and Medicaid coverage, and strengthening
of patient advocacy services such as the nursing home ombudsman
program.
   ``One of my most urgent pleas is for adequate insurance coverage
for mental illnesses,'' Mrs. Carter said. ``I think the Congress
should do everything possible to assure this coverage. It is is
another of our sadly neglected needs.''
   Celeste stressed the need for community-based services for the
elderly and the relatives who take care of them.
   ``It is a family and community issue. It impacts on all of us at
one time or another,'' he said. ``Many of us here today know
firsthand the responsibility of caring for an elderly family
member.''
   Rep. Claude Pepper, D-Fla., said more than 25 percent of all
suicides are committed by the elderly, ``indicating in many cases
the desperation that they feel.'' He also said more than half the
patients in nursing homes have Alzheimer's disease.
</TEXT>
