<1ST_LINE>r p AM-LiddyDole     03-02 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liddy Dole,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liddy Dole Is Effective Booster for Husband in South</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It might have sounded corny if said by
someone else, someplace else. But this was Elizabeth Dole, and the
praise of her presidential candidate husband struck a pleasing
chord with her fellow North Carolinians.
   ``He kind of reminds me of a laser beam,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``I'm
in awe of the way he can cut through the complexities of a tough
issue and come up with an answer.''
   The crowd responded with applause and approving smiles.
   Standing atop a platform in the parking lot of a suburban office
complex, the former transportation secretary spoke with feeling
about the decision she had made days before to relinquish her
Cabinet post and become a full-time campaigner.
   ``This is where my roots are,'' said the one-time debutante and
beauty queen from Salisbury, N.C. ``This is home. This is where I
draw my strength.''
   George Bush boasts a superior organization and Pat Robertson has
his ``invisible army,'' but Bob Dole has had his own not-so-secret
weapon in the battle for Southern votes next week on Super Tuesday.
   The weapon, he says, is Elizabeth Dole _ known as Liddy _ whose
old-South charm and Ivy League credentials propelled her from
small-town North Carolina to the Reagan Cabinet. She has shown a
talent for holding crowds in the palm of her hand.
   ``She's a vivacious, bright, enthusiastic campaigner,'' said
Haley Barbour, a Mississippi consultant and former political
adviser in the Reagan White House. ``I think other Southerners will
feel a kinship to her.''
   Mrs. Dole agreed last fall to step down as transportation
secretary and hit the campaign trail, making what she said was one
of the toughest decisions of her life. Some feminists complained,
saying she had squandered on opportunity to debunk the traditional
image of the candidate's wife.
   But Mrs. Dole, 51, said there was nothing demeaning about her
change of course.
   ``I mean, this is a challenging assignment to be discussing
national and international issues with the press and the public,''
she said then. ``I will be lucky if I get to see Bob very much at
all. It is not just standing at his side and smiling.''
   She spent the fall crisscrossing the South, speaking at rallies,
giving interviews, lining up commitments among GOP activists and
raising money for the Kansas senator.
   Observers say the final vote counts on Tuesday may well show
Vice President Bush, not Senate Republican Leader Dole, the big
winner in the South. But that wouldn't mean Mrs. Dole failed, they
say.
   ``She's a charmer, but there's only so much you can do,'' said
Ted Arrington, a Republican activist and political scientist at the
University of North Carolina at Charlotte.
   Tim Archie, the Dole campaign's deputy press secretary, said,
``She laid the groundwork for our presence in the South. She
represents the region, can pull in a crowd, and her experience in
the administration is useful.''
   She's also been credited with helping Dole change the image as a
slashing campaigner acquired in his 1976 quest for the vice
presidency. She speaks of his compassion and courage, qualities she
says are most evident close-up.
   Campaign strategists considered Mrs. Dole's vote-getting
potential important enough to hustle her to Iowa in the weeks
leading up to that state's caucuses _ which Dole won.
   Mrs. Dole grew up in a small, conservative town in the North
Carolina Piedmont, the only daughter of well-to-do parents. She was
a debutante at age 18 and two years later was student body
president of the Women's College at Duke University. She graduated
from Harvard Law School and went to Washington, where she spent two
decades in various government posts including the Federal Trade
Commission.
   In 1976, shortly after her marriage to Dole, she took a leave of
absence to help him run for vice president. In 1979, she quit the
FTC to join Dole's presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
