<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeafClubbing     03-02 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaf Clubbing,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Deaf Man Clubbed In Case Of Mistaken Identity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deaf man mistaken for an auto theft suspect
was clubbed with a nightstick, sparking complaints from his sister
and an internal police investigation.
   ``We made a mistake, no doubt about it. I don't know what went
wrong,'' police spokesman Steve Cole said Tuesday. ``Sometimes in
the heat of trying to catch somebody, it's going to happen and it's
unfortunate that it did.
   ``I think (the officer's) main concern was he thought he had
somebody that was going to get away from him,'' Cole said.
   Jeffery Johnson, 21, suffered shoulder bruises Monday night.
   ``The main thing is he doesn't understand why he was struck. He
keeps asking why,'' said his sister, Betty Matthews, who shares her
home with Johnson. She filed a complaint with police.
   The incident began when Officer Delier Diaz gave chase to a car
that had refused to pull over. The chase led to an apartment
complex, where the car's two occupants parked the vehicle and fled.
   Johnson had just helped two maintenance workers at the complex
free a tractor from a ditch when Diaz arrived.
   The officer approached Johnson, who raised his hand to his ear _
the signal used by the deaf to indicate they can't hear. Diaz
ordered him to the ground, said apartment resident Elizabeth Borreo.
   ``Jeff put up his hand and the cop just started hitting him,''
Mrs. Borreo said. ``He hit him with his stick on the leg. Jeff bent
down to grab his leg, and he hit him again on the left shoulder.
Then the cop pushed him down.''
   She and her husband said Diaz held Johnson's hands behind his
back while another officer handcuffed him and put him in a patrol
car.
   ``I said, `You got the wrong guy. He lives here and I saw him
not five minutes ago,''' apartment manager Iris Cox said. Within 30
minutes, the officers released Johnson.
   Later Monday, two people were arrested on charges of grand theft
auto and resisting arrest without violence.
   After those arrests, Diaz filed a report saying he mistakenly
tried to apprenhend Johnson, who he thought was ignored his order
to lay down.
</TEXT>
