<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Basilica     03-02 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Basilica,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says He Is Paying For Huge Basilica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Felix Houphouet-Boigny
says his family is paying for a huge new basilica whose
construction has attracted attention during the West African
nation's economic crisis.
   Houphouet-Boigny told a visiting French boy's choir the
government would never pay for construction of a church building
because the nation was made up of many religious faiths.
   The government daily Fraternite Matin on Wednesday quoted the
president as saying that ``on the streets, some people are amusing
themselves by saying the basilica is financed by the Ivorian
government.''
   ``It will be a gift from my family to the Holy See,''
Houphouet-Boigny said.
   The basilica, which will be the second-largest in the world,
will be built on land donated by Houphouet-Boigny to the state in
his native Yamoussoukro, Fraternite Matin said.
   Pope John Paul II is scheduled to open the church Sept. 10,
1989. It will have 120 arches and a row of columns about 275 yards
long. Figures on its cost have not been released.
   The Ivory Coast has a budget shortfall of more than $600
million, and last year it suspended payments on its international
debt.
</TEXT>
