<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WormGett'r     03-02 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Worm Gett'r,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Agency Seeks Worm Probe Recall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal safety agency filed a civil
complaint Wednesday seeking to force the recall of a device
intended to help fishermen collect worms, but which it says could
wind up electrocuting the anglers instead.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission said it wants to halt
sales of the WORM GETT'R made by P&M Enterprises of Caldwell, Idaho.
   Directory information showed no listing for P&M Enterprises in
Caldwell.
   The device uses metal probes on wooden handles and is tied
together by an electric wire, the commission said. When the probes
are inserted into the ground, electric current passed through the
wire drives worms to the surface.
   But the commission said the design exposes users to the bare
metal charged with electricity and thus could lead to a dangerous
shock.
   No injuries have been reported involving the device, but there
have been 23 deaths since 1971 involving other brands of similarly
designed worm probes, the agency reported.
   About 30,000 WORM GETT'R devices were sold nationally over the
past five years at prices ranging from $8 to $30, the commission
said.
   The commission asked that consumers who have been injured, or
know of others who have had mishaps involving any type of worm
probe, to call it at 1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
