<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SniperAttack 3rdLd-Writethru a0645 03-02 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sniper Attack, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0645,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gun Attack Wounds Five People, Including Gunman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf, `Another victim...' to update with hospitals
for two others.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man armed with two guns leaped out
of a taxicab and opened fire on a crowded street today, wounding
four people before being shot moments later, police said.
   Witnesses said the gunman got out of a taxicab after arguing
with the driver of another vehicle and began firing repeatedly
about a half-block from the Hyatt Regency Hotel, which is about
five blocks from the Alamo.
   ``I saw there was a confrontation with the man in another
vehicle. He pulled out a gun and started firing,'' said Tod Tarble,
20, who witnessed the 9 a.m. incident from a bus stop about 90 feet
away.
   ``There were people all around the street who were trying to get
up there when everybody was being shot, but I tried to keep them
back,'' he said.
   A 55-year-old man believed to be the gunman was being treated at
Medical Center Hospital for a gunshot wound to his left thigh,
spokeswoman Inez Eisazadeh said. His condition was not known, she
said.
   Another victim was being treated at Medical Center Hospital for
a wound to her right knee, and another was treated at Brooke Army
Medical Center for multiple gunshot wounds. A third was taken to
Baptist Memorial Hospital with a leg wound, and the fourth to Nix
Hospital, also with a leg wound.
   After the initial shots, the gunman ``heard the sirens and began
running. A downtown foot patrolman and a park ranger confronted
him,'' police Sgt. Paul Buske said.
   ``The man apparently was out of shells in one of his guns, and
was trying to reload while attempting to shoot with the other
one,'' he said. ``The officers returned fire, and the man was
struck in the upper leg.''
   Buske said he didn't know whether bullets from the officers'
guns or from the gunman's struck the man.
   Tarble said that when the gunman, who was a passenger in the
taxi, began firing, the taxi driver and the driver with whom the
gunman had argued both tried run away.
   The gunman got out of the car, shot a passer-by in the leg,
fired two shots at a woman trying to hunker down in her car's front
seat and fired again at a passing station wagon, hitting the driver.
   He then went around a corner, shot at another person and was
then felled by gunfire, Buske said.
</TEXT>
