<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1304EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Cubans-GOP Bjt   03-02 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cubans-GOP, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Electorate Grows in Strength, Sophistication</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like many of his fellow Cuban-Americans, Agustin
Aguero is Republican and staunchly anti-communist.
   The vice president and manager at Florida National Bank's Little
Havana Branch calls himself a moderate conservative and voted for
President Reagan in 1980 and again in 1984.
   But Aguero is among the growing ranks of well-educated and
politically sophisticated Cuban-Americans who will require more
from presidential candidates than fierce anti-communist rhetoric.
   ``We Cubans are anti-communist, but that isn't our only goal,''
said Aguero, who left behind Cuba and Fidel Castro 17 years ago.
   In the waning days before Super Tuesday, when 20 states
including Florida will hold presidential primaries and caucuses,
Cuban-Americans are weighing their options with a heavy tilt toward
Vice President George Bush.
   More than two-thirds of the 165,274 Cuban-American voters
registered in Dade County are Republicans, according to the Dade
County Elections Department.
   Since the 1984 presidential elections, the Republican party in
Dade has added more than 42,000 Cuban-Americans to its rolls.
   In Tampa, the Cuban-American community, made up mostly of
second-and third-generation Cubans and some who have been around
since the turn of the century, tends to vote Democratic, according
to the Hillsborough County Elections Department, which keeps no
record of the ethnic breakdown among parties.
   But the much larger and politically mobilized Cuban-American
community in Miami is clearly dominated by Republican fervor.
   Here, Bush appears to be the ticket for most Cuban-Americans. He
has made regular forays here and has a strong organization headed
by Gov. Bob Martinez and his son, Jeb, who is the state secretary
of commerce.
   Bush could conceivably capture about 70 percent of the Cuban
vote, said Dade County Republican Party Chairman Carlos Salman. A
recent poll of south Florida Hispanics showed Bush the choice of 81
percent, with the other GOP candidates far back in single digits.
   Pat Robertson cannot be counted out, however. He has made a
serious pitch for the Cuban-American vote, criticized Castro as a
``butcher'' and his claim that there are Soviet nuclear weapons in
Cuba fell on receptive ears here.
   But the former television evangelist's recent anti-communist
appeals apparently aren't being taken very seriously, and some say
his impact on the Cuban vote will be negligible.
   ``I think the Cubans are very sophisticated ... They can see
when people are saying things just to cater to them,'' said Jaime
Suchlicki, director of the Institute of Inter-American Studies at
the University of Miami. ``They prefer truth and candor, not
political sloganism.''
   Bush's ties to the Reagan administration could hold negatives,
Suchlicki said.
   ``There has been an enormous amount of disillusionment vis-a-vis
Nicaragua,'' he said.
   As well, immigration policy also has been a sore point, with a
reversal in the special treatment once accorded Cubans by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   ``There is definitely a great deal of disappointment,'' said
Eddie Levy Rodriguez, former president and founder of the Cuban
American Democrats Association, ``with the way immigration
(officials) and the State Department are treating the Cubans from
Mariel and ... the fact that (Cuba and the United States) are
talking constantly, even though Reagan promised he would never deal
with Castro.''
   Foreign policy remains a top concern of Cuban-Americans, but
increasingly they say their other interests are not being
addressed, including but not limited to, issues such as the
economy, housing and unemployment.
   Aguero said the new generation of Cubans, who don't harbor
notions of ever going back to Cuba, simply have different ideals.
They consider themselves Americans first and Cubans second, he said.
   Levy said the number of Cuban-American Democrats is growing, and
he said Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis should fare well among
them.
   But most of the Cuban-American population still votes Republican.
   ``We feel the Republicans have done more for the things we
like,'' Salman said. ``Since Ronald Reagan is president of the
United States we have not lost one country to communism. We also
are interested in being able to have better lives, better jobs, low
interest, low inflation and high employment. Republicans do this
more often and better than the Democrats.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1306EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SubwayRevolt Bjt   03-02 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Subway Revolt, Bjt,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commuters Rebel on Problem-Plagued Train</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mutiny broke out on among usually meek and
patient London commuters, with passengers refusing orders to leave
their delay-plagued subway train until its driver took them to
their destination.
   Only about a dozen rebellious passengers were involved in the
Tuesday night incident on the ``tube,'' as the subway system is
known, but London Regional Transport said it was unprecedented,
given the meek and humble nature of the British commuter.
   To the London Evening Standard newspaper, it was ``The Great
Tube Revolt,'' and the mutineers' unidentified leader was ``a
superhero in the Clark Kent mold _ quiet, mild-mannered and
unassuming.''
   The excitement generated by the incident reflected not only the
frustrations of riding the system's aging Northern Line, but the
amazement of Londoners at the prospect of British commuters
abandoning their fabled reserve and making a public fuss.
   A similar incident occurred in New York City's subway system in
April 1985, when about a dozen commuters refused to leave a
disabled train until they were taken from it by transit police.
   London Regional Transport accused the tube mutineers of being
selfish.
   Spokesman David Morris said the problem began with delays caused
by a signal failure. Passengers bound for High Barnet, at the end
of the Northern Line, were told to disembark five stations before
their destination and wait for the next train.
   They started filing off, but then, according to the Standard, a
``mild-looking and well-dressed'' passenger declared: ``I've had
enough. I'm staying put. If we all do it, they'll have to take the
train on.''
   About a dozen passengers got back into the train, it said. More
passengers followed, and after hurried consultations the staff
bowed to the pressure and sent the train on.
   Morris said that had the passengers done as they were told, the
next train would have taken them to High Barnet, while the first
train could have turned back to collect passengers in central
London who had been delayed by the earlier signal failure.
   ``We had an overall picture of what was happening,'' he told The
Associated Press. ``Those passengers had only a narrow and selfish
view and put their needs above others.''
   Passenger Sheila Golding of High Barnet was quoted by the
Standard as saying the mutineers were cheering and laughing,
because ``we knew that if everyone did it _ and stayed put _ there
wasn't anything they could do about it.''
   Another passenger, Maria Gama, was quoted as saying: ``Everybody
was just totally fed up. The waiting room was freezing and nobody
could tell us why the train was stopping where it did. But when
everybody climbed back on, it was a marvelous moment.''
   The Northern Line, parts of which are more than a century old,
carries 700,000 passengers a day and serves 50 stations between
south and north London.
   Dubbed ``The Misery Line'' by newspapers, it is attacked for
defective trains and equipment, last-minute schedule changes,
signal failures and dirty stations. It is to have a major
modernization in the 1990s.
   Morris denied the line was worse than others but conceded that
some employees can be rude. ``They know what they're up against and
they probably don't look forward to coming to work any more than
passengers look forward to using the line,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1341EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATOSummit-Arms Bjt   03-02 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO Summit-Arms, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Allies Put New Accent on Non-Nuclear Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By putting new emphasis on the threat
to Europe from Soviet tanks and troops, Western leaders hope to
blunt Moscow's drive to capitalize on splits within NATO on nuclear
arms strategy.
   In a joint statement Wednesday, leaders of the Western alliance
called on the Soviet Union and its allies to begin negotiations
aimed at eliminating the East's capability for launching a surprise
attack in Europe.
   They said Soviet non-nuclear forces facing NATO are far in
excess of Moscow's needs for self defense and ``cast a shadow over
the whole of Europe.''
   President Reagan called the declaration ``a major step forward
for the alliance.''
   The idea is to portray the North Atlantic Treaty Organization as
united in calling for fewer non-nuclear weapons at a time when the
alliance members cannot agree how far to go in scrapping atomic
arms.
   The NATO initiative also shifts the public spotlight away from
West Germany's dispute within the alliance over whether and when to
replace very short-range nuclear weapons with new, more effective
ones. Most of these weapons, if used, would strike German soil,
East or West.
   The main NATO theme is that the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact's
numerical superiority in conventional weapons and troops _ not the
existence of nuclear arms in Europe _ is the greatest danger to
Western security.
   According to Western estimates, the Warsaw Pact holds about a
3-to-1 advantage in tanks and artillery and nearly a 2-to-1 edge in
combat aircraft and troops, including reserves in the Soviet Union.
Moscow contends that East-West conventional forces are roughly
equivalent.
   The stress on conventional arms, NATO hopes, will steal some of
the momentum from Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's campaign to
woo the European public with calls for ridding their continent of
all nuclear weapons.
   NATO leaders agree that some nuclear arms are needed in Europe
to deter attack.
   Gorbachev appears to have significantly improved his public
image in Western Europe by agreeing last year to a longstanding
U.S. proposal to eliminate all intermediate-range nuclear weapons,
based mostly in Europe.
   The 16 NATO nations have strongly endorsed this deal, known as
the INF Treaty. The Senate is expected to ratify the treaty this
spring.
   But in the aftermath of the INF deal, the alliance has fallen
into disagreement over whether to press immediately for East-West
negotiations to reduce a large Soviet edge in short-range nuclear
missiles. West Germany, which is most directly threatened by these
weapons, wants such talks to start soon; most of the other NATO
allies do not.
   The Brussels NATO summit was not expected to discuss this
quandry in detail, much less find a solution. Instead, a key aim of
the meeting was to turn the public's attention to other aspects of
East-West relations, including human rights and non-nuclear arms
talks.
   The NATO members and the seven Warsaw Pact nations have been
working for a year to agree on the framework for a new set of
negotiations to establish a more stable balance of conventional
forces in Europe.
   These talks, likely to begin this fall, would replace a narrower
set of East-West negotiations on cutting troop levels, which began
in 1973. After 15 years, these talks have not produced a single
agreement.
   NATO members hope the new negotiations would focus more directly
on warfighting equipment as well as troops. These talks also would
encompass the full European area, from the Atlantic to the Ural
mountains. The old troop talks were limited to the central front.
   Even though the Western allies acknowledge that it may take
years to reach a meaningful agreement on conventional forces, they
hope the drive to reach the bargaining table will put NATO back on
the diplomatic offensive.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDITOR'S NOTE: Robert Burns covers the North Atlantic Treaty</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Organization for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
