<2ND_LINE>AM-Chopped Hand,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Who Chopped Off Uncle's Hand to Get Psychiatric Evaluation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A juvenile court judge ordered a
psychiatric evaluation for a 13-year-old boy who chopped off his
uncle's hand at the uncle's request.
   Juvenile Judge Kenneth Turner said Tuesday that the youth was
charged with mayhem, the crime of cutting off a body part of
another, after he chopped off his uncle's hand Sunday at the man's
home in Lakeland, near Memphis.
   Shelby County Sheriff's Department Inspector Buck Wood said the
uncle, James Veazey, 33, had a history of treatment for mental
problems. Wood said the man told his nephew he had rabies in the
hand and asked him to chop it off.
   Sgt. Travis Taylor said the youth had said Veazey had repeatedly
asked him to cut off the hand. ``I got tired of listening to it and
got on with it,'' Taylor quoted the youth as saying.
   The boy used a single-blade ax to cut off the hand and then
threw it into a garbage can, retrieving the hand only when a
neighbor doubted his tale of cutting it off.
   Veazey had prepared a bucket of hydrogen peroxide and water to
treat the stump of his arm, Taylor said.
   Neighbors called an ambulance and the sheriff's department after
they were shown the hand.
   Veazey was taken to the Regional Medical Center for surgery,
then transferred to Memphis Veterans Medical Center.
   Taylor said relatives told him Veazey had himself chopped off a
finger of the hand in the Shelby County Jail last year.
   The severed hand could not be reattached, Taylor said.
</TEXT>
