<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Probation-Reading     03-02 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Probation-Reading,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Uses Reading And Library Time As Part of Juvenile Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who orders some juvenile offenders to
go to the library and read as a condition of probation says he
harbors no illusions that it will help everyone. He'd settle for
one out of four.
   ``I understand that a good number of young people will laugh at
this,'' Baltimore Circuit Judge John Carroll Byrnes said in a
recent interview. ``Some will try, but will fall by the wayside
when they get back in with their buddies in their environment. And
others simply won't be able, intellectually.
   ``But I'm convinced that a significant minority, once coerced
into reading, will be so attracted by the experience that it will
change their lives. I'm optimistic that we can do it. If we can
reach 25 percent of the youthful offenders we see, I'd call this
plan a roaring success.''
   The judge, who splits his time between juvenile court and the
city's Circuit Court, said he has made reading a part of probation
since he came on the bench about five years ago. An ad hoc
committee of librarians, educators and parole and probation
officers was formed a year ago and hopes to have a formal list of
suitable titles, basically from the junior high school level, by
the end of the year.
   Some of the suggested titles include ``I Am The Darker Brother''
by Arnold Adoff, ``Westmark'' by Lloyd Alexander, ``Anna To The
Infinite Power'' by Mildred Ames, ``Curse of the Blue Figurine'' by
John Bellairs, ``Sounder'' by William A. Armstrong, and ``Are You
There God? It's Me, Margaret'' by Judy Blum.
   Byrnes also said he has restricted television viewing as a
condition of probation in some cases. ``It's interesting _ no
matter what you say before that, they shudder when I come to the
one about television,'' he said.
</TEXT>
