<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FerretReprieve     03-02 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ferret Reprieve,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Pardons Ferret Scheduled for Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMERS BRANCH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix the ferret was scheduled for
execution this week, but a public outcry resulted in a pardon from
the mayor.
   ``We are going to ferret out a solution,'' said Farmers Branch
Mayor John Dodd, who spared the animal Monday.
   The fuzzy, pink-eyed ferret was caged at the city's animal
shelter.
   Farmers Branch police Officer Rodney Wallace spotted the animal
Friday during patrol. When he opened the door of his car and
whistled, the ferret jumped into his lap and snuggled against him.
   Wallace took the ferret to the animal shelter in the Dallas
suburb and attached a note to his cage that said, ``Please do not
destroy. If no one claims it, I want it back.''
   Because of a city ordinance prohibiting exotic animals,
officials said the ferret would be destroyed if his owner was not
found. As news spread of the ferret's plight, the animal shelter
was deluged with requests to adopt the creature.
   Animal control officer Mike Worsham said his department could
not take responsibility for placing Felix for adoption because
there is no approved vaccine for ferrets and the animals sometimes
bite.
   But Dodd promised Monday to ``cut through the red tape.'' The
mayor said he spoke to the owner of an animal rehabilitation center
about taking the animal. The center has a state license to keep
wild animals, which will prevent the ferret's death.
   ``He's got a reprieve,'' Dodd said.
</TEXT>
