<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bodies-Graham     03-02 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bodies-Graham,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Graham's Confession Admissible in Bodies Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today ruled the confession by a man
to the slayings of seven women in his apartment could be admitted
at trial and rejected a claim of illegal arrest.
   Common Pleas Judge Robert Latrone denied a defense motion to
suppress the confession and all physical evidence seized by police
in Harrison Graham's home last August. Defense attorney Joel
Moldovsky also had sought to have Graham's arrest declared illegal.
   Latrone said the validity of the statement will be up to the
jury.
   Moldovsky and Assistant District Attorney Roger King then met
with Latrone to discuss the start of jury selection. No date was
immediately set.
   The ruling ended a 14-day pretrial hearing for Graham, accused
of killing seven women after luring them to his apartment with
liquor and drugs. Police found human remains in and near Graham's
apartment.
   Moldovsky is mounting an insanity defense for his client. He
claims Graham has three personalities: Frank, a foul-mouthed junkie
who kills women during sex; Marty, an easy-going, mother-worshiping
guy who confessed to the murders; and Junior, a mute, bad-mannered
2-year-old who and likes cartoon characters.
   Graham's full name is Harrison Frank Graham Jr.
   Moldovsky last week asked for new psychiatric evaluations of
Graham when the suspect described how he punched another inmate
during a fight at the Detention Center.
   ``Frank did it,'' said Graham, describing to Latrone how he
responded to an inmate who had kicked him.
   King has dismissed the multiple-personality claim as ``just
smoke.'' He says Graham is a shrewd, street-smart faker who
deserves the electric chair.
</TEXT>
