<DOCNO> AP880302-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1428EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh     03-02 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombs, Fires as Opposition Begins Anti-Election Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LABELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bands of youths hurled bombs, burned
cars and trucks, and shouted anti-government slogans Wednesday
during a general strike called to disrupt Parliamentary elections.
At least eight people were injured.
   Teen-agers and children, several appearing younger than 10 years
old, stopped a city garbage truck in downtown Dhaka, smashed it
with clubs and set it ablaze.
   ``We set fire to Ershad's throne!'' the youngsters chanted,
referring to President Hussain Muhammad Ershad.
   Demonstrators stoned and taunted police burned election banners,
along with at least one scooter and a taxi.
   The opposition called the strike to protest Thursday's
Parliamentary elections. Many here believe the elections have more
potential for violence than for halting the stalemate between
Ershad and his foes.
   Eight people were reported hospitalized with injuries from small
bombs, and two were in serious condition, police and hospital
officials said.
   But no major confrontations erupted between police and
protestors, and the city was calm overall.
   In the southern port city of Chittagong, witnesses said at least
50 people were injured in clashes between protestors and police.
The witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said protestors
threw bombs at the office of the local municipal corporation and
damaged several vehicles.
   In the capital, the strike appeared successful, shutting down
shops and businesses and chasing from the streets the bicycle
rickshaws that make Dhaka traffic a nightmare.
   But the strike appeared to have little effect outside Dhaka
other than stopping trucks and buses from running.
   It was the 24th strike called by the opposition since Nov. 10,
when it began its campaign to oust Ershad.
   In a move to compromise with his opponents, Ershad dissolved the
330-seat Parliament last December, 3{ years before its term was to
expire, and scheduled new elections. But opposition leaders have
said no election conducted under Ershad can be fair, and they are
urging a voter boycott.
   At least 33 people have been died since Nov. 10, either in
clashes, by police gunfire, or in campaign-related violence.
   Sheik Hasina of the opposition Awami League said Wednesday that
she expected only 5 percent or 10 percent of the 47.8 million
voters to cast ballots.
   More than 900 candidates from 102 political parties are running
for Parliament. Eighteen candidates, all from Ershad's Jatiya
Party, have already been declared elected for lack of opposition,
and voting in one district was canceled because of the slaying of a
candidate.
   In addition to the Parliamentary election, municipal elections
will be held in the cities of Dhaka, Chittagong, Khulna, and
Rajshahi.
   In similar polling for town and village councils across the
country three weeks ago, more than 100 people were killed in
battles between supporters of candidates.
   Ershad seized power in a bloodless coup in 1982 and won election
in 1986. He ordered 9,000 army troops and about 290,000 local
police and paramilitary troops deployed to ensure security for the
elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
