<DOCNO> AP880302-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Panama-Assets 3rdLd-Writethru a0682 03-02 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Assets, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0682,630</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th and 11th grafs with State Department comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department is preparing to notify
all U.S. banks where the Panamanian government has deposits not to
engage in any transactions with the regime that seized power in
Panama last week, a lawyer for a Panamanian opposition group said
today.
   William D. Rogers, an attorney for the Arnold & Porter law firm,
said the Panamanian government is believed to have deposits in five
U.S. banks and that law suits are being drawn up to ensure bank
compliance with the measure.
   Rogers told a news conference the State Department action would
require the banks to make disbursements only to the ambassador who
represented the deposed government of President Eric Arturo
Delvalle.
   Later, State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said
the department was preparing documentation certifying that persons
designated by Delvalle are the legitimate representatives of the
Panamanian government.
   But she did not say what the legal consequences of the
certification were or why it was being prepared.
   Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, who has maintained that Delvalle's
ouster was unconstitutional, said he had no precise figures on the
amounts of money in the Panamanian accounts but estimated the
number to be $50 million.
   In New York, lawyers for Delvalle sued in federal court today to
block a New York bank from turning over millions of dollars to new
government in Panama.
   A federal judge issued a temporary restraining order, blocking
the Republic National Bank of New York from transferring an
estimated $10 million.
   A hearing on the matter is slated for Monday before U.S.
District Judge Lloyd F. McMahon.
   The lawsuit seeks to establish title to the funds held in the
Republic National Bank account and ``to prevent their transfer into
the hands of a military dictatorship ... which has attempted to
seize power and overthrow the lawful authorities of the Republic of
Panama,'' according to court papers.
   In Washington, Sosa said the State Department is seriously
considering withholding from Panama the next payment on the fees
the United States gives Panama for use of the Panama Canal. He
estimated that figure at $8 million.
   Ms. Oakley confirmed that a request from the Delvalle government
to put the funds in escrow had been received and that the State
Department was consulting with other agencies on how to proceed.
   Delvalle fired military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega last
Thursday but the defense chief ignored the order and rallied his
allies in the National Assembly against the president. On Friday,
the assembly voted to oust Delvalle and installed Education
Minister Manuel Solis Palma in his place.
   Noriega has been indicted on drug smuggling charges by two
Florida grand juries and has been under heavy diplomatic, economic
and political pressure by the Reagan administration to step aside
and open the way for civilian-led constitutional rule.
   Among the banks listed by Rogers which would be affected by the
order are Marine Midland, Irving Trust, Bankers Trust and the
Republic National Bank. He said all have headquarters in New York.
   ``Every dime we can find is in those banks,'' Rogers said. He
added that any bank which ignores the order could be liable for
whatever payments it makes to the current Panamanian government.
   The coalition of opposition leaders believes that the Panamanian
government is facing a grave cash flow problem and is extremely
vulnerable to economic pressure from the United States.
   Unlike other countries, Panama cannot cover its cash shortages
by printing new money because the dollar is the national currency.
   Sosa said international opposition to the new government was
evident earlier this week when, he claimed, only eight ambassadors
showed up for a State of the Union address. From the Western
Hemisphere, he said, only Cuba and Nicaragua attended.
</TEXT>
