<DOCNO> AP880302-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1546EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Plane     03-02 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Plane,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SAA Air Crash Recording to Be Kept Secret</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Wednesday
it won't release a recording of the conversation between a control
tower and a South African Airways jumbo jet that crashed Nov. 28 in
the Indian Ocean, killing all 159 people aboard.
   The announcement was made by Supreme Court Justice Cecil Margo,
head of an international board that began meeting Monday to
investigate the cause of the crash on a flight from Taipei, Taiwan
to Johannesburg.
   The Boeing 747 went down minutes before it was due to refuel in
Mauritius.
   Reports at the time had quoted Mauritian officials as saying the
pilot reported fire or smoke in the cockpit.
   South African officials took over the investigation from
Mauritian aviation authorities, and no further information was
released. The South African officials said at the time that quotes
from the recording would not be released because they might be
misunderstood and some people might believe they were being accused
or blamed.
   Margo said the recorded conversation was indistinct in parts and
experts had disagreed about what was said, so no official
transcript or sound from the recording would be released.
   Margo said the board had decided Wednesday that the cockpit
voice recorder, flight data recorder and other pieces of the jet
must be recovered ``at all costs'' from the crash site 14,520 feet
under the ocean north of Mauritius.
   Aboard the jet were 71 South Africans, 47 Japanese, 30
Taiwanese, and one or two passengers from Australia, Mauritius,
Hong Kong, the United States, Holland, Britain, Germany, Denmark
and South Korea. Only 11 bodies were recovered.
</TEXT>
