<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1643EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PanamaMoney     03-02 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama Money,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Billions in Bank Funds Withdrawn from Panama; Some Money Deposited
in Miami</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billions of dollars in bank deposits are being
taken out of Panama for safer havens in the wake of the political
turmoil following the drug indictment of military strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, financial experts say.
   Some of that money has wound up in Miami, where federal
regulations adopted earlier this decade allow ``offshore'' banks to
escape the scrutiny that domestic banks undergo.
   Panama in the 1980s had come to be known as the Switzerland of
Latin America, offering banking secrecy and stability to the
region's investors and depositors. Banks there are unfettered by
high taxes or cumbersome rules, providing a safe haven for both
legitimately and illegitimately earned money.
   But a deposit flight began last year when street demonstrations
broke out in Panama, accelerating after Noriega's indictment last
month.
   ``This certainly has destabilized Panama as a banking center,''
said Gonzalo Valdes-Fauli, senior vice president and manager of the
Miami office of London-based Barclay's Bank.
   Valdes-Fauli said some foreign banks are moving their operations
to other Caribbean or Central American nations.
   Credit Suisse, the third-biggest U.S. bank, announced Tuesday
that it was closing its Panama office at the end of April, and said
its offshore business has already been transferred to branches in
Miami and the Bahamas.
   One unidentified top banking expert told The Miami Herald that
from June to October Panamanian banks lost $7 billion of the $36
billion they held.
   Some of that money began trickling back, but since Noriega's
indictment and the subsequent political upheaval, Panama banks are
losing the funds once more, the Herald reported Wednesday.
   Foreign deposits in Miami increased 39 percent in 1987 to $6.2
billion, although it was not known how much of that represented
deposits from Panama banks.
   The deposit flight from Panama could be accelerated by an
expected State Department notification to U.S. banks not to
transact business with the Central American nation's current
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
