<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FatMagnet     03-02 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fat Magnet,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Permits Seizure of Orders for Alleged Weight-Loss Pill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has given postal inspectors the
go-ahead to seize mail orders for ``Fat Magnet,'' a pill nationally
advertised as the ``lazy way'' to lose weight.
   U.S. District Judge Terry Hatter Jr. issued a preliminary
injunction Tuesday against the company after Assistant U.S.
Attorney George Wu argued it may be fraudulently promoting the
pill, which it claims absorbs fat and flushes it out of the body.
   The pill does not have Federal Drug Administration approval.
   The U.S. Postal Service had requested the injunction, which
allows the postal inspectors to continue seizures they began three
weeks ago. A decision on the charges will be made at an
administrative hearing in Washington, D.C., within 60 days.
   Postal Inspector Jim Harbin said the Postal Service already has
seized between 8,000 and 10,000 pieces of mail addressed to the
company in Beverly Hills and will keep the mail, including checks
for purchase of the product, until a fraud hearing is held.
   Attorneys for Fat Magnet said the product not only works, but is
a food for special dietary use, a category recognized as between
food and drugs that does not require FDA approval.
   ``We certainly agree that this product has not been approved by
the FDA,'' said Kirkpatrick Dilling, a company attorney. ``It's not
necessary.''
   Dilling said the pill's two main ingredients, fiber and purified
bile, do not qualify Fat Magnet as a new, unapproved drug.
   But Wu responded that there are questions about how well Fat
Magnet works, if it works at all, and serious consumer safety
concerns about its use.
</TEXT>
