<DOCNO> AP880302-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Economy Bjt   03-02 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Home Sales Down 9 Percent In January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New home sales fell 9 percent in January,
pushing sales activity to its slowest pace since the end of the
last recession, the government said Wednesday as the housing
industry continued to stagger following the October stock market
collapse.
   A downturn in housing has often been the harbinger of the onset
of a recession, but analysts said they believed falling mortgage
rates offered the hope of a rebound in home sales in coming months.
   In January, the Commerce Department said that sales of new
single-family homes fell for the third consecutive month, dropping
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 535,000 units, 26 percent
below a year ago and the slowest pace since the last recession was
ending in December 1982.
   In a second lackluster economic report, the Commerce Department
said orders for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in January to a
seasonally adjusted $212.6 billion.
   While this was the first decline in five months, analysts noted
that it followed an unusually large 2 percent December increase, a
gain which reflected a big jump in demand for jet airplanes.
   Analysts said the one-month setback did nothing to change their
view that American manufacturers are continuing to enjoy a sales
boom led by increased demand for exports.
   Analysts said they were surprised by the sharpness of the
decline in home sales, especially since sales had already fallen by
6.8 percent in December and 3.4 percent in November.
   The decline in new home sales followed other reports showing a
big decline in construction starts for new homes in January and the
third consecutive monthly decrease in sales of existing homes.
   ``It looks like housing is bearing the brunt of the stock market
decline, but I believe lower interest rates can solve a lot of
problems in this industry,'' said Bob Villanueva, director of
economic forecasting for the National Association of Home Builders.
   Analysts noted that fixed-rate mortgages have fallen into the
single-digit range again, averaging 9.87 percent last week,
compared to 10.6 percent when the year began.
   James Christian, chief economist for the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions, said with ``mortgage rates moving in the right
direction'' sales for all of 1988 should rebound to around 650,000
units, only 3 percent below the 1987 sales pace.
   But other analysts said it remained to be seen whether the drop
in mortgage rates will be enough to attract new buyers. They noted
that sales have been strong for the past three years and a lot of
pent-up demand has been exhausted.
   ``We simply don't have the demand for housing that we had in the
first part of the recovery,'' said Michael Sumichrast, an economist
and publisher of a construction industry newsletter. ``The South,
which accounts for almost half of all new homes sold, is still weak
and you won't see any significant improvement until that area turns
around.''
   Analysts, however, said they were not ready to forecast an end
to the current economic recovery.
   ``We are seeing a shift away from economic growth driven by
housing and other domestic sectors and toward growth in
manufacturing and other export sectors,'' said Warren Lasko,
executive director of the Mortgage Bankers Association.
   The 9 percent decline in new home sales in January was the
steepest decline since a 10.9 percent drop last May. The big
decline in sales was accompanied by a sharp rise in prices.
   The median, or mid-point, price of a home shot up 9.7 percent to
$120,000 while the average home price rose to $149,000, an increase
of 10.5 percent.
   Economists said that while home prices have been outpacing rises
in overall inflation in recent months, the January surge was skewed
upward by the fact that sales rose in the Northeast, a high-priced
section of the country, while they were down sharply in the
less-expensive South.
   Sales dropped 24.4 percent in the South to an annual rate of
177,000 units. Sales were off 13.7 percent in the Midwest to a rate
of 88,000 units.
   Sales rose 23 percent in the Northeast to an annual rate of
91,000 units, but this big increase followed a much larger 53
percent December decline. Sales edged up 0.6 percent in the West to
an annual rate of 179,000 units.
</TEXT>
