<1ST_LINE>u p PM-AlaskaCaucuses 1stLd-Writethru a0495 03-02 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alaska Caucuses, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0495,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Wins in Alaska GOP Delegate Poll</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with results</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson won a one-sided
preference poll victory in Alaska's Republican caucuses, nearly
doubling the support given Vice President George Bush, party
officials said today.
   Robertson, the former television evangelist, claimed 47 percent
of the votes compared with Bush's 24 percent in a poll of 2,020
precinct delegates. Sen. Bob Dole took third with 20 percent.
   The preference poll was not binding, though it gave an
indication of the feelings of the delegates who will attend 27 GOP
district conventions March 18-26. At those meetings, 400 delegates
will be chosen to attend the state convention in late April, when
the state's 19 GOP delegates will be named to attend the national
convention.
   A hint of Robertson's strength was suggested Tuesday when party
spokesman Linda Shafer noted that Republican regulars had noticed
new faces in the precinct caucuses that began Saturday.
   In other early-contest states, Robertson supporters have signed
up thousands of new party members to participate in caucuses.
   ``There were people new to the political process,'' said Shafer.
``You could tell by their political platforms _ things like
anti-marijuana and anti-abortion _ that they were church folks.''
   Many of the delegates had been expected to back Robertson,
Shafer said. But Robertson had competition on the religious front.
A Baptist preacher, the Rev. Jerry Prevo, organized members of his
Anchorage church to attend the caucuses and support Bush.
   The caucuses were open to any registered Republican.
   Precinct and district delegates have been known to shift
allegiances, but the GOP delegates to the national conventions
never have abandoned their chosen candidates, state Republican
chairman Jim Crawford said.
   Crawford said the Alaska GOP is trying to link up with other
Western states in hopes of gaining clout, especially in selecting a
vice presidential candidate.
   The Democratic Party's delegate selection, similar to that of
the Republican Party, is scheduled to begin in Alaska with precinct
caucuses in 10 days.
</TEXT>
