<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham-Profiles 1stLd-Writethru a0481 03-02 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham-Profiles, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thumbnail Sketches Of Key Players</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham-Impeachment, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Milstead's age, fifth item, to 48, sted 59.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are capsule profiles of some of the
major figures in Gov. Evan Mecham's impeachment trial:
   
   FRANK X. GORDON Jr. _ Chief justice of the Arizona Supreme Court
and presiding officer in the Senate trial. Democrat, a self-styled
moderate, 59; described as the epitome of a small town lawyer and
judge, friendly, open, straight-forward. Scored 100 percent for
integrity in a poll of 300 Arizona attorneys in 1986. Arizona's
youngest Superior Court judge when he was appointed to that bench
in May 1962. Born in Chicago in 1929, came to Arizona with his
parents as a child. Graduate of Stanford University in 1951,
received law degree from the University of Arizona in 1954. Kingman
city attorney in 1955-56. Appointed to the state Supreme Court in
1975 by then-Gov. Raul Castro. Became chief justice in 1987.
   
   WILLIAM P. FRENCH _ Lead prosecution attorney. Hired by the
House in October to investigate Mecham's $350,000 campaign loan and
other allegations. French, 56, presented a report on Jan. 15
outlining possible grounds of impeachment and conducted the
subsequent hearings that led to the Feb. 5 impeachment. Former
presiding judge of the Maricopa County Superior Court's criminal
division. Worked for the U.S. Justice Department as a prosecutor in
the organized crime section.
   
   JERRIS LEONARD _ Hired one week before the impeachment trial
began to head Mecham's defense team. Accustomed to defending
controversial people, but forced to resign from his Washington,
D.C., law firm because it didn't want to be involved in
representing Mecham. Former head of the Law Enforcement Assistance
Administration and the Justice Department's civil rights division
under President Nixon. Former Wisconsin Senate majority leader.
Leonard, 57, headed United Sciences of America, a company accused
by the New York state attorney general of engaging in an illegal
pyramid-type scheme to sell vitamins. The company agreed to a
financial settlement in October.
   
   FRED CRAFT _ A Mecham friend and the subject of two major
disputes between Mecham and the Legislature in 1987. Mecham wanted
to hire him as the governor's Washington, D.C., lobbyist, but the
Legislature refused to appropriate the money. Mecham eventually
decided to hire Craft anyway and paid his salary and expenses from
the governor's office budget. Mecham also was accused of pressuring
a state panel to choose Craft as its lobbyist for Arizona's bid for
the federal superconducting super collider. The panel eventually
chose another lobbyist. Craft resigned as Arizona's Washington
lobbyist shortly after impeachment turned the governorship over to
Arizona's secretary and state and forced Mecham to step aside as
governor at least temporarily. Craft ad Leonard are longtime
friends, and Craft brought Leonard into the impeachment trial.
   
   RALPH MILSTEAD _ The man Mecham is accused of ordering not to
cooperate with the state attorney general's investigation of a
death threat allegation. Director of the Department of Public
Safety since 1980. Given a new five-year contract in 1985.
Previously spent 20 years in the Phoenix Police Department,
reaching the rank of major. Mecham has been rumored at various
times to have wanted to replace Milstead, 48, but by law he cannot
be fired at will by the governor.
   
   DONNA CARLSON _ Mecham's former special assistant and liaison to
the Legislature. A former state senator and unsuccessful
congressional candidate. She resigned in October 1987, saying the
controversy surrounding Mecham's administration had made it
impossible for her to do her job. Ms. Carlson, 50, was scheduled to
testify before the state grand jury regarding Mecham's failure to
report a $350,000 campaign loan when she allegedl became the
subject of a death threat by then-state official Lee Watkins.
   
   PEGGY GRIFFITH _ The woman who reported then-state official
Watkins had voiced threats to the life of Carlson. Mrs. Griffith is
director of the Governor's Office of Women's Services. She told the
Department of Public Safety on Nov. 13 that Watkins had told her
her friend, Ms. Carlson, had better keep quiet or Ms. Carlson might
go on a ``long boat ride'' and not come back. Mrs. Griffith earlier
had been close friends with Ms. Carlson, but Ms. Carlson said the
two had become somewhat distant at the time the alleged death
threat was made.
</TEXT>
