<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NYCWomen-AIDS     03-02 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NYC Women-AIDS,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Similar NY Study Produced Higher Figures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS-Babies Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state Health Department study indicated about
one in every 116 women giving birth in New York state carried the
AIDS virus, far higher than the 1 in 476 results in a similar
Massachusetts study.
   The New York study, conducted in November, showed 161 positive
tests from 18,700 infants examined in the state. In New York City,
there were 148 positive test results from 9,000 infants examined _
a rate of one in 61. The figure was even higher in the city's
poorer neighborhoods, with a figure of one in 43 in the Bronx.
   An infant's immune system reflects its mother's system. An
infant testing positive for the presence of AIDS antibodies almost
always got the virus through an infected mother.
   The Massachusetts study found that one of every 476 women giving
birth, or 2.1 for each 1,000, were infected with the AIDS virus. At
three inner-city Boston hospitals, eight per 1,000 were infected _
a rate of one per 125 births.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1926EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Delvalle'sRole     03-02 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delvalle's Role,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How Delvalle the Meek Became Delvalle the Martyr</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week ago Eric Arturo Delvalle was reviled as
a figurehead president of Panama whose chief purpose was to provide
a democratic fig leaf to the military forces who ran the country.
   Now Delvalle the Meek has become Delvalle the Martyr. In the
Reagan administration's view, he could become a Panamanian version
of Philippines President Corazon Aquino, the lightning rod for
Democratic opposition to former Philippines President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   Much of the Reagan administration's strategy toward Panama over
the past few days has been built around Delvalle and his claim to
be Panama's constitutional president.
   He is an integral part of the U.S. ``chipmunk strategy'' toward
Panama. The State Department wants to keep gnawing at Panama's
economy, at military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega's claim to
legitimacy and his support at home and abroad.
   Noriega is the chieftain of Panama's armed forces, and,
according to a federal indictment handed up in Miami, a cocaine
smuggler.
   Eventually, in the administration's hopes, Noriega will find his
hold on power has evaporated and pack up.
   In defying Noriega and ordering him stripped of power, Devalle
provided a democratic symbol around whom Panamanians could rally.
   Delvalle's image as a powerless front man dates back to when he
took office in the fall of 1985. Noriega was unhappy with the
president at the time, Nicolas Ardito Barletta, because of an
independent streak, and he forced Barletta from office.
   Delvalle was sworn in as president under the most unpromising of
circumstances. In effect, he had to behave according to Noriega's
wishes or he would end up like Barletta. He carried that burden for
two years.
   A mystique has developed around Delvalle since he tried to fire
Noriega and wound up out of office himself. Rather than flee the
country after his dismissal, he went into hiding, issuing
proclamations to his countrymen, making videotaped messages and
frustrating efforts by Noriega's forces to locate him.
   One of his chief allies these days is Gabriel Lewis, a former
ambassador to Washington who is now a captain of the anti-Noriega
campaign in exile.
   To hear Lewis tell it, Delvalle had wanted to break with Noriega
for five months but was reluctant to do so because of ``confusing''
signals from Washington.
   Lewis says Noriega has been suspicious of Delvalle's intentions
for some time and kept telling the president, ``Don't act against
me because the gringos are behind me.''
   This was based on what Noriega felt were reassuring visits by
emissaries from Washington, including Assistant Defense Secretary
Richard Armitage.
   A turning point occurred in early January, Lewis said, when
Panamanian opposition leaders gathered in Miami and Delvalle sent
an envoy.
   ``The emissary told us that if we gave him (Delvalle) assurances
that we would support him, he was ready to act and dismiss
Noriega,'' Lewis said.
   ``We sent him back a message,'' Lewis said. He said the message
was: ``We have heard that many times. We want deeds and not words.
If you fire Noriega and his cronies, we will give you support.''
   Contacts with Lewis and other Noriega opponents continued, with
some messages being passed by Delvalle's dentist in Florida.
Another turning point took place in early February when two Florida
grand juries charged that Noriega was a key figure in an
international drug smuggling ring.
   With an end to the ambiguity in Washington's position, the
opposition front suggested that Delvalle travel to Washington to
announce his break with Noriega before the Organization of American
States.
   Delvalle agreed, but had second thoughts. He reasoned that
firing Noriega at OAS headquarters in Washington might be seen ``as
acting on instructions from the United States,'' Lewis said.
   But was Delvalle getting cold feet?
   At Lewis' instigation, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., called
Delvalle to give him encouragement. On Feb. 17, Delvalle was in
Miami and invited Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams to
visit him.
   If Delvalle was ousted for trying to fire Noriega, Abrams
assured him, the United States would support him as Panama's
constitutional president, Lewis said.
   Eight days later, in an important moment in Panama's tumultuous
history, Delvalle acted.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for The
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
