<DOCNO> AP880302-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1925EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WallStreetEditing     03-02 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street Editing,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filmmakers Agree to Trim Ethnic Slur From Video</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director Oliver Stone and producer Edward
Pressman have agreed to trim a slur against Puerto Ricans from the
home video version of ``Wall Street'' following complaints from the
Hispanic community.
   State Sen. Olga Mendez said Wednesday the comment during
dialogue between actors Charlie Sheen and Sylvia Miles will be
missing when the movie is released on video.
   ``It took just a week for negotiations to remove it,'' said
Mendez. ``It shows very clearly they are very sensitive to people's
feelings.''
   According to Mendez, ex-deputy mayor Kenneth Lipper acted as
mediator in the negotiations to remove the line in question.
Lipper, who also served as a technical advisor to the film, said
the line was included to demonstrate the greed and bigotry of the
Miles' character, a real estate agent.
   In the box office hit, Sheen is trying to sell his New York
apartment. Miles, explaining that will be no easy task, tells him,
``The only things moving in New York are Puerto Ricans and
cockroaches.''
   Pressman, in a letter to Mendez, agreed to trim the comment.
   ``As you know, Oliver Stone and I are identified with such
progressive films as `The Revolutionary,' `Walker,' `Salvador' and
`Platoon,''' he wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
