<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HidingElephants     03-02 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hiding Elephants,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man On The Lam With Two 3{-Ton Elephants</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY STERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who has been on the lam for nearly
four years with a pair of 3{-ton elephants says he'll come in from
the cold if he is assured that Tory and Duchess will not be
returned to two men he alleges brutalized them.
   Arlan Seidon raised the Indian elephants from infancy and then
sold them to Edward Drake. In May 1984, he and the 7-foot-high
beasts disappeared in a tractor-trailer.
   He surfaced last week when he called a newspaper from an
undisclosed location to say he'd surrender if guaranteed that the
elephants will not be returned to Drake and his father, Richard.
   ``I want to make sure where they are going to. I don't feel that
I'm going to spend this much time trying to protect them so they
end up back with the Drakes,'' Seidon told The Star-Ledger of
Newark.
   ``I know I sound like a crazy old man but I'm not,'' he said.
   The elephants' owners and the president of a national animal
trainers group say the animals were not harmed, and both sides
accuse each other of lacking an elephant-like memory about the
incident.
   Edward Drake says Seidon sold him the elephants for $80,000 in
1981, when the Drakes owned an exotic animal ranch in Tehachapi,
Calif., about 200 miles north of Los Angeles.
   Drake said Tuesday that Seidon acted as his booking agent for
animal shows after the sale but began cheating, taking money and
finally the elephants while a circus was in New Jersey.
   Seidon told The Star-Ledger he exercised the terms of the sale
contract by repossessing the elephants when the Drakes fell behind
in their payments.
   While waiting for money at a Colts Neck Township farm, Seidon
said, he discovered the animals had wounds caused by hooks piercing
their skin during training. On May 4, 1984, after a Superior Court
judge in Monmouth County ordered the elephants returned, he fled
with them.
   His attorney, Estelle Strauss, said Tuesday her client never
stole money and that he only wanted to help Tory and Duchess.
   ``The elephants' condition was never aired at the trial,'' said
Ms. Strauss. ``He had an agreement that he could repossess the
animals if they were abused. His position has not changed.''
   But Edward Drake, who like his father is now out of the animal
business, said Seidon's story about the elephants' treatment is
``so far-fetched it's unbelievable.''
   John Cuneo, president of the Illinois-based National Congress of
Animal Trainers and Breeders, said the Drakes did not abuse their
animals. ``They had beautiful elephants. I even wanted to buy
one,'' he said.
   Cuneo said anyone concerned about an animal's condition can
alert state, federal and private monitoring authorities.
   Seidon has forsaken his Fordland, Mo., farm and his career
preparing animals for circus and television appearances to care for
his 25-year-old elephants, who eat about 200 pounds of hay a day.
   Ms. Strauss said she does not know where or how Seidon conceals
the elephants. He calls her periodically to check on his case, she
said.
   She said he would come forward to face criminal charges _
third-degree theft carrying a sentence of up to five years in
prison, a $100,000 fine or both _ if he wins a safe haven for the
elephants. The attorney filed a court motion last week to overturn
the judgment awarding the animals to the Drakes.
   County Assistant Prosecutor Alton Kenney said he was not ready
to discuss any deals for Seidon and had not heard from Ms. Strauss.
</TEXT>
