<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     03-02 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Acknowledges Anti-Semitic Excesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party said Wednesday a
sweeping political purge of two decades ago showed ``manifestations
of anti-Semitism,'' but it added that most party members took no
part in the religious bias.
   More than 9,000 Jews lost official positions in the 1968
``anti-Zionist'' purge, and an estimated 12,000-20,000 emigrated,
more than half the Jews then living in Poland.
   The acknowledgement of anti-Semitism by the party newspaper
Trybuna Ludu carried the authority of an official statement. It
also was repeated by the state-run news agency PAP and reported
prominently on state TV and radio.
   But one leader of the 1968 student protests which sparked the
purge said the newspaper's article did not go far enough in its
condemnation of anti-Semitism and that it repeated past slanders
against Jews.
   It ``amounts to drawing wool over people's eyes,'' said Adam
Michnik, a writer and prominent leader of Poland's anti-government
opposition.
   The article in Trybuna Ludu, the official daily of the Polish
United Workers (Communist) Party, was timed to coincide with the
20th anniversary of the 1968 ``events.''
   Discrimination against Jews, in the guise of ``anti-Zionism''
which had begun after the June 1967 Israeli victory in the Middle
East war, accelerated sharply after March 1968 student
demonstrations around the country against censorship.
   The purge, which began within the party, soon spread to the
government, army, academia, press and other official institutions,
   The newspaper said some conservative, nationalist party factions
at the time ``took advantage of the Jewish ancestry'' of their
political rivals.
   ``They did not realize then that they were being manipulated by
various political factions which in different ways made use of
their actions.''
   Some Western histories have charged that students were provoked
by conservative factions using them to provide a pretext for a
purge.
   Poland was home to about 3.5 million Jews before the war, who
represented about 10 percent of the population. Estimates vary, but
the number of Jews in the country now is believed to be between
7,000 and 15,000.
   Explaining the origins of the anti-Semitism, Trybuna Ludu
referred to support of Israel expressed by some Polish Jews after
the 1967 war and prominent roles held by Jews during the Stalinist
period of the late 1940s to early 1950s.
   ``Polish people preserved the memory of unlawful conduct, of
violation of law and order, and of the perpetrators of those
offenses. It was easy in 1968 to use that memory as a background
for presenting the `alien ... group' as the source of all evil,''
it said.
   But the article added that these explanations ``by no means''
could excuse anti-Semitic acts in Poland.
   Michnik, referring to the explanations, said, ``All the
obscenities of the March (1968) propaganda campaign have been
repeated, all of them. What has been done is nothing but
cosmetics.''
   A leading party theoretician and journalist, Ludwik Krasucki,
said Tuesday on Polish TV that the party's attempts to reconsider
the history of the period were vital.
   He expressed hope that by thoroughly reexamining the 1968
events, ``this chapter, which nevertheless can't be forgotten,
shall once and for all be closed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1516EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   03-02 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Open On Optimistic Note, But Difficult Problems Remain</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators on Wednesday launched their latest and
possibly last round of Afghanistan peace talks, and the U.N.
mediator said he was confident of forging a settlement to end
Soviet involvement in the country.
   ``This was a good session,'' Pakistan's acting foreign minister,
Zain Noorani, said as he emerged from the first closed-door meeting
late Wednesday. ``We are cautiously optimistic.''
   Pakistan is representing the Afghan guerrillas in the talks.
   Afghanistan's foreign minister, Abdul Wakil, told reporters that
his meeting with mediator Diego Cordovez was ``very nice.''
   Cordovez has been the go-between since the indirect negotiations
began nearly six years ago. Because Pakistan refuses to recognize
Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government, the delegations sit in
separate rooms, with Cordovez shuttling back and forth.
   Before the talks opened, Cordovez told reporters he believed
both sides had the ``political will'' to work out an agreement.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced last month that if
a settlement were signed by March 15, the withdrawal of an
estimated 115,000 Red Army troops from Afghanistan could begin by
May 15.
   The Soviets intervened in 1979 to back the Kabul government in
its war with Moslem guerrillas.
   Pakistan wants any settlement to be accompanied by formation of
a transitional government, replacing the present one headed by
President Najib.
   It argues that only a broad-based government could prevent new
bloodshed in a country where war has already claimed more than a
million lives.
   Cordovez said the new talks would ``last as long as necessary''
to reach an agreement and added, ``Perhaps it will be signed
earlier than you think.''
   He said some ``difficult'' problems remained but said he was
sure they could be resolved soon.
   Cordovez didn't say what those problems were, but reports have
suggested they focus on the timetable for the Soviet withdrawal and
the timing of the cutoff of military aid to the warring sides.
   The United States last year gave an estimated $700 million worth
of military assistance to the 200,000 insurgents fighting the
Soviets and the smaller Afghan forces.
   Noorani said Pakistan will decide next week whether it is
prepared to sign a settlement with the present Afghan leadership.
The decision will come after consultations Sunday between Prime
Minister Mohammed Khan Junejo and political leaders, including
those from opposition groups.
   Pakistan has argued that under current conditions, the more than
3 million Afghan refugees in Pakistan and another 2 million in Iran
could not return home.
   Cordovez said, ``Civil strife is part of the way of life
there,'' and he said there was a ``posibility'' that it would
continue. But he added that he believed that the ``people of
Afghanistan are tired of this conflict, that they want peace.''
   Cordovez said he had been in contact with representatives of
several countries, including the United States, the Soviet Union,
the European Community and Australia, to discuss humanitarian aid
to Afghanistan after a settlement.
   ``I have the feeling that there will be a broad international
effort,'' he said.
   The sense of optimism was not shared by Iran, which is not
participating in the talks. Tehran has refused to participate as
long as the Moslem resistance is not invited.
   Iranian ambassador Sirous Nasseri told reporters that Iran
attaches ``no significance to the settlement as it is being
forumulated here.'' He said the main problems were related to
formation of a government acceptable to all Afghans and the phasing
of the Soviet pullout.
   ``I doubt very much that this could be solved here,'' he said.
</TEXT>
