<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ClubChallenge     03-02 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Club Challenge,0698</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Woman Challenges Exclusivity of All-Male Clubs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Harvard student who contends she is
being excluded from the breeding grounds of power is challenging
the membership policies of nine exclusive all-male student clubs.
   In her complaint before Massachusetts Commission Against
Discrimination, Lisa J. Schkolnick argues that the Fly and eight
other ``final clubs'' may be violating state laws prohibiting
sexual discrimination in public institutions by refusing to admit
women.
   Schkolnick said in a recent interview that she picked the Fly at
random as the target of her suit, and considers it representative
of the other clubs. The commission, a quasi-legal entity, has the
power to investigate cases, award damages, and seek injuctions.
   The clubhouses are located in some of the most expensive real
estate holdings in and around Harvard Square, discreetly shielded
by tall hedges and unmarked doors. Some have separate entraces for
women visitors.
   They were originally called final clubs to distinguish them from
waiting clubs _ less exclusive, now extinct organizations. Evolving
from fraternities to eating clubs in the past century, they became
social meeting places by the 1950s. Past members have included both
Franklin and Theodore Roosevelt and several members of the Kennedy
clan.
   Harvard formally severed ties to the clubs in 1984, after
members refused a university demand to admit women. But
Schkolnick's case rests on the argument that the clubs remain an
integral part of student life and cannot be considered private.
   The issue has become a major topic of debate on campus.
   The undergraduate student council last week narrowly rejected a
proposal to endorse Schkolnik's cause, but voted to reimburse $250
in office costs to a lawyer who offered to help her without a fee.
   Harvard Law Professor Alan Dershowitz expressed moral support,
urging council members to back Schkolnick.
   ``I think it's the first major challenge to what have been very
entrenched institutions at Harvard,'' Dershowitz said in an
interview. ``These finals clubs are the minor leagues for the power
clubs in the major cities, the all-male ones.''
   Dershowitz, a former Yale student, compared the clubs to Yale
groups ``so secret I didn't even know about them until I
graduated,'' and to Princeton University's two remaining all-male
eating clubs, now appealing a state order to admit women.
   Barbara Bolten, vice president of public relations in the Boston
chapter of the National Organization for Women said, ``We support
the philosophy of what she's doing totally, and I hope she wins.''
   Schkolnick, a 21-year-old philosophy senior from Princeton,
N.J., said she was the target of a rash of crank calls, ``some
obscene, others frightening,'' for several weeks after she filed
her complaint Dec. 14.
   She suggested that the clubs serve as old-boy networks to the
detriment of women.
   ``These are power centers, and these people are being fed into
powerful positions, and women are being excluded,'' she said. ``I'm
going to be a lawyer one day, and I could have used some of these
positions that members are exposed to.''
   The clubs, in turn, deny that their members gain undue advantage
through networking and argue they are strictly private
organizations which should be allowed to decide on membership.
   ``There are some people in the clubs established in business,
but it's definitely not an institutionalized process through which
you secure interviews through alumni,'' said Stan Novak, former
president of the Fox final club.
   Novak, who graduated last year, was the only one of several
final club members polled on the controversy willing to go on the
record. Judith Malone, a lawyer retained by the Fly, declined
comment.
   The clubs do not publicize their membership rolls. But several
students estimated that more than 10 percent of Harvard's
undergraduate males belong. Total undergraduate enrollment is about
6,400.
   Novak said membership didn't help him in his job search.
   ``The fact that after being president for a year, I was still
sitting around from June till Jan. 1, that will give you an idea
about ... how effective alumni ties are,'' said Novak, of
Barrington, R.I.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
