<DOCNO> AP880302-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1940EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-PrisonCosts     03-02 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Prison Costs,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Urged To Block States From Seizing Inmates' Federal Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court was urged on Wednesday to
block states from recouping the costs of keeping criminals behind
bars by seizing money which prison inmates receive in federal
benefits.
   Lawyers representing the Reagan administration and a former
prison inmate attacked an Arkansas law that let authorities seize
for state use an inmate's Social Security or Veterans
Administration benefits.
   They said the law, similar to those enacted in four other
states, conflicts with federal laws specificially barring any legal
action aimed at diverting benefits away from designated recipients.
   ``Congress could have made an exception for state institutional
care,'' argued Justice Department lawyer Richard J. Lazarus. ``But
Congress has not done so here. In our view, that is simply the end
of the issue.''
   Thomas M. Carpenter, a Little Rock lawyer representing former
state prison inmate George Bennett, also contended that the
Arkansas law ``must fall.''
   The issue before the high court is not whether those inmates
with available money may be charged for their imprisonment but
whether states may get at money the inmates receive in federal
benefits.
   The impact of the justices' decision, expected by July, has been
blunted somewhat by laws passed by Congress in 1980 and 1983
withholding or limiting benefits otherwise due imprisoned felons.
   The justices asked few questions, and what had been scheduled as
a hour-long argument session was over in 35 minutes.
   Bennett had served 11 years of a 21-year sentence at a Pine
Bluff prison for second-degree murder when he turned 62. He started
receiving $275 a month in Social Security retirement benefits.
Bennett was released from prison in late 1984 but is seeking to
recover $3,600 in benefits confiscated by the state.
   The Arkansas Legislature in 1981 had passed an Inmate Care and
Custody Reimbursement Act. Under it, state authorities may seek
court approval to seize an inmate's estate _ income from any source.
   Similar laws have been enacted in Michigan, Ohio, Oklahoma and
Tennessee.
   Reagan administration lawyers had told the justices in briefs
submitted previously that the rationale used by the Arkansas
Supreme Court in upholding the 1981 state law ``would seem to
validate the attachment of Social Security and VA benefits paid to
persons confined in state mental hospitals or in other institutions
where they are provided care by the state.''
   They said it is important for the Arkansas law to be invalidated
so the growing number of states asking prison inmates to help foot
the bill of their imprisonment will not seize federal benefits.
   Arkansas Attorney General Steve Clark told the justices
Wednesday that Arkansas merely was trying to prevent ``windfall
benefits'' for prison inmates who receive their food, clothing and
medical care at state expense.
   Clark said Congress' intent of protecting people ``from the
rigors of poverty'' was ``not frustrated by the Arkansas statute at
all.''
   Responding to Clark's contention that the state had not
``created any kind of hardship,'' Carpenter said his client could
make good use of the money wrongly withheld from him.
   Carpenter described Bennett as ``a 69-year-old man who can't get
a job'' and who would be destitute if he had not been cared for by
relatives.
   The case is Bennett vs. Arkansas, 86-6124.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
