<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CampusTakeover     03-02 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campus Takeover,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students End Nine-Day Occupation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nine-day sit-in by minority students at
Hampshire College ended Wednesday with the signing of a 16-point
agreement designed to encourage racial harmony at the small private
school.
   ``The acceptance of our demands by the administration is both an
acknowledgment of institutional indifference and neglect and of the
immediate need for redress,'' Anita Fearman, a spokeswoman for the
protesters, told a gathering of 150 students.
   The group watched as college President Adele Simmons and two
other administrators signed the document outside the dormitory
office occupied by an estimated 40 protesters since Feb. 23.
   The six-page settlement provided for a dean of multicultural
affairs, an adviser for the group that occupied Dakin House office
and at least $4,500 in yearly funding for the group.
   The adminstration also agreed to take no disciplinary action
against the students and to allow them to make up work they missed
during the sit-in.
   ``I think the institution won,'' Simmons said after the signing.
``For the last several years we've been working to improve student
life and this represents a finishing of the old agenda.
   ``A number of the things they asked for were already in place,
but I think the occupation strengthened the institution,'' she said.
   Dean of Students Trey Williams said the occupation had taken a
toll on many at the liberal arts school, where about 100 of the
1,100 students are minorities.
   ``The students are exhausted, the president is sick. But it's
better that it took us only one week than forever,'' he said.
   The occupation was prompted by what students described as the
school's longstanding indifference to their concerns.
   ``They were claiming this is a multiculturally diverse
community, which isn't true,'' said protester Penny Predmas.
   College officials said the allegation was a surprise, given the
school's image as a progressive alternative to the sort of
traditional liberal arts education offered at nearby Amherst, Mount
Holyoke and Smith colleges. Hampshire students design their own
courses of study and graduate after passing three divisional
examinations requiring them to complete individual research
projects and some classwork.
   ``We're way in front in transforming curriculum to be much more
global,'' said Faculty Dean Penina Glazer, ``but we're lagging in
recruiting of minority students and we're trying as hard as we
can.''
   The agreement came two weeks after the end of an occupation at
nearby University of Massachusetts that was sparked by campus
racial violence. That takeover ended when Chancellor Joseph Duffey
agreed to increase funding of minority student programs and other
demands.
   A university disciplinary hearing began Tuesday into allegations
that five white male students assaulted two black male students on
Feb. 7, said spokeswoman Jeanne Hopkins.
   Protesters at Hampshire said racial violence is rare on their
campus, but said there have been several instances of harassment
and discrimination since a cross was found burning on a building
lawn 11 years ago.
   The protesters said, however, that the sympathy shown them by
students and faculty during the occupation had changed their minds
about warning minorities away from the school.
   ``I really would tell them to come here,'' said Predmas.
   A few white students watching the signing ceremony said they
supported the protesters' aims, but disagreed over the wisdom of
occupying the dormitory office.
   ``There basically was a lot of friction,'' said Paul Trunnell.
``The feeling was, `Either you're in or out. Either you support us
or you don't.' Well, no two of us agreed on this campus, but it's
important that we band together to solve these sorts of problems.''
</TEXT>
