<DOCNO> AP880302-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1943EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     03-02 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He's Stable, Steady</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush called
himself ``the most stable'' candidate Wednesday, crediting himself
with good judgment that sets him apart in the presidential race.
   ``You want steadiness. You want judgment. You want even
temperament,'' Bush said. He added that a president ``can't make
these outrageous claims.''
   Bush didn't elaborate, but in recent days he has disputed rival
GOP candidate Pat Robertson's contentions concerning Soviet
missiles in Cuba, Robertson's knowledge of U.S. hostage whereabouts
in Lebanon and the possibility the Bush campaign tried to hurt
Robertson by manipulating the timing of allegations against TV
evangelist Jimmy Swaggart.
   In a much-publicized Iowa flap one month ago, a Bush aide
questioned Dole's temperament, calling him ``mean-spirited.''
   Bush commented Wednesday after seeing U.S. Navy warships in
drydock at the Ingalls Shipyard here. He was accompanied by former
Navy Secretary John Lehman.
   The vice president told the shipyard workers that Democratic
candidate Michael Dukakis wanted to reduce the number of Navy
battleships. Bush called that ``a dumb idea.''
   Beginning his day in Clearwater, Fla., Bush talked of his five
children _ including Florida Secretary of Commerce Jeb Bush _ and
10 grandchildren, and also said his support of prayer in the
schools is of long standing.
   ``They ought to take a look at my family and what I epitomize in
this regard,'' Bush told reporters.
   Bush also served boiled crawfish at a small rally in Biloxi,
Miss., spoke briefly to supporters at the Mobile, Ala., airport and
planned to participate in a Cajun feast in Baton Rouge, La., before
heading to Greenville, S.C.
   At the shipyard here, Bush saw the USS Stark, the Navy ship
damaged last year by Iraqi missiles in the Persian Gulf. It is
being overhauled and repaired. He also toured the first of a new
class of amphibious assault ships called the LHD Class.
   He spoke of the expansion of the Navy under the Reagan
administration and Lehman.
   On Tuesday, Bush was accompanied through Florida by former Sen.
Barry Goldwater of Arizona.
   ``Goldwater is right when he says George Bush will be the best
president,'' Bush said in Mobile. ``I can think of no single
endorsement more helpful than that of Barry Goldwater.''
   The Bush campaign plans to use a Goldwater endorsement
commercial in some of the Southern states voting in the March 8
Super Tuesday primary.
</TEXT>
