<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1947EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ScotusRdp     03-02 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus Rdp,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Throws Out Award to City Employee Over Firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Wednesday made it more
difficult for people to win lawsuits against a city government
based on claims that low-ranking officials violated their rights.
   But the decision in a St. Louis case yielded no clear-cut
majority view and left some key questions unanswered
   By a 7-1 vote, the justices threw out a $15,000 award St. Louis
was ordered to pay James J. Praprotnik, a fired city architect.
   But only four of the seven justices voting to overturn the award
joined in the court's main opinion, creating the possibility that a
future case could prompt a different result.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, who wrote the court's main opinion,
said generally only the highest ranking city officials can commit
constitutional violations that make the city liable.
   In the case of St. Louis, that is limited to the mayor, city
aldermen and the civil service commission, she said.
   Cities may not be held liable unless those who claim their
rights were violated prove the ``existence of an unconstitutional
municipal policy,'' O'Connor said.
   A city cannot be sued successfully based on the claim that
high-ranking officials failed to override a subordinate's decision
that violated someone's rights, she added.
   ``Simply going along with discretionary decisions made by one's
subordinates ... is not a delegation to them of the authority to
make policy,'' O'Connor said.
   She also said that state law, and not a jury's examination of
the facts in a particular case, determines who the policy makers
are in a city.
   Justice William J. Brennan, in a separate opinion, said
O'Connor's opinion ``turns a blind eye to reality'' in assuming who
makes policy in a particular community.
   Brennan said O'Connor's opinion ``ultimately would permit
municipalities to insulate themselves from liability for the acts
of all but a small minority of actual city policy makers.''
   Brennan's opinion was joined by Justices Thurgood Marshall and
Harry A. Blackmun. Nonetheless, all three voted with O'Connor and
three other justices to throw out Praprotnik's $15,000 award. They
said a St. Louis official who transferred Praprotnik to a job that
led to his firing lacked policy-making authority.
   O'Connor's opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Byron R. White and Antonin Scalia.
   Justice John Paul Stevens dissented, voting to uphold
Praprotnik's lower court victory. Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who
only recently joined the court, did not take part in the decision.
   Praprotnik was a mid-level manager in St. Louis' community
development agency when in 1980 he became embroiled with his
superiors over the proposed installation by the city of a
controversial sculpture.
   Praprotnik was suspended for 15 days by a superior for having
accepted outside employment without prior approval. But after he
appealed to the city civil service commission, he was reinstated
with back pay.
   Then in 1982 he was transferred to another city agency, and his
job responsibilities were reduced. He was fired, in what the city
said was a budget-cutting move, on Dec. 30, 1983.
   Praprotnik then sued under a federal civil rights law, charging
he was shunted to a dead-end job and then kicked out because of his
appeal to the civil service commission for his suspension back in
1980.
   A jury awarded him $30,000. The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals reduced the amount to $15,000 while ruling he was fired for
exercising his constitutional rights.
   The appeals court said the city was liable, even though the jury
exonerated the individual officials sued by Praprotnik.
   The justices on Wednesday ordered further lower court hearings
for Praprotnik to determine whether he still has a viable case.
   In another ruling, the justices, by a 4-4 vote, ruled that an
airline may be forced to continue to collect union dues from
workers after its contract with employees has expired.
   The court upheld rulings that forced Trans World Airlines to
continue the dues check-off for replacement employees during a
strike by flight attendants in 1986. TWA also was forced to collect
dues from the strikers once they returned to work.
   The ruling was not accompanied by any written opinion or by any
indication of how each individual justice voted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1536EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FactoryOrders     03-02 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Factory Orders,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orders Decline 0.6 Percent In January</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that
orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in
January, the first decline in five months, but private economists
said the setback was not serious.
   The report said orders for both durable and non-durable goods
dropped to a seasonally adjusted $212.6 billion in January, down
$1.25 billion from December, when orders had posted a huge 2
percent increase.
   It was the first setback in orders since a 1.4 percent drop in
August, but economists discounted the decline, contending that it
reflected a swing in the volatile transportation category.
   Transportation orders declined 8.8 percent in January, erasing
an 8.9 percent December increase, which had reflected a big jump in
orders for passenger jets.
   Without the large swings in transportation, factory orders would
have climbed 0.8 percent in January following a 0.9 percent
December rise.
   Manufacturing has been enjoying steady increases over the past
year as American producers enjoy booming export sales spurred by
the decline in the value of the dollar.
   Lawrence Chimerine, president of the WEFA Group, a private
forecasting firm, said that the January factory orders showed more
strength than analysts had been expecting.
   He said manufacturing demand is holding up well despite a large
increase in business inventories during the final three months of
the year. The big inventory rise has raised concerns that orders
will need to be cut until the backlog of unsold goods is reduced.
   ``The inventory scare may be somewhat overblown. If it was that
serious, we would probably see orders weakening more sharply,'' he
said. ``While the economy is not booming, manufacturing is still on
an upward trend and we are likely to miss a recession.''
   The Reagan administration is counting on continued strength in
export sales to provide almost half of the expected growth in the
overall economy this year.
   The January decline in manufactured goods included a 1.5 percent
drop in demand for durable goods. An advance report a week ago put
the January decline in durable goods at 2.8 percent. Orders for
non-durable goods, items not expected to last at least three years,
rose 0.5 percent in January, erasing a 0.5 percent December decline.
   Demand for military equipment fell 3.8 percent in January
following a 7.1 percent drop in December.
   Orders for non-defense capital goods, a key category which
reflects industry plans to expand and modernize, rose 2.6 percent
in January following a 12.6 percent December advance.
   Shipments of manufactured goods fell 1.7 percent in January to
$207.7 billion following a 2 percent December increase.
</TEXT>
