<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     03-02 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0758</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least One Reported Killed in Ethnic Rioting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note spelling of Azerbaijan, sted Azerbaidzhan, reflects a
change in AP style.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least one person was killed in ethnic riots in
a southern republic but the violence was short-lived, a Soviet
television employee in the region said Wednesday.
   The violence occurred Sunday in Sumgait, an industrial city of
more than 160,000 people in Azerbaijan. The newspaper in Baku, the
republic's capital, did not mention casualties in its report
Wednesday, but said arrests were made.
   ``Order and peace have been ensured by law enforcement organs.
People caught in the unrest have been detained,'' said the
newspaper, Bakinsky Rabochy. It did not give the number of arrests.
   Trouble between Armenians and Azerbaijanis began when ethnic
Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh, a region assigned to Azerbaijan,
began demonstrating for union with the neighboring Caucasian
republic of Armenia. The protest spread to Armenia's capital,
Yerevan.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said Tuesday he
could not confirm reports by Armenian activists that up to 20
people were killed in Sumgait, but added: ``There was hooliganism
and there can be deaths in such cases.''
   The television worker reached by telephone mentioned a ``small
number of victims.'' He identified himself as a duty officer at the
Baku broadcast studios but would not give his namem,
   Pressed for a figure, he said one or two people were killed. He
said he did not know the circumstances of the deaths, but gave a
description of how the riots began.
   About 50 to 60 young ethnic Azerbaijanis who live in Armenia
traveled to Sumgait last weekend and spoke of ethnic problems in
Armenia, he said.
   ``They were frightened,'' said the television employee, who said
he was half Armenian and half Azerbaijani. ``When they told their
relatives, and friends at the vocational school, everyone got very
excited.''
   A group of ``young hooligans'' then went on a rampage, he said.
``It's not a nationality problem, it's just hooliganism,'' he
declared, adding that the violence was limited to Sunday.
   The official media have not reported on causes of the
disturbance. They said Wednesday that Sumgait was calm.
   ``The unrest has been stopped,'' the Baku paper said.
``Businesses and establishments of trade and public dining places
are working in a normal rhythm and classes are taking place in
schools.''
   Gerasimov read the newspaper article to The Associated Press
over the telephone. Copies of the paper itself won't reach Moscow
for several days.
   It and Baku radio said Azerbaijan's premier, Gasan N. Seidov,
had traveled to Sumgait.
   Gerasimov told the news briefing Tuesday that authorities put
Sumgait under curfew. He suggested the unrest there and elsewhere
in the Caucasus was due to ``mistakes'' made 65 years ago when a
territory inhabited largely by Armenians was made part of
Azerbaijan.
   More than three-quarters of the 157,000 people in
Nagorno-Karabakh are ethnic Armenians.
   Predominantly Moslem Azerbaijan is the largest of three Soviet
republics in the region, bordered on the west by largely Christian
Armenia and Georgia and on the north by the Russian republic. The
Caspian Sea runs for nearly 800 miles along its eastern edge.
   Foreign journalists based in Moscow have been barred from the
region and only sporadic reports from witnesses, activists and
official media have reached Moscow. Few telephone calls got through
to Baku and Sumgait on Wednesday.
   A man answering the telephone at the Azerbaijan Interior
Ministry in Baku said ``everything is over'' in Sumgait. The
conversation was cut off before a reporter could ask his name and
position.
   Baku radio, monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp., said
two non-voting members of the national Communist Party Politburo,
Georgy P. Razumovsky and Pyotr N. Demichev, visited businesses and
other establishments in Baku to speak to ``working people of these
multinational collectives.''
   It did not say when they were there or whether they went to
Sumgait.
   Hovik Vassilian said by telephone from Yerevan on Wednesday he
had learned from travelers and telephone calls to residents that
protests continued in Nagorno-Karabakh and food was in short supply.
   A Soviet prosecutor reported Saturday that two people living in
a part of Azerbaijan bordering Nagorno-Karabakh had been slain in
unrest linked to the territorial dispute.
   On Friday, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed for
restraint, and said the Central Committee would review relations
among the Soviet Union's more than 100 nationalities.
</TEXT>
