<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LorraineResident     03-02 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lorraine Resident,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Resident Evicted From Motel Where King Shot</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last resident of the small motel where
Martin Luther King Jr. died refused orders from sheriff's deputies
to leave the rundown building Wednesday and was carried sobbing to
the sidewalk.
   ``You people are making a mistake. You people are making a
mistake,'' said Jacqueline Smith, 37, who had been holed up at The
Lorraine Motel since it was closed by state order Jan. 11 to make
way for an $8.8 million civil rights museum.
   Deputies evicted Ms. Smith after forcing open the door to the
room where she had set up residence. A picture of King and an
American flag decorated the large front window of her room, about
25 feet from where the civil rights leader was felled by an
assassin's rifle slug.
   They carried her to the sidewalk outside the chain-link fence
surrounding the motel, put her down and walked away.
   ``I refuse to stand up,'' she said. A few moments later,
however, she moved to a straight-back wooden chair retrieved from
her belongings stacked nearby under a sheet of black plastic to
keep off a light rain.
   ``If I have to sit out here on this street, I refuse to go,''
she said. ``I'm not going anywyere.''
   Ms. Smith, who has lived and worked at the Lorraine for 11
years, said the museum project will speed efforts to gentrify her
low-income neighborhood.
   ``I'm trying to help the people who live in this area. We're
being forced out,'' she said.
   Ms. Smith said she has relatives in other parts of town, but
does not want to move from neighborhood. She said she cannot afford
to rent an apartment in the area.
   She said the Lorraine should be turned into housing for the
homeless.
   Her eviction was watched by a crowd of news reporters and about
a dozen spectators. Several well-wishers spoke with Ms. Smith after
the deputies left.
   King was killed at the Lorraine on April 4, 1968 while helping
organize a strike by city sanitation workers.
   James Earl Ray, a prison escapee from Missouri, pleaded guilty
to the killing and is serving a 99-year sentence at the Southeast
Tennessee Regional Prison.
   The Lorraine, which has fallen into disrepair over the years,
was bought at a foreclosure auction in 1982 by a citizens group
pushing plans for a civil rights museum at the site.
   The state has appropriated $4.4 million for the project and city
and county governments have agreed to match that amount. The state
has title to the property and will build and operate the museum,
scheduled to open in 1991.
   Ms. Smith repeatedly ignored requests to move, and the state
obtained a court order Tuesday directing sheriff's deputies to
evict her.
   When deputies arrived, Ms. Smith retreated to her room and
refused to open the door.
   Randy Wade, an administrative assistant to the Shelby County
sheriff, pleaded with her to leave peacefully.
   ``We're just doing our job,'' Wade shouted to Ms. Smith as
deputies prepared to force open the door.
</TEXT>
