<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GoetzInheritance     03-02 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Goetz Inheritance,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subway Gunman Bernard Goetz Inherits $140,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernhard Goetz Jr. has inherited $140,550
from his father's estate, but the man known as the New York subway
gunman has huge legal bills that will quickly eat that up, and
more, his attorney says.
   ``That won't go very far in defending him on anything,'' said
Joseph Kelner, an attorney defending Goetz in three civil cases
asking a total of $63 million in damages.
   Goetz, 40, was sentenced last October to six months in jail and
five years' probation for carrying an unlicensed gun, which he used
to shoot four teen-agers on a subway in December 1984. Three of the
four are suing him for injuries and punitive damages.
   Goetz, who claimed the shootings were in self-defense, is free
on $5,000 bond while his case is appealed.
   His father, Bernhard Willard Goetz Sr., died in 1984, and his
estate was recently settled in Orange County Probate Court. After
payment of taxes, there was $562,200 to be split between the
younger Goetz, his brother and two sisters.
   The estate's attorney, Jerome Bornstein, said Wednesday that all
money had been distributed to the heirs within the past few days.
   The elder Goetz moved to Orlando in 1963 from Rhinebeck, N.Y.,
where the family owned a dairy, a bookbinding company and real
estate. He joined his brothers Fritz and Ludwig in developing a
subdivision in east Orange County.
   Kelner said Tuesday that Goetz, an electronics specialist, can't
afford to take a taxi from Manhattan to the Bronx for civil court
appearances. It's dangerous for Goetz to use public transportation,
the lawyer said.
   One of the shooting victims, James Ramseur, seeks $8.5 million;
another, Troy Canty, has filed two suits for $2.5 million. Darrell
Cabey, who was left a paraplegic from the incident, is suing Goetz
for $50 million.
   Kelner, who is working for Goetz free of charge, said his client
has countersued for $1 ``as a matter of principle because they
foisted this entire incident on him 2{ years ago _ ruining his
life, his business, all of it.''
   Ramseur's lawyer said he was surprised at Goetz's inheritance.
   ``His attorneys have been telling us all along that he doesn't
have a dime,'' said the lawyer, Ron Kliegerman. ``Now we know
there's something there.''
   Goetz has refused to talk to the press in recent weeks.
</TEXT>
