<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 2004EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Anti-HungerBill     03-02 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Hunger Bill,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy, Panetta Introduce Anti-Hunger Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., on Wednesday
unveiled a $266 million Democratic plan to bolster the government's
emergency food programs, saying ``we cannot afford to do less'' to
battle hunger.
   Kennedy, chairman of the Senate Labor and Human Resources
Committee, said the bill would increase funding for federal
programs for food stamps, school breakfasts, child care food and
summer food service.
   ``We have to ask what the cost of not doing this will be,''
Kennedy said at a news conference.
   Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., said the question of hunger is ``a
moral issue'' and ``a test of America's conscience.''
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., introduced companion anti-hunger
legislation in the House.
   Kennedy said domestic hunger had been largely eradicated by the
late 1970s, but that the recession of the early 1980s, coupled with
sharp cuts in social programs under the Reagan administration, has
brought it back at record levels.
   The Emergency Hunger Relief Act of 1988 would focus on the
government's food stamp program, a program started under Kennedy's
brother, John F. Kennedy, in 1961. The senator argued that benefits
for many families are running out well before the end of the month.
   For a typical family of four, the bill would increase benefits
by about six meals per month per person.
   Eligibility modifications would add about 1 million people to
the food stamp program, Kennedy estimated. There now are 18.6
million recipients.
   The bill also would:
   _ Allow other non-profit organizations besides schools and local
governments to operate the Summer Food Service Program. The current
limitations have denied thousands of children nutritious lunches
during the summer when schools are closed, the lawmakers said.
Kennedy said an estimated 170,000 additional children would be
receive benefits under the plan.
   _ Extend the Temporary Food Assistance Program and authorize $50
million annually for the distribution to the needy of corn, wheat
and other surplus commodities.
   _ Increase to $10 million a year the authorization for the
Community Food and Nutrition Program, which funds soup kitchens and
relief centers. The current authorization is at $3 million annually.
   _ Increase school breakfast funding by 3 cents per meal so
children can have eggs on most mornings.
   The bill calls for $266 million in new spending in fiscal 1989
and $675 million in 1990.
   ``We could obviously do more, but we cannot afford to do less,''
Kennedy said. ``The measure ... is designed to be a new declaration
of war on hunger, and this time we intend to see that the war stays
won.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
