<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TempletonPrize     03-02 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Templeton Prize,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Winner Of Religion Prize Works For Harmony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem leader Inamullah Khan, named Wednesday as
winner of the Templeton Prize for progress in religion, said his
lifetime goal is to heal discord among different faiths.
   He is the first Moslem to win the $390,000 prize, the largest in
the world and about $40,000 more than the Nobel prizes.
   ``My life has been spent in the service of mankind seeking peace
where there is war, reconciliation where there is conflict, harmony
where there is discord,'' Khan said.
   Khan, 73, of Karachi, Pakistan, a founder and secretary-general
of the World Moslem Congress, added in a message from his home city:
   ``I do this from my religious conviction and will continue to
work with people of different races and religions and with those of
different views within the same religion.''
   He was cited for his ``tireless work as coordinator for peace
between Moslems, Christians and Jews.''
   At a news conference at the Church Center of the United Nations
where the winner was announced, a Jewish colleague voiced ``great
appreciation'' for Khan's leadership.
   Norma Levitt of New York, who serves with him as one of nine
regional presidents of the World Conference on Religion and Peace,
said the reward was a sign of hope that people of good will can
``live together and advance together in harmony, in justice and in
peace.''
   Khan is chairman of the executive committee and also a regional
president of the World Conference on Religion and Peace.
   Khan, born in Burma of Indian parentage, was editor of Burma's
Moslem Daily until 1942 when Burma was occupied by Japan. He then
moved to India, settling in Karachi when Pakistan was established
in 1948.
   There, he was a founder of the World Moslem Congress, with its
offices initially in his home.
   The annual prize, established in 1972 by American investment
counselor John Templeton, is to recognize those ``who through
original and pioneering ways advanced the knowledge and love of
God.''
   This year's prize is to be presented May 10 in London by
Princess Alexandra.
   Previous winners included 13 Christians, one Hindu and one
Buddhist.
   Templeton, who resides in Nassau, Bahamas, said the award is
intended to encourage people to ``take religion more seriously, to
get excited about the new thinking in it.''
   He told the news conference the prize was purposely kept higher
than the Nobel prizes because religion was more important than
other fields.
   He said world expenditures for scienctific research amount to $1
billion every day, and ``I'm not saying it's not worth the
results,'' but ``it should be equaled by research in the spiritual
realm.''
</TEXT>
