<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MatthewsTrial     03-02 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Matthews Trial,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-agers Knew of Murder Weeks Before Police Notified</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager testified Wednesday that his
14-year-old friend plotted the murder of a classmate, saying he
wanted ``to know what it was like to kill someone.''
   Robbie Peterson, 16, told a hushed courtroom how he was twice
shown the body by Rod Matthews and even accompanied Matthews and
another friend to a pizza parlor to eat after viewing the victim.
   Matthews, 15, went on trial Wednesday as an adult for the murder
of Shaun Ouillette, 14.
   The body remained near a lonely wooded hilltop for three weeks
before another friend wrote an anonymous letter to police.
   ``Rod said not to say anything,'' Peterson said. ``He said it
could happen to us. He said, `You never know.'''
   Norfolk County Assistant District Attorney Peter Casey told the
jury of 12 men and four women that Matthews plotted the death of
his schoolmate for more than a month.
   ``He was deliberate in the plan and put it into effect
efficently and effectively,'' he said.
   In opening arguments, defense attorney John Philip White Jr.
said his client suffered from a ``psychiatric illness of major
proportions'' and was not in contact with reality.
   White said Matthews was affected by his use of Ritalin, a
stimulant used to calm hyperactive children.
   Peterson testified Matthews began talking about killing someone
around Halloween 1986. He refined his plan to lure a victim to a
deserted area known as ``The Pits,'' then beat him with a baseball
bat. Peterson said Matthews also planned to cut off his victim's
legs ``and toss them.''
   ``I said why? He said he wanted to know what it was like to kill
somebody. He said `Just for the heck of it,''' said Peterson.
   The teen-ager, testifying in a barely audible voice, told how
Matthews named several potential victims before settling on
Ouillette, an overweight high school freshman.
   ``He said he (Ouillette) would be the least missed, that he
didn't have that many friends,'' Peterson said.
   Peterson said he had warned other potential victims not to go to
Matthews' home. Although he knew of Matthews' plan to lure
Ouillette into the woods with the promise of fireworks, Peterson
said he only suggested to Ouillette that he have Matthews bring the
fireworks to school.
   Peterson said the day of the murder he saw Matthews walking down
the street with a baseball bat and asked if he killed Ouillette. He
said Matthews hestitated before admitting to the killing, then
agreed to take Peterson to the murder scene after leaving a large
knife in Peterson's room.
   Peterson said Matthews explained how he walked in Ouillette's
footsteps in the snow, then hit him with a bat.
   ``He said Shaun fell down and said `help me' and Rod hit him
again.''
   Ouillette's mother, Jeanne Quinn, sobbed as she heard the
description of her son's murder. Matthews was expressionless.
   White portrayed his client as a youth from a troubled home
obsessed with personal hygiene and fascinated by fire. He told of a
note Matthews wrote to a health teacher a Canton High School which
warned of his plans to kill.
   According to White, the note read in part, ``My problem is that
I like to do crazy things ... lately I want to kill people. I hate
and I want to set houses on fire.''
   White said the teacher made note of the letter on a file card,
but did nothing until after Matthews was arrested.
</TEXT>
