<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 2013EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BiologicalTesting     03-02 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biological Testing,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utah Governor Skeptical Over Army's Proposed Biological Test Lab
Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUGWAY PROVING GROUND, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army's claims that it
does not plan the highest-level of experiments at a proposed
biological testing laboratory drew skepticism Wednesday from Utah
Gov. Norm Bangerter.
   Bangerter, who toured the western desert installation's current
biological test lab Wednesday, told reporters that officials had
given him a different message than he received when he met with
Defense Department representatives last month in Washington.
   He said officials had told him then that ``there's a high
likelihood they're going to be BL-4 (the highest level of biosafety
containment). If they really think they're going to do B-L4, that's
what they ought to clear for,'' the governor said.
   However, Army officials maintained Wednesday the proposed $5.3
million lab at Dugway Proving Ground had plans only for B-L3
experimentation. Dugway spokeswoman Kathy Whitaker stressed that
the new lab's mission would be defensive _ testing soldiers'
protective gear against various biological agents.
   ``The plan is to do B-L3 work. We're overbuilding for the added
safety it gives us,'' she said, noting that the proposed facility
would feature three pressurized labs and double-layered walls over
1,540 square feet.
   Dugway Director of Material Test Col. Wyett Colclasure said
another reason for building the new lab complex to B-L4 guidelines
was cost.
   While the project cost $600,000 more as a B-L4 than B-L3
complex, trying to upgrade the facility later would cost much more,
he said. Colclasure did not say how much more, however.
   Colclasure said the Soviet Union's endeavors in biological
testing made the project a neccessity.
   ``I believe the Soviets are working very diligently on a
biological warfare capability. We must be sensitive to that,'' he
said.
   The Army released an environmental impact statement on the lab
complex in January, saying that construction and operation of the
facility posed no danger to employees, the public at large or the
environment.
   The present B-L2 level test facility at Dugway was established
in 1952. Although it has been modified over the years, the facility
has become inadequate for present-day testing needs because
operators are unable to conduct the full range of tests required,
officials said.
</TEXT>
