<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RacialAssault     03-02 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Assault,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Source Says Brawley Family May Cooperate With Prosecutors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Threats against Tawana Brawley may
soon motivate the family to end a stalemate and begin cooperating
with state prosecutors, according to a report published Wednesday.
   The family of the black Wappingers Falls teen-ager who claims
she was kidnapped and sexually assaulted by six white men in
November is increasingly concerned about her safety, the
Poughkeepsie Journal, said, quoting an anonymous source said to be
close to the family.
   On the advice of her lawyers, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox
Jr., the family has thus far refused to cooperate with Attorney
General Robert Abrams, whom Gov. Mario Cuomo appointed as a special
prosecutor.
   The lawyers want Abrams ousted and a permanent special
prosecutor named to investigate race-related crimes.
   Mason and Maddox did not immediately return telephone calls to
their office Wednesday.
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, a New York City minister who has been
advising the Brawleys, denied that the family was on the verge of
cooperating with authorities and refused to comment on reports
there had been threats against Miss Brawley.
   Sharpton confirmed that he had taken Miss Brawley from the home
of Matthew Strong, the uncle with whom she had been staying since
the attack. He would not say where Miss Brawley was staying.
   A woman who answered the phone at the Brawley's house Wednesday
said neither Glenda Brawley, Miss Brawley's mother, nor Juanita
Brawley, the girl's aunt, were available. She said the family had
no comment.
   Miss Brawley, 16, was found wrapped in a garbage bag after being
missing for four days last November. Excrement was smeared on her
body and ``KKK'' and ``nigger'' were written in charcoal or black
ink on her body.
   Strong had vowed to ``march Tawana down to Abrams' office'' if
the stalemate did not end in the next few days, the Journal quoted
the source as saying. Strong has been critical of the lawyers'
handling of the case, according to several published reports.
   A 23-member grand jury was empaneled Monday to investigate the
case, and jurors heard an opening statement from Abrams. Sharpton
called the attorney general's participation Monday ``a good sign.''
   The panel is not expected to hear evidence this week.
</TEXT>
