<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 2041EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Powell-ParkPlan     03-02 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Powell-Park Plan,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jody Powell Joins Fight Against Mall Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANASSAS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jody Powell is volunteering the public
relations skills he practiced in the White House to fight plans for
a shopping mall near fields where his Confederate ancestors fought.
   Powell, who was President Carter's press secretary, is putting
the resources of his firm, Ogilvy & Mather Public Affairs of
Washington at the disposal of groups joined in the Save the
Battlefield Coalition.
   Powell said Tuesday the fight to preserve the site near the
Manassas Battlefield National Park is worthwhile because
encroaching development is a problem at many other battlefields and
historic sites as well.
   ``Goodness, if you can't stop something this bad, then what
hopes do you have of fending off more creeping sorts of problems,
where a park gets nibbled to death?'' Powell said.
   Ten of his family members fought at the Battle of Second
Manassas in 1862, part of which was waged on land where the
Hazel-Peterson Cos. of Fairfax plan to break ground for William
Center.
   One of Powell's ancestors was mortally wounded just before the
battle, as Confederate Maj. Gen. Thomas ``Stonewall'' Jackson
raided the Union supply depot at Manassas Junction.
   On the site where Gen. Robert E. Lee built his headquarters
during Second Manassas, Hazel-Peterson and the Edward J. DeBartolo
Corp. of Ohio plan to build a 1.2 million-square-foot shopping mall.
</TEXT>
