<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 2041EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-RepublicanDelegates     03-02 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Republican Delegates,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opponents Fail To File Delegate Slates, So Bush Picks Up 24 NY
Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate George Bush
picked up 24 delegates in New York this week by virtue of his
opponents' failure to file delegate slates in eight of the state's
congressional districts.
   And successful challenges to non-Bush delegate slates in other
districts, if upheld by the courts, could leave the vice president
with at least two dozen other delegates running unopposed.
   The Board of Elections on Tuesday wiped two slates of delegates
supporting Bob Dole off the the April 19 primary ballot, one day
after stripping the Kansas senator's slate and one backing New York
Rep. Jack Kemp from the ballot.
   The petitions were rejected mainly because they did not contain
the required 1,250 signatures of registered Republicans, or were
signed by Republicans living outside the congressional district the
petitions were filed for.
   While Bush slates remain on the ballot in 33 of the state's 34
congressional districts, Kemp will be able to field delegate slates
in only 12 districts, Dole in 11 and Robertson in nine.
   Having delegate slates on the ballot is all-important in New
York where registered Republicans will not vote for any of the
candidates, but for the delegates who pledge to support them at the
national convention in New Orleans.
   The candidates that the delegates back will be listed next to
the delegates' names on this year's ballot.
   At stake in New York are 102 delegates, three from each
congressional district. The Republican state committee will
designate 34 other delegates after the primary.
   The vice president's campaign has managed to get 10 Dole slates
knocked off the ballot, as well as six slates supporting Pat
Robertson and five backing Kemp.
   Decisions disqualifying nominating petitions can be appealed to
state courts, and Bush opponents say they will pursue that course
in most cases.
   Meanwhile, in the early round of the Wyoming caucuses, Dole
gained one delegate while another remains uncommitted. Caucuses in
the state continue through Saturday.
</TEXT>
