<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AIDS-Blood     03-02 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Blood,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homosexual Prostitute Acquitted of Selling AIDS-Tainted Blood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mentally ill prostitute who sold his blood
even though he is infected with AIDS was acquitted Wednesday of
charges of attempted poisoning.
   Jurors said they had decided that Joseph Markowski lacked the
intent required for a conviction under state law, frustrating
prosecutors who said the 29-year-old drifter ``can go out and do
this again.''
   ``What this has told us here today is that the law in the state
of California does not make it a crime to sell AIDS-contaminated
blood. And that's unfortunate,'' said Los Angeles County District
Attorney Ira Reiner.
   Markowski, a homosexual prostitute who has tested positive for
the AIDS virus, nodded to his attorney, Guy O'Brien, as the jury
found him innocent of two counts of attempted poisoning.
   He had been accused of selling his tainted blood for $10 to
Plasma Production Associates last June 22 and of trying to do so
again June 25. One of the ways AIDS can be spread is by transfusion
of infected blood or blood products. He would have faced up to
seven years in prison if convicted.
   ``I'm delighted and I'm a little surprised'' by the verdict,
said O'Brien, who had argued that Markowski, homeless and
destitute, had sold his blood in desperation.
   ``I was afraid the jury wouldn't have the courage to follow the
letter of the law. I thought the fear of AIDS ... would preoccupy
the jury.''
   Markowski, originally from Michigan, was first arrested June 23
after screaming, ``Kill me! Kill me! I have AIDS!'' in a Hollywood
bank while attempting to grab a security guard's gun. Police found
on him a receipt for the plasma center.
   Deputy District Attorney Antonio Barreto Jr. argued at trial
that Markowski knew his blood was tainted. He said the drifter sold
it knowing it might contaminate the plasma pool but didn't care.
   Juror Bill Ferguson of Echo Park said that even though Markowski
knew what he was doing, he was doing it for money, not to poison.
   ``Right now you have to prove specific intent. You have to be
able to prove that a person went down there willfully to poison the
supply. That was not the case in this case,'' Ferguson said.
   ``The legislature has been sitting on their duff in this area
for some time,'' said Barreto. ``We need legislation on this. He
can go out and do this again today, as long as he said `I just did
it for the money.'''
   Prosecutors tried last year to have a law passed that would make
it a felony to knowingly sell or donate AIDS-contaminated blood.
The Assembly failed to approve it, and Reiner said he will push for
it again this year.
   ``Mr. Markowski is today free to do what he did when he was
arrested for the crime,'' Reiner said. ``Will he do it again?
Perhaps. All he needs to do now is adopt an alias.''
   Markowski had allegedly admitted to police that he sold his
blood because he needed money and didn't care about the public, but
Superior Court Judge Ronald Coen ruled the statement inadmissible
because police had not read Markowski his rights to remain silent
and wait for an attorney.
   The detective who interrogated Markowski said he committed the
error because he was so shocked by what Markowski had done.
   Deliberations began Monday after a 10-day trial before Coen.
Jurors returned the verdict Tuesday after deliberating for seven
hours, but it was sealed until Wednesday because O'Brien was unable
to make it to court.
   Reiner originally charged Markowski with attempted murder. But
Coen dismissed those counts, saying the law required a specific
intent to kill that was not present.
   O'Brien said Markowski suffers from mental illness and carries
the AIDS virus but has not developed the disease. The attorney said
Markowski will be placed in a halfway house.
   ``The long-term prognosis at this point is not good. I'd say the
outlook is guarded,'' he said.
</TEXT>
