<HEAD>New Case Of Hanged Dogs Reported At Train Station</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note nature of the following</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boys playing in an abandoned railroad
station discovered a dog hanged by its neck from a pipe, the latest
of several such incidents in the area, authorities said Wednesday.
   The dog, a German shepherd mix, had been dead for five or six
months, animal control officer John Holmes said.
   ``It would have to be some type of nut that would take an animal
like that and hang him from a pipe,'' Holmes said.
   The schoolboys told Holmes on Tuesday that they had discovered
several dead dogs in the crumbling Pawtucket-Central Falls station.
   Three years ago, Holmes said, he found a hanged dog in the same
place in the depot. Similar cases have been reported in Cumberland,
Lincoln, and Attleboro, Mass.
   In 1986, a 26-year-old Pawtucket man was charged in connection
with a rash of dog hangings in Cumberland, but he skipped bail
before trial.
</TEXT>
