<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-EconomyGlance     03-02 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Glance,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home Sales, Factory Orders Down in January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By the Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments in the economic picture
Wednesday:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOME SALES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   New home sales fell 9 percent in January. Sales activity was the
slowest since the last recession ended in December 1982.
   Analysts were surprised by the decline, since sales had already
fallen 6.8 percent in December and 3.4 percent in November.
   The sales downturn was accompanied by a sharp rise in prices.
The median price of a home shot up 9.7 percent to $120,000.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FACTORY ORDERS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent
in January, the first decline in five months.
   Orders for both durable and non-durable goods dropped to a
seasonally adjusted $212.6 billion following a big 2 percent
increase in December.
   It was the first setback in orders since a 1.4 percent drop in
August, but economists said it showed a return to more normal
demand following the placement of several large orders for jet
aircraft in December.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S. STOCK MARKET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The stock market settled for a small gain after a broad early
advance faded. The Dow Jones average, up about 15 points at its
best level of the day, finished with a .83 gain at 2,071.29.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JAPAN STOCK MARKET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange surged closer to pre-crash levels. The
Nikkei stock average closed at 25,682.82 points, up 246.92 points,
or 0.97 percent from Tuesday's close. Before the October crash, the
index stood at 25,746.56. Volume in the first period of trading was
1.7 billion shares, a record high for this year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DOLLAR</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound when the
Bank of England sold pounds to keep the British currency below 3.0
West German marks as the mark fell against the dollar. At the end
of the day, one pound cost $1.7680, cheaper than $1.7775 late
Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 128.47 Japanese yen, up from
128.30 Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GREENSPAN-BUDGET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve Board chairman, said deep cuts
in ``entitlement'' programs, which include Social Security and
Medicare, may be the most realistic way for cutting the federal
budget deficit.
   Greenspan, testifying before the Senate Budget Committee, also
called for a 15-cent-a-gallon increase in the federal gasoline tax.
   But he said that, in general, tax increases do not appear to be
a feasible way for trimming the budget shortfall, which was $150
billion last year.
</TEXT>
