<1ST_LINE>u a AM-RestaurantCritics 2ndLd-Writethru a0783-813 03-02 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Restaurant Critics, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0783-813,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Legislature Asked To License Restaurant Critics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 15th graf ``The reviewer'' with 2 grafs with comment
from reviewer, picking up 16th graf ``J. Charles''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill to require licensing of restaurant
reviewers has been introduced in the Legislature after an owner
complained that her establishment was savaged by a critic who
didn't know a Bolognese sauce from bottled tomato sauce.
   Lawmakers give the measure little chance of passage because of
concerns that it would violate the First Amendment right of free
speech. However, the restaurant industry says debate over the bill
helped accomplish its main purpose.
   ``We wanted to provide a message to reviewers, the public and
some editorial people that ... some of the persons providing the
reviews are less than capable,'' Carroll J. Hughes, executive vice
president of the 700-member Connecticut Restaurant Association,
said Wednesday.
   Hughes persuaded lawmakers to draft the bill after Lucille
Trzcinski, co-owner of Casagrande restaurant in Wallingford,
complained that two ``grossly inaccurate'' reviews last month
caused her business to drop 15-20 percent.
   Hughes said he gets a dozen complaints a year from restaurant
owners about reviews. No state licenses restaurant critics, he said.
   ``We have to stand helplessly by while people are allowed to
make unfounded, unsubstantiated and gratuitous remarks,'' Mrs.
Trzcinski told a legislative committee Tuesday. ``The damage that
these reviews do numbers in the millions of dollars. It is our
business and it is our livelihood.''
   Alan Neigher, an attorney who specializes in media law, called
the proposal ``preposterous.''
   ``It's nothing more than a temper tantrum by some lobbyists and
their clients who don't have an elementary understanding of what
the role of free speech in a free economy is about,'' Neigher said.
``The courts have repeatedly struck down attempts to license the
press.''
   Mrs. Trzcinski, who has operated Casagrande with her husband for
11 years, said her restaurant previously received high marks from
some of the toughest critics in the state for its northern Italian
cuisine.
   She complained that two recent reviewers made numerous mistakes,
even when praising aspects of her menu.
   One mistook a fine loin of veal for a veal pattie and complained
about her bagna cauda, an elegant oil-and-anchovy dip, because he
was expecting a more pedestrian dip, she said.
   Another incorrectly suggested that her Bolognese sauce was
tomato based and flavored with cheese, when it's actually a pork
sauce flavored with a little tomato, Mrs. Trzcinski said.
   ``I would say he probably couldn't recognize a proper Bolognese
because he's familiar with Ragu,'' she said.
   The reviewer also made an ethnic joke about the restaurant's
having a Polish chef, she said.
   The reviewer, who uses the pen name R. Alan Richards in
restaurant reviews for the New Haven Register, said he thought his
review was ``fairly positive'' and blamed the dispute over the
Bolognese sauce on semantics and misinformation supplied by a
waitress.
   ``Licensing opinions is kind of silly,'' said Richards, who has
been reviewing restaurants for seven or eight years. Neither he nor
the New Haven Register would reveal his real name.
   J. Charles Mokrisky, an attorney and the part-time food critic
who complained about the bagna cauda, defended his opinion.
   ``I call 'em the way I see 'em,'' said Mokrisky, who calls
himself a ``food fanatic.''
   Under the proposal, restaurant critics would have to be licensed
through the Department of Consumer Protection. A critic could be
fined $500 for reviewing without a license.
   The proposed license requirements include experience in
food-service operation and management, graduation from a recognized
culinary arts degree program, or a combination of at least six
years of experience and formal training.
   ``I have sympathy for her,'' said Rep. John Wayne Fox,
co-chairman of the General Law Committee that held a public hearing
on the bill. ``But I just was not convinced it was a serious enough
problem that we as a legislature ought to regulate it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
