<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-02 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer-lawmaker is hoping his colleagues will
hop to it and approve a bill that would give a tax break to frog
farmers.
   Farms for frogs should be exempt from local property taxes, just
like any other place that has ``livestock,'' Conservative Michael
Colvin told a House of Commons committee studying a local finance
bill.
   As now written, the bill defines livestock as ``any mammal or
bird kept for the production of food or wool, or for the purpose of
its use in the farming of land.''
   That's fine for mammals and birds, but where does the frog, an
amphibian, fit in? asked Colvin.
   ``The definition of livestock is most unclear. Times have
changed in agriculture,'' he said, suggesting that the bill
substitute ``creatures'' for ``livestock.''
   ``It would be a sad day if any government started imposing a tax
on frogs,'' said Colvin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WAUSA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Getting the attention of the Wausa High
School girls basketball team is easy. Just shout ``Anderson!'' and
the five starters will turn their heads.
   The Anderson girls _ only two of them related _ may be the first
quintet with the same last name to assemble on court in a Nebraska
high school basketball game.
   The Lady Vikings, 22-1, play Exeter on Thursday in the opening
round of the state high school basketball tournament in Lincoln,
and fans will get a chance to see the five Andersons and their
eight teammates.
   ``Everyone notices it,'' said Becky Anderson, a 5-foot-11-inch
junior who plays center and forward.
   Becky and her cousin Lori are joined by Collette, Tiffany and
Laura Anderson in the starting lineup.
   Senior Laura is the team's star, averaging 16 points per game.
She says having the same name as four other players on the team
hasn't caused the players any problems. But it's another matter for
announcers.
   ``They get mixed up once in a while,'' she said.
   ``It's easy to tell them apart,'' said Charles Haag, the team's
assistant coach. ``But we definitely have to use first names.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ballet fans beware: A California
legislator is trying to make the West Coast Swing, a space-saving
variant of the jitterbug, the official state dance.
   Under state Sen. Quentin Kopp's bill, the West Coast Swing would
join the ranks of gold, serpentine rocks, the desert tortoise,
dog-faced butterfly and the saber-toothed tiger _ all officially
recognized symbols of the Golden State.
   Gold is the state mineral, serpentine the state rock, desert
tortoise the state reptile, dog-faced butterfly the state insect
and the saber-toothed tiger the state fossil.
   ``West Coast Swing is an intricate dance, requiring a great deal
of coordination, good timing and intelligent application,'' Kopp, a
San Francisco independent, wrote to fellow lawmakers recently.
   According to Oakland businessman Walter Harmon, who approached
Kopp with the idea of honoring the dance, West Coast Swing is a
variation of the jitterbug, a jazz dance.
   The variation was developed because it takes up less room than
the freewheeling jitterbug, and thus more couples can dance on a
smaller floor, said Harmon.
   ``It's a very complex, very beautiful dance,'' said Harmon,
legislative liaison director for the United States Swing Dance
Council.
   He also claims it is the only indigenous California dance to
survive in essentially its original form, and is thus worthy of
historical recognition and preservation.
</TEXT>
