<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Ehrlichman, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0801,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Watergate Conspirator Covering Mecham Trial For Magazine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to CORRECT name of prison to Swift
Trail sted Swift Trial and fix typo in `assignment' in lead. PICKS
UP 5th graf pvs, `He now ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Ehrlichman, a former White House aide
who spent time in prison for his role in the Watergate scandal,
says his assignment covering the impeachment trial of Gov. Evan
Mecham for Rolling Stone magazine is ``a match made in heaven.''
   ``I'm working on a novel and it has an impeachment scene in it,
so I was going to come over and and take a look at this, anyway,''
Ehrlichman said Tuesday. ``It's a ready-made opportunity to
observe. Secondly, it's a subject that intrigues me. I certainly
have some feel for the underlying issues.''
   Ehrlichman, a former top-ranking official for President Richard
Nixon, resigned from his White House post in April 1973 and was
convicted in 1975 for obstruction of justice, conspiracy and
perjury in the attempted cover-up of the Watergate burglary.
   Ehrlichman, 63, spent 18 months at Swift Trail Camp, a
minimum-security federal prison south of Safford, Ariz., and was
released in 1978.
   He now lives in Santa Fe, N.M., and is working on his seventh
novel, a story about a fictional U.S. president.
   Ehrlichman said he sees few correlations between the problems of
Nixon and Mecham.
   ``Here is a fellow (Mecham) with a criminal proceeding, an
impeachment and a recall all going on at the same time, all pretty
much bottomed on the same facts,'' said Ehrlichman. ``I think it's
very different (from Watergate). It raises all kinds of interesting
legal questions about double jeopardy and things like that.''
</TEXT>
