<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Army-DrugTesting     03-02 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Army-Drug Testing,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Stops Random Drug Testing of Civilians, But Seeks Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army said Wednesday it had stopped random
drug testing for civilian workers to comply with a court ruling,
but was asking the Justice Department to appeal the judgment.
   The service, in a brief statement, said it would limit its
civilian drug testing for the time being to those instances in
which ``there is a reasonable suspicion that a specific employee is
under the influence of drugs while on duty.''
   Testing on a random basis, however, has been halted for now, the
service added.
   The move follows a decision in U.S. District Court in Washington
on Tuesday in which a judge ruled that random drug testing amounted
to an unreasonable search prohibited by the Constitution.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas F. Hogan said random checks of
employees in so-called sensitive positions could not be justified
by safety concerns, because the urine test used by the Army did not
indicate whether an employee was using drugs on the job.
   ``The Army has asked the Department of Justice to appeal the
ruling,'' the service said in its statement. ``The Army has also
requested that Justice ask for a stay of the judge's order during
the appeal process.''
   Hogan's ruling had no effect on the right of the armed forces to
conduct random drug tests of active-duty personnel.
</TEXT>
