<2ND_LINE>AM-Tampering Case, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0807,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fingerprints of Woman Accused of Excedrin Tampering Found in
Poison Books</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, `Mrs. Nickell's ...' to ADD that book was
found on a library shelf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fingerprints found in a book about poisons match
those of a woman accused of killing her husband by putting cyanide
in a non-prescription drug, according to court papers released
Wednesday.
   A memorandum filed by U.S. Attorney Gene S. Anderson also said
Stella Nickell had failed a lie-detector test ``on whether she was
the Excedrin killer'' and that she apparently forged her husband's
signature on life insurance applications.
   Mrs. Nickell is charged in the deaths of Bruce Nickell, 52, and
Susan Katherine Snow, 40, both of Auburn. Both died in June 1986
after swallowing tainted capsules of Extra-Strength Excedrin.
Authorities have not suggested any other links between the victims.
   Mrs. Nickell was indicted in December on two counts of causing a
death by product tampering and three counts of tampering with a
product involved in interstate commerce. She has pleaded innocent.
   Mrs. Nickell checked out a book on poisoning from a library in
mid-1984 without returning it, and pages on cyanide poisoning in a
book titled ``Deadly Harvest'' that was found on a library shelf
bore 84 fingerprints and three palm prints belonging to Mrs.
Nickell, court documents said.
   The prosecutor's memo said the defendant and her husband, Bruce
Nickell, had experienced ``intensified marital discord'' just
before his death _ an assertion strongly disputed by Ms. Nickell's
court-appointed defense attorney.
   In accompanying documents, federal public defender Thomas
Hillier II also disputed the government's claim that the polygraph
test was conclusive.
   The maximum penalty on each death count is life, and the other
charges carry maximum terms of 10 years. Trial has been set for
April 18.
   The prosecutor's memo, filed in support of the government's
motion that Mrs. Nickell remain in custody pending trial, and
accompanying documents had been sealed by U.S. District Judge
William S. Dwyer because of concern that release of the information
might make it harder to obtain an unbiased jury.
   The Seattle Times, Seattle Post-Intelligencer and Morning News
Tribune of Tacoma appealed the order, which was overturned Monday
by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Tainted capsules of pain relievers were found in both victims'
homes and in bottles on the shelves of two stores in the suburbs
between Seattle and Tacoma.
   Mrs. Nickell had sued Excedrin's manufacturer, Bristol-Myers,
and two stores where tainted capsules were found after an insurance
carrier refused to pay benefits on her husband's death.
   Shortly before he died, Nickell obtained a life insurance policy
that would pay his wife $31,000 if he died of natural causes and
$136,000 for an accidental death.
   In September and October 1985, Ms. Nickell applied for two other
life insurance policies for a total of $40,000, with she and her
husband each the beneficiary of the other.
   ``Handwriting examination has definitely concluded that Bruce
Nickell did not sign what purports to be his signature,''
Anderson's memo says. ``Bruce Nickell's fingerprints were not found
on either insurance application.
   ``Stella Nickell's fingerprints were found in one of the two
applications, and handwriting analysis conclusively established
that she signed her husband's name to one application and probably
signed his name to the second application.''
</TEXT>
