<DOCNO> AP880302-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 2133EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GuidelineChallenge     03-02 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guideline Challenge,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Lawyers Group Challenges Federal Sentencing Guidelines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national lawyers group Wednesday joined a
challenge to federal sentencing guidelines that require judges to
impose prison terms of particular lengths for certain crimes.
   The guidelines, established by a congressional commission,
violate the Constitution's separation of powers doctrine, says a
friend-of-the-court brief filed by the National Association of
Criminal Defense Lawyers.
   The association joined a challenge filed by Assistant Federal
Public Defender Stewart Abrams, who represents a woman with no
criminal record who under the guidelines must receive at least 6{
years in prison for smuggling cocaine.
   A judge may go outside the guidelines, which create a 43-level
system of punishment based on the crime and defendant's record,
only in extreme cases.
   U.S. District Judge James King, chief of the Southern District
of Florida, said all 15 federal judges in his district will rule
together on the matter to avoid discrepancies from courtroom to
courtroom. No hearing date has been set.
   It will be the first time the judges have sat together since
they considered the immigration of 125,000 Cubans to Florida during
the 1980 Mariel boatlift.
   The sentencing guidelines have been challenged on constitutional
grounds three times in the Southern District of California since
Feb. 18 with different results, said NACDL representative Benson B.
Weintraub.
   In the test case, Beverly Bogle, 21, was arrested after her
arrival at Miami International Airport from Jamaica on Nov. 11 with
1.9 kilograms of cocaine she was carrying for someone else, Abrams
said.
   ``She was not profiting from it,'' he said. ``She was doing it
for a person she perceived to be a friend.''
   Ms. Bogle pleaded guilty to importing cocaine and has been
jailed while awaiting sentencing March 25.
   Under the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986, Congress set a minimum
sentence of five years in prison for the offense.
   However, the U.S. Sentencing Commission, created in 1984, set a
guideline ranging from six years and seven months to eight years
and one month in prison for the crime, Abrams said. The guidelines
apply to crimes committed after Nov. 1.
   In Ms. Bogle's case, the federal probation office wants to use
the commission's guidelines, Abrams said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
