<2ND_LINE>AM-Federated, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0837,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retailer Agrees to Macy Acquisition, Campeau Pursuing Tender Offer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 14-17 bgng `It had ...' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with new Campeau offer; ADDS 3 grafs to UPDATE with Federated
chairman announcing plans to retire, $3 million `golden parachute'
and to ADD four largest retailers.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Version moving on business wire.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS4, LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federated Department Stores Inc. on Wednesday
chose R.H. Macy & Co. over a rival suitor, agreeing to a marriage
that would put famous retailers such as Macy, Bloomingdale's and
Bullock's under one enormous corporate roof.
   A rejected Campeau Corp. said it would proceed with its bid for
Federated, the nation's fifth largest retailer.
   Federated said in a joint statement with Macy, the nation's 10th
largest general retail concern, that the two companies had signed a
definitive agreement to create a new company, Macy's-Federated Inc.
   Macy operates 96 stores in 14 states, while Federated has 650
stores _ including Bloomingdale's, Bullocks and Filene's _ in 36
states.
   Federated's choice of Macy over Campeau came as no surprise.
   Analysts noted that the Macy bid offered Federated the
opportunity for future growth, while Campeau would bring with it a
history of having bought and broken up Allied Stores Corp.
   No matter who ends up controlling Federated, the new owner is
expected to sell its Gold Circle discount stores and Ralphs
supermarkets.
   Several of Federated's department store chains, which include
Burdine's, I. Magnin., Rich's, Abraham & Straus and Lazarus, also
are expected to be sold after a purchase by either Macy or Campeau.
   Abraham and Straus and Rich's were considered likely candidates
for a sale by Macy, because they are direct competitors with Macy
stores in New York and Atlanta, respectively.
   The agreement provides for Macy to begin a cash tender offer of
$74.50 a share for about 80 percent of Federated's 89.6 million
outstanding shares, or a total of $5.25 billion, the companies said.
   The remaining Federated shares would be exchanged for stock in
the new company.
   Federated's current management would have a strong voice in the
new company, filling 40 percent of the seats on its board of
directors.
   Campeau, a Toronto-based real estate developer and retailer,
through its Allied Stores division, owns the Jordan Marsh, Stern's,
Ann Taylor and Maas Brothers chains.
   The retailer said in a statement that Macy's bid was ``not
competitive and we intend to prevail in the marketplace.''
   Late Wednesday, Campeau said it was amending its previously
announced $66 cash tender offer. It said it would pay $75 per share
in cash for 80 percent of Federated's shares, and after a merger
would pay $44 per share for the remaining 20 percent.
   Campeau said its latest proposal, which was to expire March 15,
had a combined value of $68 per share and a total value of $6.1
billion.
   The amended Campeau bid was announced after the close of trading
on the New York Stock Exchange, where Federated stock fell $1 a
share to $66.75.
   Earlier, Campeau repeated a charge that the Macy offer was
highly speculative because of the unknown value of the stock. Macy
is currently privately held, and it is difficult to know how much
its shares are worth.
   Wall Street analysts said they found it hard to predict what
shareholders would do, given the problem of putting a value on the
stock portion of the offer.
   ``If you don't know that, it's really tough to figure out which
is a better deal,'' said Joseph Ronning, a retail industry analyst
with Brown Brothers Harriman & Co.
   Macy's bid, which came to light Monday, was originally for
$73.80 a share in cash plus stock, but the offer was increased
before the agreement was reached.
   Macy was taken private by a management group in a $3.6 billion
leveraged buyout in 1986. Its stores rang up $5.21 billion in sales
during the fiscal year ended last Aug. 1.
   Federated Chairman Howard Goldfeder said at a news conference
Wednesday he would resign after helping Macy Chairman Edward
Finkelstein implement the merger.
   Goldfeder said he expects to be paid $3.06 million when he
leaves the company under a ``golden parachute'' approved by
Federated's directors. Similar departure payments are due other top
Federated officers.
   The nation's four largest retailers are Sears, Roebuck and Co.,
with $30.21 billion in sales during fiscal 1987; K mart Corp.,
$25.63 billion; Wal-Mart Stores Inc., $15.96 billion, and J.C.
Penney Co. _ $13.98 billion.
</TEXT>
