<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     03-02 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Hit Police Station After Killing Peasants, Ranchers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas killed 14 people in
three raids this week, part of the rebels' biggest offensive yet in
Colombia, authorities and news accounts said Wednesday.
   About 100 rebels attacked Pelaya town, about 250 miles north of
Bogota, on Tuesday night, Alfredo Araujo said in a broadcast
interview with the Colombian radio chain RCN.
   Araujo, administrative assistant to the Cesar state government
office, said the attackers stormed a police station, killed two
officers and injured five people.
   The daily El Tiempo of Bogota reported that leftist guerrillas
murdered eight peasants Tuesday in the Santa Marta Mountains in
northern Colombia.
   El Tiempo quoted peasants there as saying the pro-Soviet
Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces killed the eight for refusing
to cooperate with the rebels.
   The Santa Marta Mountains are on Colombia's Caribbean coast.
   Araujo said that last Sunday the National Liberation Army, or
ELN, attacked San Jeronimo, another town in Cesar state, and killed
four ranchers for refusing to pay what the guerrillas call a
revolution tax.
   The guerrillas also gathered townspeople in the town square and
exhorted them not to vote in the March 13 nationwide mayoral
elections.
   In the first two months of 1988 rebels kidnapped 14 mayors,
attacked a dozen towns, killed 31 soldiers, 28 police and 80 other
people, blew up oil pipelines and electricity cable towers and
attacked oil company drilling camps.
   Two of the mayors _ Luis Alberto Gonzalez of Pitalito and Anibal
Pena of San Agustin _ were freed in army attacks Friday on
guerrilla encampments near the southern town of San Agustin, the
Defense Ministry said.
   San Agustin is popular with foreign tourists because of the many
pre-Columbian statues in an archaeological park there.
   The mayors were kidnapped Feb. 25 by the National Liberation
Army, which freed 12 mayors previously after telling them to do
more for poor people in their districts.
   Political violence has been worst in southern Caqueta state,
where 40 local leaders of the governing Liberal Party were killed
in the last three months.
   Party leaders said the rebels were trying to terrorize it into
withdrawing from mayoral elections so the leftist Patriotic Union
party will win.
   Antonio Serrano Duarte, a congressman from the state, was shot
and wounded Tuesday night in Florencia, the state capital, national
police said in a communique. It said Serrano was out of danger in a
hospital.
   There are five leftist guerrilla groups in Colombia.
   Three members of the Patriotic Union Party were murdered in
Caqueta state in the last month. Right-wing death squads were
blamed for killing nearly 500 of the party's workers in the last
two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
