<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Grammys-FirstWinners     03-02 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grammys-First Winners,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Time Grammy Winners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Grammys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not always the big names in the music
business who capture the coveted Grammy Award as Wednesday night's
announcement of first-time winners showed: actor Jack Nicholson,
veteran rocker Frank Zappa, ex-Righteous Brother Bill Medley and
the South African vocal group, Ladysmith Black Mambazo.
   ``First of all I thank God and then Paul Simon,'' said Joseph
Shabalala, Ladysmith's lead singer. The group performed on Simon's
breakthrough ``Graceland'' LP, and Simon produced the group's
``Shaka Zulu'' album which won for best traditional folk recording.
   Nicholson won his Grammy for best recording for children for his
narration of ``The Elephant's Child.'' The actor was not at Radio
City Music Hall to accept the award bestowed by the National
Academy of Recording Arts & Sciences.
   Joining him in the winner's circle for the first time was
Medley, who thanked God for his ``nine lives'' in the music
business.
   ``I've waited 26 years for this,'' said the bass singer after
winning best pop vocal performance by a duo or group for ``(I've
Had) The Time of My Life,'' a song he did with Jennifer Warnes.
   Zappa defeated his son, Dweezil, earning his first Grammy _ for
best rock instrumental performance _ after a career spanning more
than two decades. Bruce Springsteen was also a runner-up to Zappa
in the category.
   The awards, announced off-camera prior to the televised show,
also included a posthumous first-time Grammy for reggae star Peter
Tosh, who was murdered in his Jamaica home last year.
   ``It is so unfair that Peter Tosh is not here. He deserved this
very much,'' said his cousin Pauline Burgess, who accepted the
award.
   Professor Longhair, the New Orleans piano player, also won his
first Grammy with ``Houseparty New Orleans Style,'' which won as
best traditional blues recording.
</TEXT>
