<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NorthwestAirlines     03-02 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northwest Airlines,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attendants Advised To Begin Slowdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The union representing 6,700 Northwest
Airlines flight attendants instructed members Wednesday to begin a
slowdown by doing everything by the book.
   The attendants have remained on the job since a deadline for a
new contract passed Friday.
   ``Keep them busy, keep them guessing, keep them confused,'' Jeff
Musto, a spokesman for Teamsters Local 2747, said in a recorded
message on the union hotline.
   ``Remember you have to have all luggage stowed before you can
give permission to close the front boarding door. I think you get
the idea,'' he said.
   Northwest spokesman Redmond Tyler said the airline operated
normally Wednesday. ``We have seen no evidence of any disruption or
attempt at disruption,'' he said.
   No talks are scheduled. The main stumbling block to a contract
is a company proposal to delay the promotion of lower-paid workers
to the higher bracket.
   Linda McMahon, operations manager for the five AAA Travel Agency
offices in Minneapolis, said she had not noticed any effect on
business or service from slowdown tactics.
   ``I haven't heard any specific complaints at this point. I was
certainly apprehensive when I heard about the `guerrilla warfare'
this morning. Everything seems to be going pretty much as usual,''
Ms. McMahon said.
   The threat of a strike has not deterred many travelers from
flying Northwest, she said.
   ``A lot of times there isn't comparable service on another
carrier. They will take their chances that Northwest will be
operating because they want to fly non-stop,'' Ms. McMahon said.
   Many business travelers are making alternate arrangements in
case of a strike, but vacationers who bought discount tickets in
advance have little recourse, she said.
   The unions representing the pilots and Machinists, who are
trying to negotiate separate contracts, have not said whether they
would honor flight attendants' picket lines.
</TEXT>
