<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 2019EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru a0815 03-02 0899</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0815,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Landmark Bill In Face Of Reagan Veto Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 22 grafs new with House passing bill, other new material;
PICKS UP 13th graf pvs bgng, `The restoration'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House overwhelmingly passed a landmark
civil rights bill Wednesday that would broaden protections for
women, minorities, the elderly and the handicapped, but President
Reagan has vowed to veto the measure.
   The Civil Rights Restoration Act, considered by many lawmakers
the most significant civil rights measure in 20 years, was sent to
the White House on a 315-98 vote. The Senate passed it by an
equally lopsided 75-14 vote in January.
   Both chambers passed the bill by the two-thirds margin needed to
override a presidential veto, but it was unclear whether the huge
margins would hold up following Reagan's vow Wednesday to reject
the measure.
   The restoration act was designed to reverse a 1984 Supreme Court
decision that narrowed the scope of four major civil rights laws
meant to prevent taxpayer financing of discrimination.
   Supporters of the act said hundreds of discrimination complaints
had been dropped or restricted since the decision.
   ``We have suffered far too long in waiting for this great and
important day,'' said Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich.
   In letters delivered Wednesday to several House Republicans,
Reagan said flatly he will veto the measure ``if it is presented to
me in its current form.''
   In the letters, sent from Brussels, Belgium, where Reagan is
attending a NATO summit, the president said the bill ``dramatically
expands the scope of federal jurisdiction over state and local
governments and the private sector'' and ``poses a particular
threat to religious liberty.''
   In the case brought by Grove City (Pa.) College, the Supreme
Court held in a 6-3 opinion that Title IX _ a law barring sex
discrimination in federally funded education programs _ applies
only to specific programs or activities receiving federal
assistance and not the institutions of which they are part.
   The restoration act clarifies that entire institutions and
government agencies are covered if any program or activity within
them receives federal aid. The broad coverage also applies to the
private sector if the aid goes to a corporation as a whole or if
the recipient principally provides education, health care, housing,
social services or parks and recreation.
   The bill also says farmers getting crop subsidies, people on
food stamps and other individuals receiving federal assistance are
not required to comply with the anti-discrimination statutes.
   Sponsors of the restoration act said Congress always intended
broad civil rights protections on the theory that ``those who dip
their hands in the public till should not object if a little
democracy sticks to their fingers,'' as Rep. Augustus Hawkins,
D-Calif., put it.
   But opponents claim the bill goes far beyond restoration. Like
Reagan, they complained that it is too intrusive into the private
sector and religious organizations.
   ``The wording of the law is going to bring about unintended
consequences like you could never imagine,'' said Rep. George
Gekas, R-Pa.
   House leaders provoked controversy by bringing the Senate's
version of the civil rights bill directly to the floor Wednesday,
bypassing House committees and limiting amendments to one GOP
substitute for the entire bill.
   ``We need a Voting Rights Act for congressmen,'' sputtered Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
   But other members said there had been more than 40 committee
hearings on the Grove City bill since 1984. Hawkins, chairman of
the House Education and Labor Committee and a senior member of the
Congressional Black Caucus, said 2,500 amendments had been offered
over the years.
   ``All the compromises that can possibly be made have already
been made. Certainly all the ideas that could ever have been
thought of have already been expressed,'' said Hawkins. ``The time
(to act) is now.''
   The GOP substitute, sponsored by Rep. James Sensenbrenner,
R-Wis., would have limited the bill's impact on corporations and
allowed more educational institutions to escape compliance with the
sex discrimination ban on religious grounds.
   Sensenbrenner said he offered it in ``a spirit of
reconciliation'' to end the four-year congressional ordeal over the
bill. But it was defeated 266-146.
   An anti-abortion amendment adopted by the Senate says nothing in
the bill or in existing law requires institutions to perform or pay
for abortions. The amendment invalidates 1975 regulations that bar
discrimination against women who have had abortions or sought them
and require college health plans to treat abortions like other
temporary disabilities.
   Feminists considered the amendment a setback but did not
actively oppose the civil rights bill in the House. The National
Right-To-Life Committee called the amendment a great victory,
saying Wednesday that ``Congress has emphatically rejected the
legal doctrine that anti-abortion policies are a form of sex
discrimination.''
   The restoration act applies to the four civil rights laws
affected by the Supreme Court ruling: Title IX of the 1972
Education Amendments, barring sex discrimination in federally
funded education programs; the 1964 Civil Rights Act, barring
racial discrimination in federally-assisted programs; the 1973
Rehabilitation Act, barring discrimination against the handicapped
in any program or activity receiving federal aid; and the 1975 Age
Discrimination Act, barring employment discrimination against older
people.
   The House passed the restoration act in similar form on a vote
of 375-32 in 1984, shortly after the court decision. The bill was
bottled up in a Senate committee until last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
