<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru a0903 03-02 1135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0903,1050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Taking Legal Steps To Squeeze Panama's Economy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 30th graf pvs, bgng: ``Two officials
...'' to UPDATE with D'Amato, Kerry meeting with opposition
leaders.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is taking legal action to
prevent Panama's military-dominated regime from withdrawing
Panamanian government funds from U.S. banks, a lawyer representing
opposition forces said Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams raised
the possibility that the United States will withhold the next
payment due to Panama for tolls, fees and services for Panama Canal
operations.
   The two developments indicated Reagan administration interest in
accelerating a campaign of economic denial against the Panamanian
regime, dominated by the chief of the Panamanian Defense Forces,
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   William D. Rogers, a lawyer for ousted Panamanian President Eric
Arturo Delvalle, told a news conference about the alleged U.S.
effort to freeze Panamanian government funds deposited in American
banks.
   Although no firm figures were available, $50 million was said to
be involved.
   The State Department had no comment on the reported action, but
other officials, speaking only on condition of anonymity, confirmed
that the measures outlined by Rogers were being taken.
   Asked about the U.S. position on that issue, Abrams told the
Cable News Network, ``We know who the legitimate government of
Panama is. If the government of President Delvalle says to American
banks, don't pay money to Noriega, then all those banks are going
to come to the State Department and say, `Who's got the authority
here? Noriega or Delvalle?'
   ``We're going to answer that question. Delvalle is president of
Panama. And Noriega has been fired and he does not have legitimate
authority here.''
   Rogers, of the Arnold & Porter law firm, said the administration
action was being carried out to ensure that the banks may make
disbursements only to the Panamanian ambassador who served under
Delvalle, Juan B. Sosa. Delvalle was ousted last week after he
tried to fire Noriega and has been in hiding in Panama.
   Rogers said the State Department was issuing ``formal
certifications'' that it regards Sosa as ``the accredited
representative of the recognized government of the country.''
   State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said only
that such certifications were being prepared. She declined to
specify their purpose.
   At issue is the status of Panamanian government deposits at five
American banks. The attempt by Sosa and his allies to prevent the
transfer of these funds to the new Panamanian government is part of
an ambitious plan of economic warfare aimed at toppling Noriega.
   Delvalle was forced out last week after Noriega, under federal
indictment on drug smuggling charges, ignored Delvalle's attempt to
replace him.
   Rogers said the banks believed to have Panamanian government
deposits are Marine Midland NA, Irving Trust Co., Bankers Trust
Co., the Republic National Bank and the Bank of Boston.
   ``Every dime we can find is in those banks,'' Rogers said. He
added that any bank which ignores the order could be liable for
whatever payments it makes to the current Panamanian government.
   Marine Midland and Irving Trust refused comment on the purported
State Department action. Another New York banking source, insisting
on anonymity, questioned the legitimacy of the effort to block
transfers of funds.
   Sosa said the State Department is seriously considering
withholding from Panama the next payment, due March 15, of the fees
the United States gives Panama for use of the Panama Canal. He
estimated that figure at $8 million, but other sources said it was
closer to $7 million.
   Mrs. Oakley confirmed that a request from the Delvalle
government to put the funds in escrow had been received and that
the State Department was consulting with other agencies on how to
proceed.
   Abrams indicated that no such request had been received but that
the United States would respond positively if asked.
   ``If they ask us to pay the canal payments into a different
account or delay it, I think we'd do that. We'd respond to
President Delvalle.
   ``If he tells us he doesn't want that money going to Noriega,
then we're not going to give it to Noriega.''
   Several members of the House Merchant Marine Committee, which
has jurisdiction over the Panama Canal, called on President Reagan
to withhold the payment and threatened to legislate that step if he
refuses to go along.
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, D-La., said, ``They (the Panamanian
authorities) are in dire need of funds. If this payment is denied
to them, the Noriega regime will have great difficulty maintaining
itself.''
   The legislators said nearly $80 million a year is paid to Panama
by the United States under terms of the Panama Canal treaties.
   In New York, lawyers for Delvalle sued in federal court to block
the Republic National Bank from turning over millions of dollars to
the new Panamanian government.
   The lawsuit was dropped after the bank agreed to transfer the
money, estimated at $10 million, to the Federal Reserve Bank for
safekeeping.
   In related matters Wednesday:
   _Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y. said the CIA is conducting an
internal investigation into allegations that it was the source of
personal and political information on U.S. senators forwarded to
Noriega.
   The allegations of the CIA-Noriega link were first made at a
congressional hearing last month by Jose I. Blandon, a former top
Panamanian intelligence official. U.S. law prohibits the CIA from
engaging in domestic spying on American citizens.
   Two officials who identified themselves as being with the spy
agency's office of the inspector general interviewed Blandon last
week, D'Amato said.
   _ After meeting at the Capitol with Panamanian opposition
political leaders, D'Amato and Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said they
will offer on the Senate floor on Thursday ``a progressive plan of
increased economic pressure'' against the Noriega regime.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, president of Panama's Christian
Democratic party, said the campaign to restore democracy will
prevail by combining ``peaceful people power'' in Panama,
international public opinion and ``the growing economic pressure
that is being exercised on the illegitimate regime of Gen.
Noriega.''
   _Financial experts in Miami said billions of dollars in bank
deposits have been taken out of Panama for safer havens in the wake
of Noriega's drug indictment in Miami last month.
   ``This certainly has destabilized Panama as a banking center,''
said Gonzalo Valdes-Fauli, senior vice president and manager of the
Miami office of London-based Barclay's Bank.
   One unidentified top banking expert told The Miami Herald that
from June to October, Panamanian banks lost $7 billion of the $36
billion they held. Panama in the 1980s had come to be known as the
Switzerland of Latin America, offering banking secrecy and
stability to the region's investors and depositors.
   Unlike other countries, Panama cannot cover its cash shortages
by printing new money becuase the dollar is the national currency.
</TEXT>
