<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain in Arkansas, Oklahoma, Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms pounded Oklahoma, Arkansas and northern Texas on
Wednesday, while snow fell from the Rockies and the Plains to
Michigan.
   More than a half-inch of rain fell during a half-hour in Fort
Worth and Aledo, Texas, and flash-flood watches were posted over
west-central and southwest Arkansas, southern Oklahoma, and
northwest Texas.
   Colorado got heavy snow Tuesday night and Wednesday morning,
with 10 inches reported near Rockport, 7 near New Raymer and 6 near
Wellington. Up to 4 inches of snow fell Wednesday in parts of
Nevada, New Mexico, Wyoming, upper Michigan, Nebraska, Kansas, the
Texas Panhandle.
   Rain fell across parts of Kansas, Missouri, Oklahoma, eastern
Texas, Arkansas, Tennessee, Kentucky, Indiana, Ohio and
Pennsylvania.
   Snowfall during the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. EST included 3
inches at Denver and 2 inches at Cheyenne, Wyo. Heavier rainfall
during the same period included 1.20 inches at Fort Sill, Okla.,
.86 inch at Gage, Okla., .75 inch at Altus, Okla., .65 inch at
Waco, Texas, .60 at Wichita Falls, Texas, and .59 at Dallas.
   Temperatures at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 10 degrees at Baudette,
Minn., to 83 degrees at Fort Myers Southwest Regional Airport in
Florida. The morning low was 9 degrees below zero at Massena, N.Y.
   Thursday's forecast called for rain along the Oregon coast, rain
and occasional thunderstorms from southeast Arizona across Texas,
most of the Southeast, the Ohio Valley and from the middle-Atlantic
states to southern New York, snow over the lower Great Lakes and
cloudy skies over the upper Great Lakes, New england and the
northern Rockies.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 20s and 30s from
New England across the Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley,
the eastern half of the Dakotas and the Texas Panhandle, the 40s
and 50s from New Jersey across the Virginias, the Ohio Valley, from
central Missouri across Arkansas, over the remainder of the
northern and central Plains, Oklahoma and northern Texas, the
Rockies, the northern Plateau, the Great Basin and the Pacific
Northwest, the 80s across southern Texas and much of florida and
the 60s and 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
