<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0840,0879</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Fire Tear Gas in Ramallah Hospital, 20 Arabs Detained</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 2 grafs SUB for grafs 23-24 pvs, ``We have ... and Israel,''
UPDATING with Shamir comments attacking Jordan. Picks up 25th graf
pvs, The Haaretz ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops fired tear
gas inside an Arab hospital Wednesday, forcing doctors to don gas
masks and sending dozens of choking patients fleeing with their
faces covered by Arab headdresses.
   Soldiers clubbed a Palestinian teen-ager suspected of throwing
rocks at troops from a barricade erected about 10 yards from the
hospital's emergency room.
   An Associated Press photographer saw soldiers throw the youth
head first down a flight of stairs, then sit on his stomach while
beating him with a wooden truncheon.
   Troops detained 20 Arabs suspected of participating in
demonstrations in Ramallah, Israel radio said.
   President Reagan, meanwhile, ordered Secretary of State George
P. Shultz to return to the Middle East on Thursday for further
talks with Arab and Israeli leaders.
   In Jerusalem, police detained 27 Israeli students from the
Bezalel art school after their parade for the Jewish holiday of
Purim turned into a protest against the Israeli handling of unrest
in the territories.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin defended Israel's policy of using
blows to subdue Arab protesters, saying that of several thousand
soldiers serving in the occupied territories, only 2 percent to 3
percent had commited excesses, the Itim news agency reported.
   As a matter of policy, the army does not release exact figures
on troop deployment.
   In Ramallah, eight miles north of Jerusalem, soldiers fired at
least six tear gas canisters at Palestinian protesters who used
rocks and twisted metal to block a street outside government-run
Ramallah Hospital and hurled stones at a dozen soldiers.
   One smoking canister landed in the emergency room reception area
and a second in a hospital courtyard.
   Two doctors donned gas masks and others held onions to their
noses to counter the effects of the gas. About 30 coughing
patients, including old men with canes, used Arab headdresses to
cover their faces.
   ``Even the doctors couldn't breathe, so imagine the effects on
the patients inside, many of whom are seriously ill,'' said one
doctor, who declined to identify himself.
   Soldiers detained three youths outside the hospital, dragging
away one of them with a gash on his forehead and a blood-drenched
shoulder.
   The tear gas attack was the second on the hospital in two days.
On Tuesday, three soldiers burst into the hospital, fired tear gas
and struck two doctors with their rifles as they searched for
demonstrators, the hospital director said.
   An army spokesman denied soldiers entered the hospital or beat
doctors in Tuesday's incident.
   Palestinian protesters have used hospitals, schools and sacred
mosques as hideouts to elude arrest and as staging grounds for
anti-Israeli riots, according to Israeli officials and eyewitnesses.
   Also in Ramallah Wednesday, police briefly detained three
Italian legislators who chained themselves to electric poles
outside a refugee camp and distributed anti-occupation leaflets,
Israel radio said.
   In the Gaza Strip, Palestinian organizers permitted merchants to
open their stores for three hours a day following a three-month
commercial strike, an Arab reporter said.
   But the army forced the stores to remain closed, saying
storekeepers were being intimidated, and the army would only permit
them to resume business when they did it of their own free will. In
the past, soldiers repeatedly tried to force stores to open to
break the strike.
   On the diplomatic front, right-wing legislators said Jordan's
King Hussein had gone back on previous understandings with Israel
by insisting the Palestine Liberation Organization be involved in
peace talks.
   ``King Hussein says the PLO must be involved in the peace
process and he wants a full-scale international conference,'' Likud
legislator Dan Meridor, a close aide to Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir, told Israel television. ``If that's progress, I don't know
what going backward is.''
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres agreed the PLO should not be
included in talks.
   Shamir himself on Wednesday accused Jordan of siding with ``the
most extreme elements in the Arab world'' and said the ultimate
goal of all Arab leaders was to destroy Israel.
   He spoke to members of the Conference of Presidents of Major
American Jewish Organizations.
   The Haaretz daily reported that, in order to prevent excesses by
soldiers, the army decided troops should not serve in the occupied
territories for more than 1{ months at a time.
   The newspaper said the army believed frustration and anger built
up during more than two months of serving in the territories had
caused four soldiers photographed by CBS News to beat two bound
Arabs with stones last week.
   Shamir said he was considering further restrictions on media
access in the occupied territories, saying journalists have harmed
Israel. He did not say what steps he might take. Soldiers now are
authorized to temporarily close parts of the occupied territories
to reporters.
   Shamir also called on American Jewish leaders to quell any
criticism of Israel within their ranks, saying it was ``non-Jewish
to join an anti-Israeli front of non-Jewish people.''
</TEXT>
