<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0803,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Hints At Noriega-Bush Connection</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead and INSERTS grafs 5-9 with Bush response</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential hopeful Bob Dole
implied Wednesday there was a connection between Vice President
George Bush's tenure as head of the Central Intelligence Agency and
speculation that Panamanian strong man Manuel Antonio Noriega was
on the CIA payroll. That drew a sharp response from Bush.
   Dole appeared with a dancing pineapple before a crowd of about
300 at a windy, rain-threatened rally in downtown New Orleans.
   At least twice Dole implied that Bush, who was head of the CIA
from 1976-77, might have had some dealings with Noriega.
   ``There's some evidence (Noriega) was on the CIA payroll as far
back as 1966. That's all I know,'' Dole said. He would not discuss
what the evidence was or what he knew.
   Bush, campaigning in Baton Rouge, La., criticized Dole for
bringing up the subject.
   ``I find it amazing that a United States senator will talk about
CIA matters. I took an oath of office to protect sources and
methods of intelligence and I would never discuss anything I was
doing at the CIA that would affect the national security,'' Bush
said.
   ``There has been one charge after another in this campaign and I
have just decided not to respond to Mr. Dole's charges.''
   However, Bush pointed to Noriega's recent indictment on federal
drug charges.
   ``I would point out that it's the Reagan-Bush administration
under which Mr. Noriega is being indicted in Florida for drugs.''
   Dole has grown increasingly critical of Bush in the final days
before the Super Tuesday round of caucuses and primaries in which
the vice president has a comfortable lead.
   ``I need to convince a lot of people in the next few days
there's only one candidate tough enough to do the job, and that
candidate's Bob Dole,'' Dole said.
   Dole said if elected he would force his desire for a line-item
veto into the courts.
   ``When the appropriations bill comes down, I'd line-item veto a
few things ... and send it back to Congress. Then we'd have a
constitutional question,'' Dole said, which would throw the issue
into the courts.
   If Congress won't approve a balanced budget amendment, Dole said
he would go to the American people and call a constitutional
convention to get one.
   Dole also pledged to support American interests in the Panama
Canal Zone after the year 2000, when the United States is supposed
to turn over control of the canal to the central American country.
   ``I sure am glad I voted against the Panama Canal treaty. That
vote looks better every day,'' he said.
</TEXT>
