<DOCNO> AP880302-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 2121EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DrugConference 1stLd-Writethru a0749 03-02 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Conference, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bureaucrats, Congress Hindering Drug War, Meese Contends</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 grafs after 12th graf pvs, bgng: ``Responding to
...'' to UPDATE with Customs Service to seize passports.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two big obstacles in the war on drugs are
low-level bureaucrats who don't have their hearts in the effort and
an overbearing Congress, two top administration officials contended
Wednesday
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III, one of four Cabinet officials
appearing on a nine-member administration panel at the White House
Conference on a Drug-Free America, asserted there is no problem of
leadership at the top.
   He called for more state and local financial assistance, less
congressional meddling and more determination by federal employees
to get with the programs outlined by their superiors.
   Responding to written questions submitted by some of the
estimated 2,000 people attending the conference, Meese said there
is no need for a federal drug czar to coordinate the battle.
   ``I thik this idea has been so discredited there is nobody that
really believes in that any more,'' he said. ``What has happened is
there is a drug czar in the United States, and that is the
president of the United States.''
   Meese acknowledged that with several different agencies involved
``you're going to have differences of opinion,'' but he said there
are mechanisms for resolving interagency disputes and that he is
``not worried about the organizational aspects.''
   However, he continued: ``I am extremely concerned about the
fragmentation that goes on in Congress, the fact that we have 32
different committees in the Congress with cognizance over the drug
problem so that too many of the leaders who are seated on the stage
here are spending their time testifying in front of congressional
committees instead of leading the forces that ought to be out in
the field working on the drug problem.''
   William von Raab, commissioner of the U.S. Customs Service, said
too many bureaucrats lack enthusiasm for fighting the drug war.
   ``I have been flat out told by many bureaucrats that just
because the president is supporting an effort it doesn't mean that
money goes with it,'' he said. ``We don't need a bunch of
bureaucrats that will deal with this war on drugs the way they
dealt with the war in Vietnam. We need heart in this effort ....''
   ``There are still too many people who work for us _ in my
organization as well _ who still have their noses too deeply buried
in their old books,'' the Customs chief said. ``These are the
conscientious objectors, the shirkers and the fourth columnists in
this war.''
   Meese associated himself with those remarks, but neither he nor
von Raab identified the people they were talking about.
   Responding to another question, Meese discounted any implication
that he does not favor continued federal financing for federal drug
treatment programs. But he said state and local officials need to
do more.
   Von Raab said that starting March 15, the Customs Service will
begin taking the passports of Americans who try to re-enter the
country with drugs. The passports are to be seized as evidence of a
crime and forwarded to the State Department, said Customs Service
spokesman Edward Kittredge.
   Among the other administration participants at the
congressionally ordered conference was Education Secretary William
Bennett, who embraced the long-simmering idea of making more use of
U.S. military forces to interdict the flow of drugs into the United
States.
   ``As the greatest military and economic power in the world, we
can do more to prevent criminals in foreign nations from growing or
processing illegal drugs,'' Bennett said.
   ``It is to be hoped we can do this in collaboration with foreign
governments, but if need be we must consider doing this by
ourselves,'' he said. ``And we should consider broader use of
military force against both the production and shipment of drugs.''
   Congress has considered legislation since 1983 to authorize
military intervention against drug shipments. The measure has
passed the House in one form or another on three occasions, but has
never passed the Senate.
   The latest congressional action on the issue called for the
General Accounting Office to study the impact on military readiness
of having the Defense Department play a lead role in the anti-drug
effort.
   During Wednesday's session, New York Mayor Edward I. Koch was
rebuffed when he attempted to ask a question about the role of the
military in the drug war from the floor rather than submit it in
writing as others were required to do.
   ``What I saw was a lot of back-scratching,'' Koch said later of
the preceedings. ``It is incredible ... that they would stifle
debate and not allow questions from the floor. It is a disservice
to the mission.''
   But Koch, who said he was speaking for the U.S. Conference of
Mayors, told reporters he liked what he heard from Bennett and von
Raab _ especially the idea of using military forces against foreign
drug dealers.
   ``We'll take care of the communists later,'' he said. ``They're
not now seeking to invade the United States. It's the drug
dealers.''
</TEXT>
