<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0850 03-02 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0850,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Works Out With Red Sox, Campaigns in Florida</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS grafs 5-6 with Dukakis anti-Gephardt commercial; ADDS
8 grafs with Hawaii endorsements</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINTER HAVEN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
fulfilled a boyhood ambition Wednesday as he detoured from the
beaten political campaign trail to make a pilgrimage to the Boston
Red Sox spring training camp.
   He didn't forget politics, also making a speech at a Florida
high school, celebrating his victory in Tuesday's non-binding
Vermont primary and crowing in Miami that ``we must be coming on
strong folks'' when told that Republican candidate George Bush had
criticized him in another Southern state.
   Bush, in Mississippi, said Dukakis wanted to reduce the number
of Navy battleships, which Bush called a ``dumb idea.''
   ``We'll have a strong, well-equipped Navy, but we're not going
to spend $36 billion on two super carrier task forces,'' Dukakis
said.
   The Massachusetts governor began airing a new television
commercial attacking Rep. Richard Gephardt and mocking Gephardt's
populist slogan, ``It's your fight too.''
   The advertisement says Gephardt is taking campaign contributions
from ``big establishment power brokers'' and adds: ``Kinda makes
you wonder, is Dick Gephardt fighting your fight or theirs?''
   In Winter Haven, unlike ordinary tourists, the governor even got
a turn in the big league batting cage, although he had little to
show for it.
   The one-time freshman catcher on the Brookline, Mass., High
School squad donned Red Sox jersey No. 1 and took 10 swings against
a batting practice pitcher. He fouled off three balls, popped one
into the batting cage, hit five grounders and whiffed once.
   ``I want you to work on your swing,'' advised outfielder Dwight
Evans.
   ``At least I made contact,'' said the 54-year-old governor. He
acknowledged to reporters, ``I'm a little rusty, as you can see.''
   The self-described ``long-suffering'' Red Sox fan said, ``It's a
great thrill to be here. I've never been to spring training. It's
something all Boston kids want to do.''
   ``I'm very optimistic about the campaign and the Red Sox,'' he
said. ``If we could both win our World Series, that would be a
(great) 1988.''
   Dukakis is doing well in many polls heading into Tuesday's round
of 20 primaries and caucuses, primarily in the South, but he said
the Red Sox, like himself, should ``just keep working and don't pay
any attention to the polls.''
   Outside a high school in Apopka, Fla., Dukakis said, ``We're
going to do well across the South'' with a campaign emphasizing
``jobs, good health care, the environment _ things that people care
about in the South and all over the country.''
   Referring to rival Albert Gore Jr., the Tennessee senator who
has geared his campaign to the South, Dukakis said, ``If you put
all of your eggs in one regional basket ... it becomes a lot more
crucial that you do exceedingly well.''
   He got an enthusiastic welcome at an assembly of Apopka High
School's 460-member senior class, but there were a few groans when
Dukakis defended his stands against aid to the Contras and the
Strategic Defense Initiative.
   When Dukakis asked, ``Is it going to be Star Wars or housing for
the homeless, is it going to be MX missiles or housing for the
homeless?'' some of the teen-agers replied, ``Star Wars, MX
missiles.''
   Nearly one-fifth of Apopka's students are in a Marine ROTC
program and several seniors wore their dress blues.
   Dukakis also got a campaign boost in the Super Tuesday state of
Hawaii, where Gov. John Waihee has thrown the support of the
state's Democratic Party leadership behind him.
   Waihee had maintained an uncommitted stance until now.
   ``I think the game is on the line Tuesday. We can stand on the
sidelines and watch, or we can get into the game,'' Waihee told a
news conference Wednesday in Honolulu.
   The announcement came with Dukakis listening in from Miami,
Fla., on a telephone conference call.
   ``I'm sitting here glowing,'' Dukakis said. He called Waihee ``a
man who has shown great wisdom in his choice of presidential
candidates.''
   Waihee said the Dukakis endorsement has the backing of Hawaii's
Sens. Daniel Inouye and Spark Matsunaga and Rep. Daniel Akaka, Lt.
Gov. Ben Cayetano and other Democratic leaders.
   Hawaii's Super Tuesday precinct elections will include a
presidential preference vote that will be binding on at least 20 of
Hawaii's 28 delegates to the Democratic Party National Convention.
   Before the Dukakis endorsement, party leaders said they had
expected Jesse Jackson to gain a plurality in Hawaii's precinct
elections, with Dukakis and ``uncommitted'' splitting most of the
balance.
</TEXT>
