<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 2ndLd-Writethru a0936 03-02 0898</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0936,0922</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham Lawyer Suggests Alleged Threat Was `Political Matter'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 18th graf, `Johnson and ...' to CORRECT spelling of
liaison and ADD that Carlson was a former aide.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senator complained Wednesday that Gov.
Evan Mecham sent an ``inappropriate'' letter proclaiming his
innocence to every member of the Arizona Senate, which is sitting
as judge and jury at his impeachment trial.
   An irate Sen. Jesus ``Chuy'' Higuera arose at the close of the
third day of the first-term Republican's impeachment trial and held
up the letter.
   ``I hope Governor Mecham understands the oath we have taken,''
said Higuera, urging other senators not to read the document. ``I
hope Mr. Mecham would understand it's inappropriate to try to
communicate with us.''
   The five-page document was a copy of Mecham's statement from a
Saturday news conference during which the governor pleaded his case
and claimed it was unfair to try him on impeachment charges before
a criminal case can be resolved.
   A cover memo on the governor's official stationery accompanied
each copy.
   Mecham, 63, was impeached by the House on charges of concealing
a $350,000 campaign loan, borrowing $80,000 in state funds for his
auto dealership and trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged
death threat against a former aide.
   He also also faces a March 22 trial March on charges of
concealing the loan and a May 17 recall election.
   One of Mecham's lawyers, Tom Crowe, told The Associated Press he
considered the governor's sending the letter appropriate.
   ``It's a political proceeding,'' said Crowe. ``The senators have
received communications from many people pro and con. I don't see
why the governor should be any different.''
   Some senators who had voted to delay the impeachment trial said
they had received notes from Mecham thanking them for their support.
   In recent weeks, senators have asked that Mecham stop making
phone calls to their offices during the impeachment proceedings.
They said they consider the calls inappropriate and did not talk
the governor, who is suspended from office.
   On Tuesday, a flap arose when it appeared that Mecham had tried
to contact a witness, but the governor later said the phone call
was placed by mistake.
   During testimony earlier in the day, an attorney for Mecham
suggested that the alleged death threat to a grand jury witness was
``a political matter,'' not a crime.
   Mecham's former security chief, testifying for a second day,
said he considered the incident a potential felony and told Mecham
a crime could be involved.
   ``The criminal nature of it was primary in my mind,'' said
Department of Public Safety Lt. Charles ``Beau'' Johnson. ``I did
not really think of it in the political sense.''
   ``Didn't you also believe this could be a political matter?''
defense attorney Fred Craft asked.
   ``I don't recall that that crossed my mind,'' Johnson said.
   Johnson and another former member of the governor's security
detail have testified they were told that Mecham's aide, Lee
Watkins, threatened in November that the governor's former
legislative liaison, Donna Carlson, might ``go on a long boat
ride'' if she didn't stop testifying before a grand jury
investigating Mecham.
   Mecham is accused of instructing the head of the DPS not to
cooperate in the attorney general's probe. Watkins has denied
threatening Ms. Carlson, and he has not been charged.
   Mecham, who stayed away from the trial for a third day, has said
he didn't know all the details of the incident, contended that he
didn't know a potential felony was involved and blamed his security
officers for not fully informing him.
   ``I told him it was a felony to tamper with a witness,'' Johnson
said. ``I didn't say the words `death threat.' But I said
`tampering with a witness.' I have no doubts about that ... I was
not hiding anything from the governor.''
   He also said he thought the matter was ``being taken too
lightly'' by the governor and his staff.
   ``When you took it to Fred Craft did he take it seriously?''
Craft asked, referring to himself. Craft was formerly Mecham's
lobbyist in Washington.
   ``Yes,'' said Johnson. ``But I think the focus of your concern
was embarrassment to the governor.''
   Craft's participation as defense attorney as well as a principal
in the disputed events raised protests from some senators.
   Republican Majority Leader Robert Usdane accused Craft of
misleading senators about his role when they agreed to let him join
the defense. His participation as a lawyer bars him from being
called by either side as a witness, although some senators believe
they could call Craft to testify.
   Earlier, the trial's presiding officer, Arizona Chief Justice
Frank X. Gordon, said he would not allow the defense to introduce
an affidavit intended to discredit a key witness by alleging he had
an affair with an employee in 1982.
   The prospective witness, DPS Director Ralph Milstead, has said
the allegations are ``ridiculous.''
   ``I don't think it's necessary to go into old past history about
someone's past sexual liaison, and he denies it,'' said Gordon.
``It has no value to prove anything material to these issues.''
   A two-thirds vote of the Senate would be required to convict
Mecham on any count and remove him from office. The Senate could,
by another two-thirds vote, then bar Mecham from holding any state
office again.
</TEXT>
