<2ND_LINE>BC-Speeches-Republicans, Adv 06-2 Takes,0918</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from basic speeches
delivered recently by candidates for the 1988 Republican
presidential nomination:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>GEORGE BUSH</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   I think the American people are going to be looking for
leadership.
   You know my background _ combat pilot, serving in the United
States Congress, meeting a payroll, building a business, ambassador
to China, ambassador to the United Nations, running the CIA at a
tough time and head of the (Republican) party, and seven years
standing shoulder to shoulder as vice president with a president
for whom I have great respect. ...
   The presidency is different. It's not like Congress. It's not
business. It's not like anything else when that cable comes in, a
plane's been hit, or an American ship's been shot at or you have to
punish a Marxist or a terrorist dictator like Gadhafi, or have to
take bold action to save American citizens' lives at risk in a tiny
Caribbean country. It's different. ...
   I think the president took the proper steps (when he learned
about the Iran-Contra affair). ...
   Covert action should not be run by the NSC (National Security
Council). It should be run by the CIA. ... I am worried about the
erosion of presidential power. ... Mistakes were made, but we must
move ahead now. ...
   Let's try to hold the highest possible standards (of ethics). It
is an honorable profession, public life. ... I want men and women
of excellence to come and serve, not to profit. ...
   I think that I would be the best for getting this (budget)
deficit down, with a four-year freeze that allows for the growth
and inflation, that will hold the line on taxes but doesn't freeze
in bad programs. ...
   I want to keep the United States strong, offering the hope of
peace and freedom. ... When people go into that (voting) booth,
they're going to be saying, who has the values that we believe in,
who has the breadth of experience, the ability to get people to
work together, and who has the integrity that we trust. ...
   The question is what do we do in the future? ... I believe that
I have had more real life experience than anyone else running
against me, and I am proud to have stood with this president
through thick and through thin, through good times and bad times,
without cutting and running when the going got tough.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>BOB DOLE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   I come from a small farming town. I was born and raised in the
values that come from deep roots, deep faith and an abiding love of
country. Russell, Kan., may be a long way off from Atlanta on the
map, but we share a lot of the same values.
   We know the importance of family, of neighbors helping neighbor,
of sticking together in good times and bad. ... I learned ... that
if you worked hard and really believed, you could overcome
hardships and build a better tomorrow. And if your country called _
in war or peace _ you served. ...
   That's how I've always tried to live my life. And that's the
kind of president our country will need to lead us into the 21st
century.
   Values and leadership _ that's what this crucial election is all
about. And, this year ... the South will play a key role in
choosing the man who will sit across the table from Mr. Gorbachev.
...
   The people ... must look at the record and decide which
candidate has demonstrated the strength it takes to stand tough, to
make the hard choices, to forge a consensus that will lead this
nation forward.
   Which candidate's leadership got President Reagan's tax cut
passed.
   Whose leadership stopped the liberals from repealing those tax
cuts.
   Whose leadership put together the plan which saved Social
Security from bankruptcy.
   Whose leadership produced a majority of votes in the Senate for
aid to the Nicaraguan freedom fighters.
   Whose leadership lined up the votes to keep the president's
Strategic Defense Initiative alive.
   And whose leadership produced the 1985 farm bill to save the
family farm.
   Bob Dole led each one of the battles in the U.S. Senate. And we
won. No other candidate in this race can match that record. No one.
   That's the true test of leadership. Not how many jobs we've had,
but what you've done in the jobs you've held. And that speaks
volumes for what you'll do as president.
   There's no instant, magic formula to make the deficit vanish.
But, with the right leadership, we can start solving the problem.
   There's no miracle cure to make freedom safe in a dangerous
world. But the right leadership can do it.
   There's no quick fix to make America competitive again, an
opportunity society where all our people can rise as high as their
God-given talents will take them. But leadership can make it happen.
   There's no easy way out of the plague of drug abuse, the decline
in values and education, the high cost of health care and so many
other urgent problems. But they can be solved.
   These are all tough challenges. It's going to take tough,
dedicated, understanding leadership to overcome them. ... I believe
that I can deliver the kind of leadership we need.
</TEXT>
