<DOCNO> AP880302-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Speeches-Republicans Adv06-1stAdd   03-02 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Speeches-Republicans, Adv 06-1st Add,0841</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHN: we need.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>JACK KEMP</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   No public policy decision we make in the next 10 years ... will
be as important as the decisions we make about defending and
nurturing and strengthening the bedrock of Western values _ our
families and our children.
   There is no better school, no better engine of economic growth
or job training, savings and investment than the traditional
family. There is no greater moral teacher, disciplinarian, help for
the weak, protector of the young, or builder of character than the
family.
   Our Democratic friends urge us to look to government as mother
and father, but they have it exactly backwards. ...
   I believe that America needs a rebirth of respect and compassion
for the value and the dignity and the sanctity of each and every
child and every human life. ...
   I have pledged that, as president, I will help lead America to
its highest standards of educational excellence _ not by expanding
budgets or new government programs, but through reforms that stress
the ABCs of education:
   A _ restoring accountability by granting parents greater
oversight and greater choice. ... B _ renewing stronger emphasis on
a basic core curriculum of English, science, math, history and
computer and vocational skills and expecting superior levels of
achievement to be met. C _ building and developing character. ...
   We've put forth a three-part plan to stop the spread of AIDS:
First, routine testing to help identify those infected; second,
confidential sharing of this information by public health
authorities with those in danger of infection; and, third, common
sense education that teaches right and wrong about the sexual
behavior that spreads AIDS.
   We must do everything we can to find a cure. We must treat AIDS
victims with compassion and give them care. But we must also give
the American people confidence that we have a plan and that we will
stop AIDS, now, not later. ...
   Our liberal friends tell us that we need ... activist judges.
Well, I agree. We need activist judges who actively support the
Constitution.
   We live in a democracy and it is the right and the
responsibility of the people and their representatives to decide
fundamental questions of public policy _ it is not, and must never
be the right and responsibility of judicial elites to appropriate
that right and responsibility to themselves.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PAT ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   If we are to recapture the greatness of America we must go back
to our fundamental faith in God. And when we train our children ...
it is absolutely crucial that we teach them the moral values of our
society. Little children must once again be allowed to pray in the
schools of America.
   When our ancestors came to these shores ... there was one thing
that was uppermost in the minds of the people. They believed in
individual self-reliance. ... When they went across these plains
... when they made an empire out of a wilderness ... when they
fought disease and battled enemies, when they endured privation,
hunger and starvation, they relied on their own initiative under
God.
   And if we are going to be strong we must recognize that we as a
people can do it ourselves. Government doesn't give us our freedom.
Government can't take our freedom away from us. It is a gift of God
given every one of us. ...
   We have built in this nation with 200 years of labor a
magnificent industrial base. But over the last few years of this
decade we have seen our industries slowly crumbling, some of our
basic industries going overseas to other nations. ...
   Recently I was in one of the Southern states and I learned of
1,000 factories that have closed. I learned of 300,000 people who
lost their jobs. And they told me about them, and they said: Are
you aware that imports to this country of the particular product
they were mentioning, textiles, from mainland China have risen from
230 million yards to 1.8 billion yards. ... Are you aware, they
told me, that from January of 1986 until November of 1987 that
imports of textiles from the Soviet Union had risen by 7,000
percent. ...
   If the communist countries want to help their workers, that's
fine. ... But I think the time has come in America when we no
longer are going to allow our basic industries to be destroyed and
our people put out of work in order to enhance the standard of
living of communist China and communist Russia. ...
   Recently, the Congress of the United States refused to vote
military aid to assist the freedom fighters of the Contras in
Nicaragua. I do not think it is in the best interest of the United
States of America to permit the Soviet Union to establish a land
base in the North American continent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
