<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Prices Fall on Rumored OPEC Discounting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices have reversed their
recent course, tumbling amid rumors that OPEC oil was being sold at
a discount.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Tuesday, crude oil for April
delivery fell 29 cents to settle at $15.72 per 42-gallon barrel.
The contract had gained 23 cents on Monday.
   Among refined products sold on the exchange, wholesale heating
oil for April delivery slipped 1.04 cents to 43.47 cents per gallon
Tuesday. Wholesale gasoline fell .93 cent to 45.29 cents per gallon.
   Prices came under pressure as rumors circulated that some Saudi
Arabian oil was being sold below the prices set by the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries, said Richard Redoglio, a trader
with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Price-cutting by the influential Saudis could signal a wider
price war, many analysts believe.
   Traders also sold oil because they believe there is too much
crude available, which also could depress prices, Redoglio said.
</TEXT>
