<DOCNO> AP880302-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Stevens Bjt   03-02 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stevens, Bjt,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Point-Pepperell Bids For J.P. Stevens; Management Revises Its
Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL MENEZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Stevens & Co., months ago a rumored
takeover target, now finds itself fielding three rival offers from
a management-led group, industry competitor West Point-Pepperell
Inc. and an undisclosed suitor.
   West Point-Pepperell said Tuesday it had offered to pay $56 a
share for Stevens, or about $867 million, in a negotiated buyout.
   The textile company actually had delivered its offer to Stevens
late Monday.
   On Tuesday, the J.P. Stevens management group led by Chairman
Whitney Stevens said it was increasing its own outstanding
leveraged buyout offer to $55 a share in cash and securities, or
about $850 million.
   Stevens also disclosed it had received a third, unidentified
offer.
   Stevens stock jumped $6.25 a share to $54.50 Tuesday on the New
York Stock Exchange. West Point-Pepperell was unchanged at $30.50 a
share.
   The management group offered to pay $40 in cash and $15 in
securities for each of Stevens' 15.5 million common shares
outstanding in a leveraged buyout.
   The group, led by the fifth generation member of the family that
founded Stevens in 1813, initially offered on Feb. 8 to pay a total
of $43 a share in cash and securities, or about $666.5 million.
   West Point said its $56 a share cash offer was not conditioned
on the availability of financing and indicated it was considering
the sale of certain Stevens assets to avoid antitrust concerns.
   Stevens indicated in a news release that its outside directors
were reviewing the revised management proposal and had authorized
the company's financial advisers to study the two outside proposals.
   Jim Franklin, a spokesman for Stevens, declined to comment
beyond the news release.
   A number of industry experts had predicted higher offers would
emerge following the management group's initial offer, which widely
was viewed as too low.
   Stevens is one of the nation's biggest textile producers,
concentrating on home fashion textiles such as sheets, towels and
carpets under the brand names Ralph Lauren, Laura Ashley and Pierre
Cardin. The company also makes automotive products and industrial
fabrics.
   West Point, based in West Point, Ga., also is a major household
fabrics maker, producing brands such a Arrow, Martex, Lady
Pepperell, Burberry's and Cabin Crafts.
   Joseph L. Lanier Jr., chairman of West Point-Pepperell, said an
acquisition of Stevens would be a natural step in his company's
shift toward consumer goods and away from commodity textiles, which
have lower profit margins and suffer from intense foreign
competition.
   West Point-Pepperell acquired Cluett-Peabody & Co. in 1986 as
part of the strategy.
   Stevens undertook a similar strategy beginning in 1984, moving
out of apparel fabrics and shifting its manufacturing to home
textiles such as sheets and towels. The success of that effort is
one factor that made Stevens an attractive takeover target.
   ``That's one of the great strengths of J.P. Stevens,'' Lanier
said in an interview. ``It's playing to our strength as we see it.''
   During the quarter ended Jan. 30, Stevens posted an after-tax
profit of $12.9 million, up from $11.9 million a year earlier.
Sales rose to $381.48 million from $361.67 million a year earlier.
   In the fiscal year ended Oct. 31, Stevens earned $56 million on
sales of $1.6 billion. This compared with a profit of $53.7 million
on revenue of $1.68 billion in 1986.
   West Point-Pepperell reported a profit of $25.5 million on
revenue of $480.9 million for the fiscal first quarter, which ended
Dec. 26. That was up from $20.9 million in profit and $422.7
million in revenue during a year earlier.
   Stevens said the securities portion of the management group's
offer would include $10 in market value of junior subordinated
debentures and $5 market value of preferred stock paying a dividend
in cash or additional shares.
</TEXT>
