<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Supercomputers Bjt   03-02 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supercomputers, Bjt,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Companies Unveil New Supercomputer Models As Competition
Heats Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apollo Computer Inc. got a key jump on its
competitors by developing a $70,000 desktop ``personal
supercomputer'' the company says is faster than anything else in
the market, industry analysts said.
   Two other companies also announced new supercomputers Tuesday,
marking what promises to be a period of fierce competition among
makers of sophisticated supercomputers used by scientists and
engineers.
   ``This seems to be the year for the so-called `personal
supercomputer,''' said Gary P. Smaby, who follows the industry for
Piper, Jaffray & Hopwood in Minneapolis. ``I think it's going to be
an interesting horse race.''
   Apollo said it was producing a workstation for scientists and
engineers with supercomputer power that outperforms anything in its
price range of $69,900 to $130,000.
   Analysts said the Domain Series 10000 returns the Chelmsford,
Mass.-based company to the forefront of the highly competitive
field of small, powerful workstations that combine extremely rapid
``number cruching'' with three-dimensional graphics.
   ``We think that this definitely positions them as the
performance leader to beat in the new graphics supercomputing
market,'' said David Burdick, an analyst with Dataquest Inc. of San
Jose, Calif.
   ``For a company that has been stuck in the Saragasso Sea in the
past couple of years, it is very siginificant'' said Donald Bellomy
of International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass. ``They had been
the industry leaders in every aspect and had fallen behind in every
aspect.''
   Ardent Computer Corp., a Sunnyvale, Calif.-based start-up,
announced its first product Tuesday, a graphics supercomputer in
about the same price and performance range as Apollo's.
   Convex Computer Corp. of Richardson, Texas, aiming at a pricier
segment of the market, unveiled a more powerful new line of
mini-supercomputers it hopes will cut into Cray Research Inc.'s
domination of that market.
   Another recent start-up, Stellar Computer Inc. of Newton, Mass.,
is expected to announce a similar graphics supercomputer in two
weeks, and analysts anticipate a half-dozen more to follow.
   ``Scientists and engineers are making pretty interesting use of
these computers,'' Smaby said. ``The question is how big a market
is there for a $100,000 single-user computer.''
   ``They're all vying for market share leadership in one niche or
another and not all of them are going to come out with gold
medals,'' he said.
   Apollo, which pioneered workstations in 1980, said at a Boston
news conference that the new model speeds up complex numerical
computations and its four-processor model allows several different
programs to run simultaneously.
   Ardent said its graphics supercomputer would range in price from
$79,000 for a one-processor model to $150,000 for a four-processor
model that will be available later this year.
   Ardent, founded in 1985, is run by two prominent figures in the
computer industry: Allen H. Michels, the president and chief
executive, who previously founded Convergent Technologies, and C.
Gordon Bell, the vice president of research, engineering and
development, who did pioneering work in a 23-year career at Digital
Equipment Corp.
   But analysts agree Apollo's 50,000 workstations and 1,800
software packages already on the market give it a competitive
advantage. The company said it will begin selling the models in the
third quarter this year and announce improved graphics system for
the workstation later this year.
   Convex Computer introduced a line of six mini-supercomputers
that range in power up to the level of conventional supercomputers.
In San Francisco, Convex said it invented a new kind of parallel
processing for its bigger models that keeps processors from being
idle by allocating work among them efficiently.
   Convex's new computers range in price from $275,000 to $1.3
million and are up to 10 times as powerful as its current models.
Convex claimed the most powerful model, the C240, is faster than
Cray Research Inc.'s X-MP 14, which costs $5.5 million.
</TEXT>
