<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GAF Bjt   03-02 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GAF, Bjt,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heyman Group Sweetens GAF Buyout Offer; Shareholders To Decide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GAF Corp. shareholders will have the chance
to vote on a sweetened $1.4 billion leveraged buyout offer from a
group led by Chairman Samuel J. Heyman, but may get competing
offers to consider.
   GAF's board of directors agreed Tuesday to submit the offer to
shareholders ``without endorsement,'' after the group increased its
bid from a previous $1.35 billion cash and securities package.
   The company also instructed its financial adviser to seek out
other potential purchasers, and left itself the option of accepting
any competing, superior offer.
   The Heyman group on Tuesday proposed to pay $46 in cash and
junior securities with a face value of $6.50 for each of GAF's 27.7
million outstanding common shares.
   In December, the Heyman group offered $1.35 billion, or $40 in
cash and $8.50 in securities per share.
   That offer was a downward revision from its initial $2.3 billion
offer, made in September, of $64 in cash and $2.50 face value in
debt securities. Heyman revised the initial proposal due to rising
interest rates stemming from unsettled conditions in the market for
high-yield ``junk bonds'' following the October stock market crash.
   In order for shareholders to vote on the latest buyout offer,
they first first vote on an amendment to the company charter. The
amendment would allow shareholders to act in place of the board in
considering a merger offer, as the Heyman-led proposal has been
presented.
   A special committee of the board of directors had rejected the
initial $64-a-share proposal as inadequate. GAF said it had decided
to let stockholders decide based on the favorable opinion of the
offer by Salomon Brothers Inc., the committee's financial adviser.
   The committee also instructed Salomon to solicit other possible
purchasers, GAF said. The committee said that if it receives an
``economically superior alternative proposal'' for GAF, it could
cancel its agreement with the buyout group.
   ``We think the price is a fare and full price,'' Heyman said.
``It's seven times the price of the stock only four years ago.''
   GAF also said it had reached tentative settlements of lawsuits
brought in connection with the buyout offer.
   GAF stock rose 25 cents to $50.25 a share Tuesday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Heyman, who wrested control of GAF in 1983 after a bitter proxy
fight to oust former Chairman Jesse Werner, has said that taking
GAF private would give the company more leeway to pursue
acquisitions without having to worry about short-term shareholder
value.
   Since taking over GAF, Heyman has led the company on
unsuccessful but profitable attempted takeovers of Union Carbide
Corp. and Borg-Warner Corp.
   Heyman owns 2.8 million shares of GAF, or about 10 percent of
its outstanding stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
