<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mexico-LuxuryClub     03-02 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Luxury Club,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peso Slide Puts Luxury Club Dues at $30 a Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years ago a Monterrey company
promoting membership at a new Pacific coast resort hotel offered a
special deal: ``Buy now and your 10-year lease will be renewed at
the same price in 1988.''
   But inflation and the devaluation of the peso since then have
made the deal even more special than anyone anticipated: the
average 70,000 peso price for the leases in 1978, worth the
equivalent of $3,182 back then, now equals just $30.
   Hotel clients in this northern industrial city are complaining
that the company is balking at renewing the time-sharing leases at
the cheaper price.
   They estimate that about 1,000 people throughout Mexico paid an
average of 70,000 pesos in 1978 to spend one week each year at the
luxury hotel Club Maeva in Manzanillo in the Pacific coastal state
of Colima.
   The hotel is run by Casolar, the tourism division of the huge
Monterrey-based Alfa conglomerate.
   Alfa fell into a severe economic crisis along with the rest of
Mexico in 1982 and has seen the value of Mexico's currency plunge
from 22 pesos to the dollar in 1978 to 2,350 to the dollar now.
   The peso devaluation has made the 70,000-peso fee equal to $30,
about the price of dinner for two in a nice restaurant. But clients
here say they took the gamble a decade ago when they invested in a
hotel complex that was under construction.
   ``We know it's very little money now. But, remember, nothing was
built at the time. It was an enormous risk,'' said Concepcion
Rodriguez de Salazar, who sold herself one of the contracts 10
years ago when she worked as a Casolar sales representative.
   Her son, Monterrey lawyer Jorge Salazar, says Casolar now wants
to charge 10 million pesos _ $4,255 _ to renew the contract.
Salazar is handling the complaints for about 60 hotel clients here.
   ``The company didn't have any idea that things were going to
turn out as they did. But the people that bought there didn't
expect the company to decide whether or not it was going to
comply,'' Salazar said.
   Martha Barrios of Casolar said on Monday and Tuesday that
officials involved in the contract dispute were in meetings or out
of town and not available for comment.
   Salazar said in a telephone interview late Monday that his
clients want him to negotiate with Casolar, but he has been unable
to locate company officials.
   ``These people had to sacrifice to pay the fee 10 years ago, but
they thought they'd get 20 years of vacations,'' Salazar said.
   He said the peso-dollar equivalent had nothing to do with the
written contract. The renewal offer was in the contract as well as
the company's advertising, he said.
   ``We don't earn dollars or spend dollars or do business in
dollars,'' he said. ``We still have faith in what a contract says.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0158EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-KaiserTech     03-02 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-KaiserTech,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KaiserTech Sues Chairman To Recover Stock Trading Profit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KaiserTech Ltd. has taken the unusual step of
suing its own chairman of the board, in an attempt to recover
profits made from his short-term dealings in the aluminum company's
stock.
   The suit filed Tuesday against Alan E. Clore came a day after
the reclusive British investor agreed to sell his 27 percent stake
in KaiserTech to Texas oilman Charles Hurwitz, a move that appeared
to irritate KaiserTech officials and signaled management turbulence
at the Oakland, Calif.-based company.
   Clore acquired his position at KaiserTech after a lengthy
takeover struggle last year. Hurwitz's intentions toward KaiserTech
remain unclear.
   Asked if it was considered unusual that a company would sue its
own chairman, KaiserTech spokesman Robert W. Irelan said: ``It's
the first time we've done it.''
   KaiserTech stated that its suit filed in a Manhattan federal
court resulted from Clore's disclosures in a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing on Monday about his sale of stock to a
Hurwitz-controlled company, Los Angeles-based Maxxam Group Inc.
   KaiserTech contended the SEC disclosures showed Clore and his
affiliates made about $4 million in undisclosed profits via
so-called ``short-swing trading'' _ trading done within a six-month
period _ of KaiserTech stock.
   Under federal securities law, a company or its stockholders are
entitled to recover such profits from a director or officer who
engages in short-swing trading.
   Clore, who usually resides in Switzerland, could not be reached
for comment on the lawsuit, which was part of a rapid series of
events concerning KaiserTech stock.
   In Los Angeles, the investment firm Jefferies & Co. said it was
selling 1.39 million shares of KaiserTech stock to Maxxam for
$16.68 million or $12 a share.
   Combined with the 6.2 million shares acquired from Clore, plus
an option to buy his 8.2 million convertible preferred KaiserTech
shares, acquisition of Jefferies' stake would give Maxxam about
one-third of KaiserTech's approximately 45 million shares
outstanding.
   But Wall Street's reaction indicated skepticism about a possible
takeover move. In composite New York Stock Exchange trading,
KaiserTech fell 12{ cents a share to $11.75, after rising $1.12{ in
the previous session.
   KaiserTech had stated Monday it would have preferred that Clore
had sold his stock to a broader range of investors, reflecting
concern about what Maxxam intended to do with its stake. Maxxam
officials said it was premature to speculate on whether the comapny
would attempt to acquire more KaiserTech shares.
   Clore's maneuvering to sell his KaiserTech shares came against a
background of heavy pressure on him to cut losses suffered in the
October stock market crash.
   If Clore hadn't found a buyer by a Monday deadline, he could
have faced default on loans he had obtained by using Kaiser stock
as collateral. After the stock plunged in October, lenders wanted
repayment.
   His sale of stock came as the company was rebounding from six
straight years of losses. Kaiser has sold its chemical, oil and gas
businesses, slashed debt and concentrated on its core aluminum
business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0211EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CigaretteSuit     03-02 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cigarette Suit,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memo: Tobacco Industry Worked To `Create Doubt' About Cigarette
Risks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lorillard Inc. tobacco company sought to
downplay discounts that its insurance company affiliate was
considering offering to non-smokers several years ago, according to
evidence in a lawsuit against three cigarette makers.
   The contention was made Tuesday as a federal jury heard
testimony and read documents that allegedly show the tobacco
industry sought to suppress information on the health dangers of
smoking.
   The suit filed by Antonio Cipollone of Lakehurst, claims
Lorillard, Philip Morris Co. and Liggett Group Inc., are liable for
the lung cancer death of his wife Rose, a 40-year smoker.
   Cipollone alleges the companies failed to do enough research on
cigarettes, did not reveal what they did know, failed to warn the
public of health dangers and did not put a safer product on the
market.
   One document released Tuesday, dated March 3, 1980, was written
by Chicago-based CNA Insurance Co. officials and discussed a
recommendation for non-smoker discounts, according to Marc Z.
Edell, Cipollone's attorney.
   At the time, CNA was owned by Loew's Theatres Inc., which also
owned Lorillard. Loew's has since sold the tobacco company.
   ``It is recognized that the introduction of non-smokers discount
could prove embarrassing'' to Loew's and Lorillard, the memo
stated. In order to minimize the potential for embarrassment, it
suggested that CNA and Lorillard jointly prepare a carefully
constructed statement saying the discount ``in no way supports or
refutes the contention that smoking causes health defects.''
   ``CNA should further refrain from advertising or otherwise
promoting non-smoker discounts,'' it continued.
   The issue also was discussed in a letter dated Nov. 5, 1979,
from Lorillard senior vice president and general counsel, Arthur J.
Stevens, to CNA Chairman Edward J. Noha.
   Stevens wrote that when the cigarette manufacturing trade group,
the Tobacco Insitute, heard of Allstate Insurance Co.'s plan to
offer a non-smoker discount the institute sought help from CNA ``in
an effort to perhaps dissuade Allstate from that course of action
by supplying background data.''
   Lorillard spokesman Chuck Wall said Lorillard and the institute
did nothing improper but merely were trying to counteract
anti-cigarette propaganda.
   According to another document released Tuesday, a Tobacco
Institute official stated in 1972 that the industry's defense
against cigarette critics included ``creating doubt about the
health charge without actually denying it.''
   The internal memorandum describes the ``three major fronts'' _
litigation, politics and public opinion _ where the tobacco
companies had fought to defend itself.
   The ``brilliantly conceived and executed'' strategy, used in all
three areas, helped ``win important battles,'' said the memo.
   However, ``it is only fair to say that it is not _ nor was it
intended to be _ a vehicle for victory,'' said the May 1, 1972 memo
from Fred Panzer to Horace R. Kornegay, president of the Tobacco
Institute.
   Wall identified Panzer as an institute vice president.
   The document says the industry had followed a ``holding
strategy, consisting of:
   _creating doubt about the health charge without actually denying
it;
   _advocating the public's right to smoke, without actually urging
them to take up the practice;
   _encouraging objective scientific research as the only way to
resolve the question of health hazard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
