<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GM-Fiero Bjt   03-02 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Fiero, Bjt,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pontiac To End Fiero Production, Shutter Plant This Summer</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT2 of March 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s plastic-body,
mid-engine Pontiac Fiero and the workers who make it have become
the first victims of slumping popularity for sporty two-seaters.
   Michael Losh, Pontiac's general manager, said Tuesday GM will
stop making the Fiero after the 1988 model and will close
indefinitely the single Fiero plant here sometime this summer,
idling 1,109 workers.
   ``The whole market's dead,'' said industry analyst Chris
Cedergren of J.D. Power and Associates, blaming high insurance
rates for a 30 percent drop in overall two-seater sales during 1987.
   The slump has not spared Japanese automakers, who report slow
sales of cars such as the sporty Toyota MR2 and the Mazda RX7, or
Europeans, whose victims include four-cylinder Porsches.
   In addition to flagging sales, Fiero had suffered problems that
included frequent engine fires, which prompted GM to recall the
entire 1984 mode production run late last year. But Losh and
Cedergren suggested the market killed the Fiero.
   ``We have seen a switch away from the high volumes of people who
were willing to buy two-seat cars with limited luggage capacity,''
Losh said. ``We led the world into this (market) segment and we may
lead a piece of the world out of it.''
   Fiero sales peaked at 101,720 cars in 1984 and fell to 47,156 in
1987. Sales for the 1988 model year, which began Oct. 1, are less
than 10,000, 41 below the same point in the 1987 model year.
   But before it died, Losh said, the Fiero helped create a new,
performance-oriented image for Pontiac. He refused to speculate on
whether the Fiero plant might reopen to build a new Pontiac or GM
product.
   Union and city officials said they were surprised by the Fiero
decision despite the car's poor sales. When the Fiero is gone, no
Pontiacs will be built in Pontiac.
   UAW Local 653 President Harold Cox said his plant was one of the
first at GM to accept Japanese-style team organization of workers
under a contract that allowed the previously closed plant to reopen
in 1983 to make the Fiero.
   ``We're going to continue to try to persuade General Motors to
try to put something in there,'' Cox said. ``It's a slap in our
face that they rewarded us this way.''
   GM already has closed a foundry, another car assembly plant, a
heavy-duty truck plant and a bus plant in Pontiac and had cut
production at the Fiero plant several times, putting more than
1,200 other Fiero workers on layoff.
   Dealers said they also were surprised by the announcement and
some expressed disappointment.
   ``We don't have anything else in my opinion that would fit in
that category,'' said Buzz Sawyers, owner of Sawyers Pontiac in
Lansing. ``It's like a cheap Corvette.''
   Pontiac spokesman Reginald Harris said GM will make sure parts
are available for the Fiero into the future.
   GM's contract with the United Auto Workers union forbids
permanent plant closings that were not announced before the
contract was signed last fall, but permits laying off workers if
sales slow.
   The Fiero plant is the third GM has decided to idle since then.
The first, in Framingham, Mass., will return to production in May.
The second, in Kansas City, Mo., will shut down April 15, idling
1,600 workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
