<HEAD>Texas Oilmen Undertake Tender Offer for Gypsum Producer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp., a leading producer of building
materials, has urged shareholders to resist a $1.9 billion tender
offer from a partnership led by two Texas oilmen.
   The $42-a-share offer for about 21.5 million shares of USG stock
was unveiled Tuesday by Desert Partners LP, which is headed by Jack
E. Brown and Cyril Wagner Jr.
   Desert Partners already owns about 9.9 percent or 5.08 million
of USG's approximately 50.8 million shares outstanding.
   After the tender offer was announced, USG issued a statement
asking shareholders to hold onto their stock until the board had a
chance to act on the matter.
   The company has stated repeatedly that it wants to remain
independent. Lasat week USG rejected the partnership's lateset
takeover proposal, also valued at $42 a share.
   In a separate filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Desert Partners said it would seek to elect six
directors to USG's 15-member board at the company's annual meeting
in May.
   Desert Partners said Wells Fargo Bank had pledged $500 million
in financing for the offer and would attempt to arrange $525
million more in financing from other banks.
   Wall Street analysts have speculated that Wagner and Brown
aren't interested in acquiring USG but want to boost the value of
their stake, purchased last year for about $44.30 a share for an
earlier takeover attempt that fizzled.
   In recent weeks USG stock had been trading around $28 a share,
but the price started rising when rumors surfaced late last month
that Wagner and Brown would make another run at the company.
   USG rose $2.75 to $40.12{ on the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday.
   Based in Chicago, USG is a leading producer of gypsum and
building materials, with about 100 plants nationwide.
</TEXT>
