<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NorthwestAirlines     03-02 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Airlines,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Attendants Urged To Begin Legal Slowdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Teamsters union is urging Northwest
Airlines' 6,700 flight attendants to use whatever measures they can
to slow their performance without breaking the law or company rules.
   ``At this time we want to keep the company confused and very
busy,'' said a recorded message that answered a union telephone
Tuesday.
   The recording urged tactics that included filing paperwork on
each piece of broken equipment at each stop during a flight and
slowing down everyday procedures the flight attendants have learned
to shorten.
   ``What they're doing is not against regulations,'' said Jeff
Musto, a spokesman for Teamsters Local 2747. ``It's just following
the rules.''
   The flight attendants, who are working without a contract,
threatened to strike at 11:01 p.m. last Friday, but no job actions
have been taken against the company, said William Wren, a Northwest
spokesman.
   Talks broke off at dawn Saturday, and no further negotiations
were scheduled, spokesmen for both sides said.
   Terry Erskine, Northwest's vice president for law and labor
relations, said Monday an unusually high number of flight
attendants called in sick over the weekend. But he attributed the
absences to attendants' fears they would be stranded by a strike,
not to orders from the union.
   ``We're winding down operations here today, letting the dust
settle for the time being,'' said Musto. ``There's still a
possibility of a strike and we're free to strike at any time,''
Musto added.
   The main stumbling block to a new contract is a company proposal
to delay the promotion of B-scale workers to the higher-paid
A-scale bracket, Musto and Wren said.
   All Northwest flight attendants were paid under one scale before
a 1982 contract created the B-scale, Musto said, while all
employees hired since then have started as B-scale employees at
rates of pay lower than the old system.
   The 1982 contract called for B-scale employees to jump to
A-scale levels in their sixth year of employment, but the current
company proposal would extend that wait until the ninth year of
employment, Musto said.
   Such an extension would mean a loss off $16,776 over the three
years for the average B-scale flight attendant, Musto said.
</TEXT>
