<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   03-02 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housing Sales, Factory Orders Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New info, editing throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   January new-home sales hit the lowest point since the last
recession and factory orders fell for the first time in four
months, the government said today in reports suggesting the economy
weakened after the October stock crash.
   The Commerce Department said sales of new homes plunged 9
percent in January to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 535,000
units, the third straight monthly decline that left sales 26
percent below year-earlier levels.
   The report reflected a significant downturn in the housing
industry, the area of the economy believed hardest hit since the
collapse in stock prices five months ago. Analysts believe many
homebuyers stopped looking after the collapse, fearing economic
uncertainty in months ahead.
   Housing is often the economic sector that declines first before
the start of a new recession. Despite the weakness, however, many
economists remain hopeful that recent declines in mortgage rates
will spur a sales rebound.
   The Commerce Department also said orders to U.S. factories fell
0.6 percent in January, the first decline since a 1.4 percent drop
last August and another possible sign of post-crash economic
weakness.
   But some analysts said the report was misleading because it
reflected a huge swing in aircraft orders, which helped push
factory orders up 2 percent in December.
   Discounting the aircraft element, factory orders would have
risen 0.8 percent in January, reflecting a higher demand for
American manufactured goods caused partly by the weaker dollar,
which makes them more affordable abroad.
   The reports today appeared to have no dampening effect on
domestic financial markets, where early stock and bond prices rose.
   On Tuesday, the markets wandered aimlessly after the release of
other economic statistics that gave no clear signals.
   The Commerce Department said its chief barometer of future
economic activity fell in January, although an upward revision of
December's figure eased fears that the nation was headed for a
recession.
   The department also said construction spending fell an
unexpected 2.9 percent in January, the biggest decline in 10
months, evidence of weakness in all sectors of the building
industry.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 1.16 points
to 2,070.46, slipping from the post-Oct. 19 market crash high it
had reached on Monday. It was equally quiet in the credit markets,
with the yield on the Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond edging up
to 8.35 percent from Monday's 8.34 percent.
   The dollar was narrowly mixed in foreign exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
