<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1106EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Britain-Frogs     03-02 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Frogs,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers In Muddle Over Tax Status of Frogs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Is a frog livestock? People wouldn't leap to that
conclusion, a farmer-lawmaker suggested Wednesday, arguing that
frog farmers need tax protection.
   Farms for frogs should be exempt from local property taxes, just
as are any premises used for any ``livestock,'' Conservative
Michael Colvin told a House of Commons committee studying a local
finance bill.
   According to the bill, livestock is defined as ``any mammal or
bird kept for the production of food or wool, or for the purpose of
its use in the farming of land.'' All other farm premises are also
exempt from the taxes.
   Fine, but where does the frog, an amphibian, fit in? asked
Colvin, who said his acquaintance with a frog farmer prompted him
to raise the point.
   ``The definition of livestock is most unclear. Times have
changed in agriculture,'' he said, suggesting that the bill
substitute ``creatures'' for ``livestock.''
   ``It would be a sad day if any government started imposing a tax
on frogs,'' said Colvin.
   Local Government Minister Michael Howard pointed out that words
aren't everything under law. After all, he said, ``snails are
covered by the exemption for fish farms.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
