<1ST_LINE>r f BC-KodakBonds     03-02 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Kodak Bonds,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Sells $1.1 Billion Of Notes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. says it has sold $1.1
billion of 10-year notes, making it the largest investment-grade
corporate debt issue in the United States.
   The previous record was held by Occidental Petroleum Co., which
issued $1 billion worth of investment-grade debentures two years
ago, according to Morgan Stanley & Co., Kodak's underwriters.
   Kodak said it had planned to sell $750 million worth of bonds,
but demand was so great the amount was increased to the record
level.
   The 10-year bonds were priced at par and carry an interest rate
of 9.125 percent. The issue will be used to either retire about $1
billion of short-term loans or help finance the company's recent
$5.1 billion acquisition of Sterling Drug Inc., Kodak said.
   Kodak has traditionally tried to stay out of the credit markets.
   In 1981 the company had borrowed less than $100 million, but its
current debt totals $3.3 billion, with much of that increase coming
in the last two years.
</TEXT>
