<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama Assets, 1st Add,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: constitutional president.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Delvalle fired military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega last
Thursday but the defense chief ignored the order and rallied his
allies in the National Assembly against the president. On Friday,
the assembly voted to oust Delvalle and installed Education
Minister Manuel Solis Palma in his place.
   Noriega has been indicted on drug smuggling charges by two
Florida grand juries and has been under heavy diplomatic, economic
and political pressure by the Reagan administration to step aside
and open the way for civilian-led constitutional rule.
   Among the banks listed by Rogers which would be affected by the
order are Marine Midland NA, Irving Trust Co., Bankers Trust Co.
and the Republic National Bank. He said all have headquarters in
New York.
   ``Every dime we can find is in those banks,'' Rogers said. He
added that any bank which ignores the order could be liable for
whatever payments it makes to the current Panamanian government.
   The coalition of opposition leaders believes that the Panamanian
government is facing a grave cash flow problem and is extremely
vulnerable to economic pressure from the United States.
   Unlike other countries, Panama cannot cover its cash shortages
by printing new money because the dollar is the national currency.
   Sosa said international opposition to the new government was
evident earlier this week when, he claimed, only eight ambassadors
showed up for a State of the Union address. From the Western
Hemisphere, he said, only Cuba and Nicaragua attended.
</TEXT>
