<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Panama-BankSuit     03-02 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Bank Suit,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Seeks to Block Noriega Access to Panama Funds Here</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the ousted president of Panama, Eric
Arturo Delvalle, sued in federal court today to block a New York
bank from turning over millions of dollars to military strongman
Gen. Manuel Noriega.
   A federal judge issued a temporary restraining order, blocking
the Republic National Bank of New York from transferring an
estimated $10 million.
   A hearing on the matter is slated for Monday before U.S.
District Judge Lloyd F. McMahon.
   The lawsuit, filed at federal court in Manhattan by lawyers from
Washington, seeks to establish title to the funds held in the
Republic National Bank account and ``to prevent their transfer into
the hands of a military dictatorship ... which has attempted to
seize power and overthrow the lawful authorities of the Republic of
Panama,'' according to court papers.
   Noriega, the military leader of Panama, was indicted on drug
charges by two U.S. grand juries in Florida Feb. 4.
   Devalle sought to dismiss Noriega Feb. 25, but was himself
ousted by the National Assembly the next day and has gone into
hiding.
   On Tuesday, Devalle froze all Panamanian assets outside the
country, and the United States, which still recognizes Devalle as
the legitimate head of Panama, has supported the action.
</TEXT>
