<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1233EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-FarmersDebt 1stLdWritethru f0024 03-02 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farmers Debt, 1st Ld Writethru, f0024,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Federal Rules Would Help Nation's Troubled Farmers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede New York</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with spokesman's comments; also moving on
general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of farmers wrestling with massive
debts or being forced out of business may get another chance under
new loan rules being drawn up by the federal Farmers Home
Administration, the Agriculture Department agency said today.
   Joe O'Neill, an FmHA spokesman, said the new rules probably will
be ready by June. In many cases, over-burdened borrowers could have
much of their debt written off, trimmed back to reflect their
assets in hopes of keeping them in business.
   However, O'Neill said he had no estimate of how much debt the
FmHA might write off under the new rules.
   ``There's just no way of knowing,'' O'Neill said. ``It'll be
each individual case all the way through.''
   At the end of last fiscal year on Sept. 30, he said, 261,291
FmHA borrowers owed the agency about $26 billion. Of that, 127,671
were delinquent, owing $6.6 billion, including principal and
interest.
   New rules governing how the agency deals with farmers who owe it
money could help prevent 100,000 farms from going under, The New
York Times reported today, quoting FmHA officials in Washington.
Agency officials also said thousands of farmers who went bankrupt
over the past 10 years could find themselves back in operation.
   The new rules are a result of a bill passed by Congress in
December calling on the FmHA, an agency that serves as a ``lender
of last resort'' for the nation's farmers, to go easier on farmers
who are behind in their payments.
   The new law requires the agency to do whatever possible to
restructure loans in order to keep FmHA borrowers in business.
   ``Our attitude is going to be different,'' said FmHA
Administrator Vance L. Clark. ``We want to make the new act work,
and we're going to have a lot of room to maneuver to restructure
these loans.''
   Lynn Hayes, an attorney with the Farmers Legal Action Group in
St. Paul, Minn., said, ``I'm thrilled they are apparently taking
this legislation seriously and are trying to make it work.''
   The new regulations would enable debt-burdened farmers to stay
in business through a number of loan restructuring options.
According to agency officials, farmers would be offered the
opportunity to pay off loans at a lower rate of interest over a
longer period of time.
   As a last resort, the agency could write off debts in excess of
a borrower's assets, O'Neill said. For example, if a farmer's
assets were $150,000 and debts totaled $500,000, the write-off
could be as much as $350,000 if the FmHA determined the farmer
could handle the remainder by staying in business.
   ``It makes sense, then, to keep that person in business and
write off the difference between what they owe and their assets _
if the government stands a chance of retrieving more by keeping
that farmer going,'' O'Neill said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880302-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1401EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankDeregulation 2ndLd-Writethru f0044 03-02 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Deregulation, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0044,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Committee Tries To Resolve Dispute Over Banking Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 4 grafs new with stalemate continuing through morning;
picks up 5th graf pvs, Legislation sponsored; also running on
general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Senate Banking Committee failed
to unravel a tangled three-way dispute this morning that has
blocked legislation to repeal the Depression-era law separating
commercial banking and the securities industry.
   Committee members, after meeting more than two hours behind
closed doors on Tuesday, struck a tentative deal that balanced the
interests of banks, securities firms and insurance companies,
according to Senate aides who spoke on condition of anonymity. But
the agreement fell apart almost immediately.
   The compromise would have given bank holding companies more
securities powers, but restricted their ability to expand into
insurance, the aides said. However, it fell apart when senators on
opposite sides of the insurance issue realized they had a different
understanding of the agreement, the aides said.
   Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., the committee chairman, called
another negotiating session for later in the day. An aide said the
nature of the restriction on banks' ability to enter the insurance
business remained the sticking point in the talks.
   Legislation sponsored by Proxmire and Sen. Jake Garn of Utah,
the committee's senior Republican, would repeal the 1933
Glass-Steagall Act, which forbids commercial banks from
underwriting and selling most securities. It was passed in the wake
of the 1929 stock market crash to preserve the safety of the
banking system.
   Affiliates of bank holding companies would be allowed
immediately to begin underwriting mortgage-backed securities,
commercial paper, municipal revenue bonds and securities backed by
consumer loans.
   Power to underwrite corporate debt would be postponed until Jan.
1 and corporate stock underwriting by bank affiliates would begin
in 1990.
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the securities
subcommittee, was advocating more restrictive legislation that
would have required separate congressional votes in 1989, 1990 and
1991 before bank affiliates could underwrite corporate bonds,
stocks and mutual funds.
   The tentative compromise, according to the aides, would have
automatically phased in power over corporate bonds and mutual funds
and required a separate vote in the future only on stock
underwriting.
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, a Democrat from Connecticut, where
insurance companies are important employers, was pushing an
amendment that would prohibit state-chartered banks owned by
holding companies from further expansion into insurance.
   Opposition from banks to Dodd's amendment, if passed, could kill
the entire bill, aides said, but some senators were reluctant to
vote against the amendment for fear of retaliation from insurance
interests within their states.
   One version of the compromise on insurance, as described by the
aides, would have allowed a state to permit its banks to underwrite
insurance within the state even if the holding company that owned
the bank was headquartered out of state. However, banks would not
be allowed to locate in a state with permissive laws and then
``export'' insurance to other states.
   A second, more restrictive, version of the compromise would
require both the bank and its parent company to be located within a
state before state officials could allow the bank to underwrite
insurance.
   Proxmire and Garn opened the all-day session Tuesday with a plea
to fellow senators to ignore pressure from special interest
lobbyists.
   ``We are not here to merely broker a compromise between the
various providers of financial services,'' Proxmire said.
   Garn, looking at a hearing room packed with lobbyists, said,
``It's time to forget all of you and your special interests and
your greed.''
   The Proxmire-Garn bill has been endorsed by the heads of all the
relevant regulatory agencies and by President Reagan, but it faces
substantial hurdles even beyond the Senate committee before it can
be enacted.
   Reps. John Dingell, D-Mich., and Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I.,
who will have jurisdiction over the issue in the House, have
expressed considerable reluctance about broadening bank powers too
much.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
