<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GMFiring     03-02 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GM Firing,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Fires Several Workers For Accepting Gifts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: version running on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has fired several
employees and disciplined others for accepting gifts from a major
tooling supplier in the late 1970s and early 1980s, a trade
publication has reported.
   This week's edition of Metalworking News identified Lamb
Technicon Corp. of Warren as the subject of a GM investigation.
   GM disciplined employees who helped make decisions concerning
tooling purchases and who accepted gifts from Lamb Technicon,
Metalworking News said. Gifts included paid trips with Lamb
Technicon salesmen to resort areas or hotels.
   Darlene Sandlin, a spokeswoman for Lamb Technicon, confirmed the
company had been investigated by GM. She said the company issued
new guidelines on ethics in 1984.
   GM officials, citing a policy against discussing individual
personnel matters, refused comment.
   Technicon recently was selected as a major tooling supplier for
GM's Saturn Corp. car project in Tennessee.
</TEXT>
