<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1439EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-McDonnellPromotions     03-02 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-McDonnell Promotions,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New President Elected At McDonnell Douglas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald A. Johnston, a top executive of the
McDonnell Douglas Astronautics Co., was elected president of
McDonnell Douglas Corp. during a board of directors meeting
Wednesday, the company announced.
   Johnston replaces John F. McDonnell, who became chairman and
chief executive officer of the corporation Wednesday when the
retirement of Sanford N. McDonnell became effective.
   Sanford McDonnell, 65, announced his retirement earlier this
year.
   Johnston, 56, had been serving as vice president and general
manager of the astronautics facilities in Huntington Beach, Calif.
His promotion became effective immediately.
   Johnston, who joined Douglas Aircraft Co. in 1956 as an
associate engineer, became vice president and general manager of
strategic systems in 1986 and vice president and general manager of
the Huntington Beach facilities last year.
   Sanford McDonnell will continue on the board of directors.
</TEXT>
