<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1624EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RepublicBank-Deposits     03-02 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-RepublicBank-Deposits,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deposits Drop 8 Percent Amid Takeover Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Dallas lost more than 8 percent
of its deposits as customers withdrew $599 million in one week last
month amid speculation about the financial health of its parent
company, regulators said.
   The Dallas bank is the lead institution of First RepublicBank
Corp., whose officials said the situation subsequently appeared to
be stabilizing.
   The bank held average total deposits of $6.87 billion during the
seven-day period ended Feb. 24, down 8.7 percent from $7.47 billion
the previous week and down $1.5 billion from the period including
Dec. 31, 1987.
   Gerald Fronterhouse, chairman and chief executive of First
Republic, said the one-week outflow of deposits at the Dallas bank
was ``unusual,'' but added that the bank's funding situation
``appeared to be stabilizing.''
   During the week covered in the report by the Federal Reserve
Bank of Dallas, the bank holding company was the subject of
published reports that takeover or bailout negotiations were under
way, and that its lead institution had suffered deposit outflows.
   A 55-member team supervised by the Office of the Comptroller of
the Currency began auditing First RepublicBank, which lost $656.8
million in 1987 and finished the year with $3.92 billion worth of
problem assets. Bank officials later denied that the negotiations
were taking place.
   Fronterhouse said the Dallas bank's recent deposit loss
``reflects mainly the impact of earlier false rumors and extensive
adverse publicity.
   ``By the middle of last week, the sources of funds for the
Dallas bank and for the corporation as a whole appeared to be
stabilizing,'' Fronterhouse said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
