<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     03-02 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Stronger, Gold Varied</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar strengthened against most major
currencies Wednesday. Gold prices stagnated or rose slightly.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar firmed on two rumors:
that the U.S. administration would allow the dollar to rise if
American trade figures continue to improve and that the Soviet
Union was buying dollars.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound when the
state-run Bank of England sold an undetermined amount of pounds to
keep the currency below 3.0 West German marks as the mark fell
against the dollar.
   At the end of the day, one pound cost $1.7680, cheaper than
$1.7775 late Tuesday.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with late
Tuesday rates included: 1.6945 West German marks, up from 1.6855;
1.4005 Swiss francs, up from 1.3915; 5.7345 French francs, up from
5.7065; 1.9013 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8940; 1,247 Italian lire,
up from 1,244.35; 1.2558 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2570.
   Earlier in Tokyo the dollar closed at 128.47 Japanese yen, up
from 128.30 Tuesday. In London the dollar traded at 129.27 yen.
   Gold bullion was higher in London at $429.50 a troy ounce, up
from $428.70 late Tuesday. It was unchanged in Zurich at $429.50.
   Traders said gold prices appeared to be stabilizing in a range
of $425 to $433.
   Gold in Hong Kong traded at $433.96, up marginally from $433.80
Tuesday.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $6.24 a troy ounce, down
from $6.29.
</TEXT>
