<HEAD>Dun & Bradstreet Agrees to Buy Securities Research Firm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dun & Bradstreet Corp. said Wednesday it has
agreed to buy Interactive Data Corp., a Massachusetts-based
securities research firm owned by Chase Manhattan Corp., for $140
million in cash.
   The acquisition is expected to be completed by the end of March,
the announcement said.
   IDC, which is based in Lexington, Mass., is a leading provider
of historical securities information and related analytical
services. It posted revenue of $85 million in 1987.
   Chase Manhattan is the second largest U.S. banking company.
   IDC provides its customers, who include research analysts for
brokerage houses and pension and mutual fund managers, with
information on the performance of public companies and prices of
equity and fixed-income securities on a current and historical
basis.
   Dun & Bradstreet is a leading marketer of business information
and related services. It owns Moody's Investors Service, which
rates corporate and municipal obligation, and Nielsen Media
Research, which compiles telelvlsion ratings, as well as a number
of other financial services.
</TEXT>
