<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed lower Wednesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade after an attempt to rally the market
failed.
   C&D Commodities, a large investment fund, was a heavy buyer of
soybean meal and soybean oil futures but the action attracted
little buying interest among other traders, analysts said.
   ``The market didn't respond, so we started to sell off and the
thing snowballed late in the day,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``We ended up near or at the
day's lows across the board.''
   Wheat also came under pressure from the Agriculture Department's
revised auction program designed to lower surplus stocks.
   The USDA announced after the close it had sold 10 million
bushels of wheat, the amount it had expected to sell, on Tuesday.
Auctions also were scheduled for Wednesday and Friday, and three
more are set for next week.
   At the close, wheat was 2} cents to 4{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.06} a bushel; corn was 2 cents
to 3 cents lower with March at $2.01} a bushel; oats were \ cent to
1\ cents lower with March at $1.93{ a bushel; soybeans were 4{
cents to 5{ cents lower with March at $6.30{ a bushel.
