<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Shell-Bookout     03-02 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shell-Bookout,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bookout Retiring as Shell Oil President, CEO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John F. Bookout, who has served as president and
chief executive officer of Shell Oil Co. since 1976, announced
Wednesday he is retiring effective June 30.
   Frank H. Richardson, executive vice president of products, will
be nominated to the Shell Oil board of directors to succeed
Bookout, the company said.
   Shell is wholly owned by the Royal Dutch-Shell Group of
Companies, which is based in both London and the Hague, the
Netherlands.
   Bookout joined the Houston-based Shell Oil as a geologist in
Tulsa, Okla., in 1950. He was elected president of Shell Canada
Ltd. in 1970 and returned to Shell Oil in 1974 as executive vice
president of exploration and production.
   Shell said one of Bookout's principal achievements was putting
into place 10 years ago a strategic planning that served the
company well during the volatile conditions the oil industry has
experienced.
   Normal retirement for Shell's senior management is at 60, but
Bookout, 65, was given two formal extensions, Shell spokeswoman
Kitty Borah said.
   Bookout has not announced any future plans, she said. He was out
of town on business and could not be reached for comment.
   Shell also announced Wednesday that Charles W. Wilson will
replace Richardson as executive vice president of products
effective May 1. He previously was vice president of refining and
marketing.
   Richardson spent the first part of his Shell Oil career in the
exploration and production organization. He became vice president
of corporate planning in 1978, executive vice president of
administration in 1982 and assumed his present position in 1983.
   Wilson joined Shell Oil in 1963, becoming vice president of
production in 1964 then moved to Shell Western E&P Inc. as
president in 1987. He returned to Shell Oil in his present position
late last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
