<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 2026EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Sears     03-02 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sears,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sears Announces Overhaul of Merchandising Sector</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck & Co. said Wednesday it was
beginning a three-year overhaul of its flagship merchandise group
to make each segment of its retail business more competitive.
   The restructuring, which will trim an as-yet undertermined
number of people from the merchandise group's management, will make
Sears stores more responsive to customer needs and wants, officials
said.
   ``The apparel business will be run differently from the hardware
business,'' said spokesman Philo Holland. ``You need different
organizational structures to compete in different businesses.''
   Michael Bozic, chairman and chief executive officer of the
merchandising group, said in a statement that the restructuring
would reduce the number of management levels, making each segment
of Sears' merchandise business leaner and more independent.
   ``We are competing in many diverse businesses, each with its own
unique structure, and (we) have been essentially using one
organizational format to compete in all of these businesses,''
Bozic said.
   ``The changes we make will result in a company that is better
structured to maintain its position as America's premier retailer.''
   Officials said they had no estimate of the number of employees
to be affected or the cost savings involved, because they were only
beginning the restructuring procss.
   ``The ultimate size and structure will be determined by how we
choose to compete in the different businesses we are
restructuring,'' Holland said.
   He said the reduction in management personnel would be achieved
through attrition and a severance offer of two weeks' salary for
each year of service, up to a maximum of 52 weeks.
   Employees at least 50 years old who have been with the company
at least 10 years will also be offered early retirement benefits,
Holland said.
   The reorganization is widely seen as an attempt to revive
sluggish sales and profits within the merchandise group, which
accounts for nearly 60 percent of the company's revenues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
