<DOCNO> AP880302-0319 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 1748EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-02 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocoa Futures Continue To Slide On Surplus Production Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices set new life-of-contract lows for the
fourth consecutive day Wednesday on fears that the International
Cocoa Organization will be unable to control the effects of
steadily rising production.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures retreated; livestock
and meat were mixed; precious metals were slightly lower; energy
futures were mostly lower; and stock-index futures advanced.
   No news from the International Cocoa Organization's week-long
meeting in London was perceived as bad news on New York's Coffee,
Sugar & Cocoa Exchange, where prices for future delivery of cocoa
settled as much as $35 a ton below Tuesday's final prices.
   ``The market continues to try and absorb prospects for surplus
production,'' said Sandra Kaul, an analyst in New York for Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. ``It's falling pretty sharply.''
   Cocoa producer and consumer nations are meeting to discuss
withholding cocoa from the market to support prices, Ms. Kaul said.
   ICCO buffer-stock buying, a price-support mechanism that was
resumed in January after a six-month suspension, has already
exhausted the allocation of 250,000 metric tons for the 1987-88
marketing year, she said.
   World cocoa production has risen steadily since 1986 and is
expected to total more than 2 million metric tons this year.
   Cocoa settled $31 to $35 lower with the contract for delivery in
March at $1,563 a metric ton.
   Grain and soybean futures finished lower on the Chicago Board of
Trade after an attempt to rally the soybean market failed, analysts
said.
   Wheat came under additional pressure from the Agriculture
Department's revised auction program designed to lower surplus
stocks.
   The USDA announced after the close it had sold 10 million
bushels of wheat, the agency's targeted amount, on Tuesday.
Auctions also were scheduled for Wednesday and Friday, and three
more are set for next week.
   Wheat settled 3 cents to 4{ cents lower with March at $3.06{ a
bushel; corn was 1} cents to 2} cents lower with March at $2.02 a
bushel; oats were \ cent to 1\ cents lower with March at $1.93{ a
bushel; soybeans were 4\ cents to 5} cents lower with March at
$6.30{ a bushel.
   Live cattle futures settled higher while feeder cattle prices
moved lower in choppy trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle futures have traded within a narrow range for more than a
month.
   Hog futures finished slightly lower in light, technically based
trading. Frozen pork bellies advanced on expectations that discount
pricing at the wholesale level would encourage sales of pork
products.
   Live cattle were .17 cent to .38 cent higher with April at 72.12
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .45 cent lower with
March at 80.27 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent to .22 cent lower
with April at 43.25 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .23
cent to .67 cent higher with March at 52.27 cents a pound.
   Gold futures have encountered support at around $430 a troy
ounce for the April contract, which settled slightly above that
level on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 10 cents to 20 cents lower with April at $432.20 a
troy ounce; silver was .50 cent to 1 cent lower with March at
$6.216 a troy ounce.
   Oil futures prices finished mostly lower on the New York
Mercantile Exchange after struggling back from a sharp selloff
earlier in the day.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .12 cent lower to .13
cent higher with April at $15.67 a barrel; heating oil was .15 cent
lower to .46 cent higher with April at 43.93 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .05 cent to .39 cent lower with April at
44.90 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures settled slightly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index ended .70 point higher at 268.35. The
underlying spot index finished .75 point higher at 267.98.
</TEXT>
