<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Atari     03-02 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Atari,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atari Earnings Rise 57 Percent In Fourth Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atari Corp. on Wednesday said its
earnings rose 57 percent to $18.7 million in the fourth quarter of
1987 and credited part of the jump to its October acquisition of
the Federated Group Inc. chain of retail electronics stores.
   Other factors contributing to the increase included strengthened
computer sales in Europe and booming video game sales in the United
States, said Greg Pratt, company spokesman.
   The fourth-quarter figure represented 32 cents a share, on
revenue of $277 million. That compared with earnings of $11.9
million, or 22 cents per share, on revenue of $92.6 million in the
same 1986 period.
   Sales of televisions, stereos, microwave ovens and other
electronics equipment at Federated's 68 stores in California,
Arizona and Texas accounted for 47 percent of revenues, or $130.6
million.
   Profits for all of 1987 rose 76 percent to $44.1 million, or 76
cents per share, from $25 million, or 53 cents in 1986.
   Sales rose 91 percent, increasing to $493 million in 1987
compared to $258 million the previous year.
   ``Video games were obviously a hot category this year,'' said
Pratt. ``There were no teddy bears or laser guns to take those
dollars away. People went back to more traditional stuff and bought
video games.''
   Federated stores now acount for 25 percent of Atari Corp., one
of the world's largest manufacturers of personal computers and
video games.
</TEXT>
