<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HomeSales-Cities     03-02 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales-Cities,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Although Sales Down Overall, Regional Picture Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A Commerce Department report that showed a slide in January
new-home sales provided further evidence of a housing industry
slump following the stock market crash five months ago. Last week
the National Association of Realtors said sales of existing homes
in January fell for the third straight month.
   Nevertheless, sales vary widely around the country, reflecting
regional economies, interest rates and demand, random AP telephone
queries of Realtors suggested. Here is a brief description of
housing markets in six areas:
   Boston: Sales were stronger in the last three months of 1987
compared with a year earlier, and preliminary figures for early
this year suggest stability. Fixed-rate mortgage rates have fallen
slightly to about 9.75 percent, while prices are up more than 6
percent above year-earlier levels.
   Dallas: Sales fell more than 30 percent in the last quarter of
1987 from the year earlier level. Prices have risen in a range of 2
percent to 8 percent. Fixed mortgage rates vary between 9 percent
and 10 percent.
   Kansas City: Sales have fallen slightly but there is no
clear-cut trend. Mortgage rates have fallen from 10.5 percent to
about 9.5 percent and prices have risen nearly 10 percent from a
year earlier.
   Southern California: Sales have fallen about 3.3 percent from a
year earlier. Fixed rate mortgages are expected to fall to 9.5
percent from 9.75 percent. Prices have risen between 1 percent and
2 percent from a year earlier.
   New York-New Jersey: Sales have slowed, and recent drops in
mortgage rates to the 10 percent level are expected to stimulate
the market. Prices have remained about the same.
   Philadelphia: Sales have improved since the start of the year
and mortgage rates have declined slightly to about 9.5 percent.
Prices have remained about the same.
</TEXT>
