<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Scotus-UnionDues     03-02 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Union Dues,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rules For Unions In Dues Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An evenly divided Supreme Court ruled
Wednesday that an airlines may be forced to continue to collect
union dues from workers after its contract with employees has
expired.
   The justices, by a 4-4 vote, upheld rulings that forced Trans
World Airlines to continue the dues check-off after a strike by
flight attendants in 1986.
   Such splits automatically uphold lower court rulings but set no
national precedent. The TWA case carried little impact for most
employers, anyway, because it involved an interpretation of the
Railway Labor Act, which only applies to the airlines and railroad
industries.
   Most private industry employers' labor relations are subject to
the National Labor Relations Act.
   Nonetheless, Vicki Frankovich, president of the Independent
Federation of Flight Attendants, said, ``We are extremely pleased
with this result.''
   The ruling was not accompanied by any written opinion or by any
indication of how each individual justice voted.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who only recently joined the court,
did not participate in the case.
   TWA and the Independent Federation of Flight Attendants had a
three-year contract that expired July 31, 1984. Prolonged
negotiations followed but the union called a strike on March 7,
1986.
   The strike ended on May 17, 1986, when the flight attendants
offered to return to work. Only some 200 attendants had stayed out
for the entire strike.
   TWA hired 2,800 new attendants during the strike, and about
1,200 others either never joined the strike or returned to work
during it.
   The airline then cancelled the dues-checkoff provision of the
old contract, meaning that it no longer would collect union dues.
   But a federal judge, upheld by the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, ruled that the airline must honor the old contract's
provisions.
   The appeals court said the Railway Labor Act bars employers from
unilaterally cancelling union security and dues check-offs contract
provisions. Any such changes must be made in negotiations between
the employer and its workers, the appeals court said.
</TEXT>
